var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Saṃyuttanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Pañcakanipāta* **";
P_HTM[4]="*5. Sekhabalavaggo* **";
P_HTM[5]="*2. Dutiyapaṇṇāsakaṃ**Powers of a Trainee*";
P_HTM[6]="*1. Saṃkhittasuttaṃ**In Brief*";
P_HTM[7]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[8]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[10]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[11]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[12]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[13]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sekhabalāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[14]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[15]="*Saddhābalaṃ, hirībalaṃ, ottappabalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, paññābalaṃ—**The powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[16]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sekhabalāni.**These are the five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[17]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[18]="*‘saddhābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, hirībalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, ottappabalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, vīriyabalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, paññābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalenā’ti.**‘We will have the trainee’s powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.’*";
P_HTM[19]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[20]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[21]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[22]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[23]="*2. Vitthatasuttaṃ**In Detail*";
P_HTM[24]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sekhabalāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[25]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[26]="*Saddhābalaṃ, hirībalaṃ, ottappabalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, paññābalaṃ.**The powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[27]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhābalaṃ?**And what is the power of faith?*";
P_HTM[28]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[29]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[30]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhābalaṃ.**This is called the power of faith.*";
P_HTM[31]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, hirībalaṃ?**And what is the power of conscience?*";
P_HTM[32]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako hirīmā hoti, hirīyati kāyaduccaritena vacīduccaritena manoduccaritena, hirīyati pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samāpattiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple has a conscience. They’re conscientious about bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and conscientious about having any bad, unskillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[33]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, hirībalaṃ.**This is called the power of conscience.*";
P_HTM[34]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, ottappabalaṃ?**And what is the power of prudence?*";
P_HTM[35]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako ottappī hoti, ottappati kāyaduccaritena vacīduccaritena manoduccaritena, ottappati pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samāpattiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple is prudent. They’re prudent when it comes to bad conduct by way of body, speech, and mind, and prudent when it comes to acquiring any bad, unskillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[36]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ottappabalaṃ.**This is called the power of prudence.*";
P_HTM[37]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, vīriyabalaṃ?**And what is the power of energy?*";
P_HTM[38]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**It’s when a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[39]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vīriyabalaṃ.**This is called the power of energy.*";
P_HTM[40]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññābalaṃ?**And what is the power of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[41]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[42]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññābalaṃ.**This is called the power of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[43]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sekhabalāni.**These are the five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[44]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[45]="*‘saddhābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, hirībalena … ottappabalena … vīriyabalena … paññābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalenā’ti.**‘We will have the trainee’s powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.’*";
P_HTM[46]="*Evañhi kho, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[47]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[48]="*3. Dukkhasuttaṃ**Suffering*";
P_HTM[49]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ viharati savighātaṃ saupāyāsaṃ sapariḷāhaṃ, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā duggati pāṭikaṅkhā.**“Mendicants, when a mendicant has five qualities they live unhappily in the present life—with distress, anguish, and fever—and when the body breaks up, after death, they can expect a bad rebirth.*";
P_HTM[50]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[51]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu assaddho hoti, ahiriko hoti, anottappī hoti, kusīto hoti, duppañño hoti.**It’s when a mendicant is faithless, shameless, imprudent, lazy, and witless.*";
P_HTM[52]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu diṭṭheva dhamme dukkhaṃ viharati savighātaṃ saupāyāsaṃ sapariḷāhaṃ, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā duggati pāṭikaṅkhā.**When a mendicant has these five qualities they live unhappily in the present life—with distress, anguish, and fever—and when the body breaks up, after death, they can expect a bad rebirth.*";
P_HTM[53]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ viharati avighātaṃ anupāyāsaṃ apariḷāhaṃ, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugati pāṭikaṅkhā.**When a mendicant has five qualities they live happily in the present life—without distress, anguish, or fever—and when the body breaks up, after death, they can expect a good rebirth.*";
P_HTM[54]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[55]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddho hoti, hirīmā hoti, ottappī hoti, āraddhavīriyo hoti, paññavā hoti.**It’s when a mendicant is faithful, conscientious, prudent, energetic, and wise.*";
P_HTM[56]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu diṭṭheva dhamme sukhaṃ viharati avighātaṃ anupāyāsaṃ apariḷāhaṃ, kāyassa ca bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugati pāṭikaṅkhā”ti.**When a mendicant has these five qualities they live happily in the present life—without distress, anguish, or fever—and when the body breaks up, after death, they can expect a good rebirth.”*";
P_HTM[57]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[58]="*4. Yathābhatasuttaṃ**Cast Down*";
P_HTM[59]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is cast down to hell.*";
P_HTM[60]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[61]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu assaddho hoti, ahiriko hoti, anottappī hoti, kusīto hoti, duppañño hoti.**It’s when a mendicant is faithless, shameless, imprudent, lazy, and witless.*";
P_HTM[62]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ niraye.**A mendicant with these five qualities is cast down to hell.*";
P_HTM[63]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ sagge.**A mendicant with five qualities is raised up to heaven.*";
P_HTM[64]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[65]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddho hoti, hirīmā hoti, ottappī hoti, āraddhavīriyo hoti, paññavā hoti.**It’s when a mendicant is faithful, conscientious, prudent, energetic, and wise.*";
P_HTM[66]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu yathābhataṃ nikkhitto evaṃ sagge”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is raised up to heaven.”*";
P_HTM[67]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[68]="*5. Sikkhāsuttaṃ**Disrobing*";
P_HTM[69]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme pañca sahadhammikā vādānupātā gārayhā ṭhānā āgacchanti.**“Mendicants, any monk or nun who rejects the training and returns to a lesser life deserves rebuke and criticism on five legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[70]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[71]="*Saddhāpi nāma te nāhosi kusalesu dhammesu, hirīpi nāma te nāhosi kusalesu dhammesu, ottappampi nāma te nāhosi kusalesu dhammesu, vīriyampi nāma te nāhosi kusalesu dhammesu, paññāpi nāma te nāhosi kusalesu dhammesu.**‘You had no faith, conscience, prudence, energy, or wisdom regarding skillful qualities.’*";
P_HTM[72]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme ime pañca sahadhammikā vādānupātā gārayhā ṭhānā āgacchanti.**Any monk or nun who rejects the training and returns to a lesser life deserves rebuke and criticism on these five legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[73]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā sahāpi dukkhena sahāpi domanassena assumukho rudamāno paripuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carati, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme pañca sahadhammikā pāsaṃsā ṭhānā āgacchanti.**Any monk or nun who lives the full and pure spiritual life in pain and sadness, weeping, with tearful face, deserves praise on five legitimate grounds in the present life.*";
P_HTM[74]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[75]="*Saddhāpi nāma te ahosi kusalesu dhammesu, hirīpi nāma te ahosi kusalesu dhammesu, ottappampi nāma te ahosi kusalesu dhammesu, vīriyampi nāma te ahosi kusalesu dhammesu, paññāpi nāma te ahosi kusalesu dhammesu.**‘You had faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom regarding skillful qualities.’*";
P_HTM[76]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā sahāpi dukkhena sahāpi domanassena assumukho rudamāno paripuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carati, tassa diṭṭheva dhamme ime pañca sahadhammikā pāsaṃsā ṭhānā āgacchantī”ti.**Any monk or nun who lives the full and pure spiritual life in pain and sadness, weeping, with tearful face, deserves praise on these five legitimate grounds in the present life.”*";
P_HTM[77]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[78]="*6. Samāpattisuttaṃ**Becoming*";
P_HTM[79]="*“Na tāva, bhikkhave, akusalassa samāpatti hoti yāva saddhā paccupaṭṭhitā hoti kusalesu dhammesu.**“Mendicants, you don’t become unskillful as long as faith is established in skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[80]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, saddhā antarahitā hoti, assaddhiyaṃ pariyuṭṭhāya tiṭṭhati;**But when faith vanishes and faithlessness takes over,*";
P_HTM[81]="*atha akusalassa samāpatti hoti.**you become unskillful.*";
P_HTM[82]="*Na tāva, bhikkhave, akusalassa samāpatti hoti yāva hirī paccupaṭṭhitā hoti kusalesu dhammesu.**You don’t become unskillful as long as conscience … prudence … energy … wisdom is established in skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[83]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, hirī antarahitā hoti, ahirikaṃ pariyuṭṭhāya tiṭṭhati;* **";
P_HTM[84]="*atha akusalassa samāpatti hoti.* **";
P_HTM[85]="*Na tāva, bhikkhave, akusalassa samāpatti hoti yāva ottappaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu.* **";
P_HTM[86]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, ottappaṃ antarahitaṃ hoti, anottappaṃ pariyuṭṭhāya tiṭṭhati;* **";
P_HTM[87]="*atha akusalassa samāpatti hoti.* **";
P_HTM[88]="*Na tāva, bhikkhave, akusalassa samāpatti hoti yāva vīriyaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu.* **";
P_HTM[89]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, vīriyaṃ antarahitaṃ hoti, kosajjaṃ pariyuṭṭhāya tiṭṭhati;* **";
P_HTM[90]="*atha akusalassa samāpatti hoti.* **";
P_HTM[91]="*Na tāva, bhikkhave, akusalassa samāpatti hoti yāva paññā paccupaṭṭhitā hoti kusalesu dhammesu.* **";
P_HTM[92]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, paññā antarahitā hoti, duppaññā pariyuṭṭhāya tiṭṭhati;**But when wisdom vanishes and witlessness takes over,*";
P_HTM[93]="*atha akusalassa samāpatti hotī”ti.**you become unskillful.”*";
P_HTM[94]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[95]="*7. Kāmasuttaṃ**Sensual Pleasures*";
P_HTM[96]="*“Yebhuyyena, bhikkhave, sattā kāmesu laḷitā.**“Mendicants, sentient beings are mostly charmed by sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[97]="*Asitabyābhaṅgiṃ, bhikkhave, kulaputto ohāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito hoti, ‘saddhāpabbajito kulaputto’ti alaṃvacanāya.**When a gentleman has abandoned the scythe and flail and gone forth from the lay life to homelessness, they’re qualified to be called ‘a faithful renunciate from a good family’.*";
P_HTM[98]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[99]="*Labbhā, bhikkhave, yobbanena kāmā te ca kho yādisā vā tādisā vā.**Because a youth can get sensual pleasures of this kind or that.*";
P_HTM[100]="*Ye ca, bhikkhave, hīnā kāmā ye ca majjhimā kāmā ye ca paṇītā kāmā, sabbe kāmā ‘kāmā’tveva saṅkhaṃ gacchanti.**Now, all sensual pleasures are just reckoned as ‘sensual pleasures’, regardless of whether they’re inferior, average, or superior.*";
P_HTM[101]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, daharo kumāro mando uttānaseyyako dhātiyā pamādamanvāya kaṭṭhaṃ vā kaṭhalaṃ vā mukhe āhareyya.**Suppose there was a little baby boy who, because of his nurse’s negligence, puts a stick or stone in his mouth.*";
P_HTM[102]="*Tamenaṃ dhāti sīghaṃ sīghaṃ manasi kareyya;**The nurse would very quickly notice*";
P_HTM[103]="*sīghaṃ sīghaṃ manasi karitvā sīghaṃ sīghaṃ āhareyya.**and try to take it out.*";
P_HTM[104]="*No ce sakkuṇeyya sīghaṃ sīghaṃ āharituṃ, vāmena hatthena sīsaṃ pariggahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena vaṅkaṅguliṃ karitvā salohitampi āhareyya.**If that didn’t work, she’d cradle his head with her left hand, and take it out using a hooked finger of her right hand, even if it drew blood.*";
P_HTM[105]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[106]="*‘Atthesā, bhikkhave, kumārassa vihesā;**I admit she’d know, ‘This will distress the child,*";
P_HTM[107]="*nesā natthī’ti vadāmi.**there’s no denying.’*";
P_HTM[108]="*Karaṇīyañca kho etaṃ, bhikkhave, dhātiyā atthakāmāya hitesiniyā anukampikāya, anukampaṃ upādāya.**Still, it should be done by a nurse who wants what’s best for him, out of kindness and compassion.*";
P_HTM[109]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, so kumāro vuddho hoti alaṃpañño, anapekkhā dāni, bhikkhave, dhāti tasmiṃ kumāre hoti:**And when the boy has grown up and has enough sense, his nurse would not worry about him, thinking:*";
P_HTM[110]="*‘attagutto dāni kumāro nālaṃ pamādāyā’ti.**‘The boy can look after himself. He won’t be negligent.’*";
P_HTM[111]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, yāvakīvañca bhikkhuno saddhāya akataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, hiriyā akataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, ottappena akataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, vīriyena akataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, paññāya akataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, anurakkhitabbo tāva me so, bhikkhave, bhikkhu hoti.**In the same way, I still need to look after a mendicant who hasn’t finished developing faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom regarding skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[112]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno saddhāya kataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, hiriyā kataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, ottappena kataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, vīriyena kataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, paññāya kataṃ hoti kusalesu dhammesu, anapekkho dānāhaṃ, bhikkhave, tasmiṃ bhikkhusmiṃ homi:**But when a mendicant has finished developing faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom regarding skillful qualities, I need not be concerned, thinking:*";
P_HTM[113]="*‘attagutto dāni bhikkhu nālaṃ pamādāyā’”ti.**‘They can look after themselves. They won’t be negligent.’”*";
P_HTM[114]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[115]="*8. Cavanasuttaṃ**Failure*";
P_HTM[116]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[117]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[118]="*Assaddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A mendicant who is faithless …*";
P_HTM[119]="*Ahiriko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**shameless …*";
P_HTM[120]="*Anottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**imprudent …*";
P_HTM[121]="*Kusīto, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**lazy …*";
P_HTM[122]="*Duppañño, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**witless fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[123]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A mendicant with these five qualities fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[124]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A mendicant with five qualities doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[125]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[126]="*Saddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A mendicant who is faithful …*";
P_HTM[127]="*Hirīmā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**conscientious …*";
P_HTM[128]="*Ottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**prudent …*";
P_HTM[129]="*Āraddhavīriyo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**energetic …*";
P_HTM[130]="*Paññavā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**wise doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[131]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.”*";
P_HTM[132]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[133]="*9. Paṭhamaagāravasuttaṃ**Disrespect (1st)*";
P_HTM[134]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**“Mendicants, a disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with five qualities fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[135]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[136]="*Assaddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A disrespectful and irreverent mendicant who is faithless …*";
P_HTM[137]="*Ahiriko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**shameless …*";
P_HTM[138]="*Anottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**imprudent …*";
P_HTM[139]="*Kusīto, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**lazy …*";
P_HTM[140]="*Duppañño, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**witless fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[141]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu agāravo appatisso cavati, nappatiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with these five qualities fails, and doesn’t establish themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[142]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A respectful and reverent mendicant with five qualities doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[143]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[144]="*Saddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**A respectful and reverent mendicant who is faithful …*";
P_HTM[145]="*Hirīmā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**conscientious …*";
P_HTM[146]="*Ottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**prudent …*";
P_HTM[147]="*Āraddhavīriyo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**energetic …*";
P_HTM[148]="*Paññavā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme.**wise doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.*";
P_HTM[149]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso na cavati, patiṭṭhāti saddhamme”ti.**A respectful and reverent mendicant with these five qualities doesn’t fail, and establishes themselves in the true teaching.”*";
P_HTM[150]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[151]="*10. Dutiyaagāravasuttaṃ**Disrespect (2nd)*";
P_HTM[152]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**“Mendicants, a disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with five qualities can’t achieve growth, improvement, or maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[153]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[154]="*Assaddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**A disrespectful and irreverent mendicant who is faithless …*";
P_HTM[155]="*Ahiriko, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**shameless …*";
P_HTM[156]="*Anottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**imprudent …*";
P_HTM[157]="*Kusīto, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**lazy …*";
P_HTM[158]="*Duppañño, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**witless can’t achieve growth, improvement, or maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[159]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu agāravo appatisso abhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**A disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with these five qualities can’t achieve growth, improvement, or maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[160]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso bhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**A respectful and reverent mendicant with five qualities can achieve growth, improvement, and maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[161]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[162]="*Saddho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso bhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**A respectful and reverent mendicant who is faithful …*";
P_HTM[163]="*Hirīmā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu … pe … ottappī, bhikkhave, bhikkhu … pe … āraddhavīriyo, bhikkhave, bhikkhu … pe … paññavā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso bhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjituṃ.**conscientious … prudent … energetic … wise can achieve growth, improvement, and maturity in this teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[164]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso bhabbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjitun”ti.**A respectful and reverent mendicant with these five qualities can achieve growth, improvement, and maturity in this teaching and training.”*";
P_HTM[165]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[166]="*Sekhabalavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[167]="*Saṅkhittaṃ vitthataṃ dukkhā,* **";
P_HTM[168]="*bhataṃ sikkhāya pañcamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[169]="*Samāpatti ca kāmesu,* **";
P_HTM[170]="*cavanā dve agāravāti.* **";
P_HTM[171]="*3. Tatiyapaṇṇāsakaṃ**Powers*";
P_HTM[172]="*1. Ananussutasuttaṃ**Not Learned From Anyone Else*";
P_HTM[173]="*“Pubbāhaṃ, bhikkhave, ananussutesu dhammesu abhiññāvosānapāramippatto paṭijānāmi.**“I claim to have attained perfection and consummation of insight regarding principles not learned before from another.*";
P_HTM[174]="*Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa tathāgatabalāni, yehi balehi samannāgato tathāgato āsabhaṃ ṭhānaṃ paṭijānāti, parisāsu sīhanādaṃ nadati, brahmacakkaṃ pavatteti.**The Realized One has five powers of a Realized One. With these he claims the bull’s place, roars his lion’s roar in the assemblies, and turns the holy wheel.*";
P_HTM[175]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[176]="*Saddhābalaṃ, hirībalaṃ, ottappabalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, paññābalaṃ—**The powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[177]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca tathāgatassa tathāgatabalāni yehi balehi samannāgato tathāgato āsabhaṃ ṭhānaṃ paṭijānāti, parisāsu sīhanādaṃ nadati, brahmacakkaṃ pavattetī”ti.**These are the five powers of a Realized One. With these he claims the bull’s place, roars his lion’s roar in the assemblies, and turns the holy wheel.”*";
P_HTM[178]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[179]="*2. Kūṭasuttaṃ**Peak*";
P_HTM[180]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, sekhabalāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[181]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[182]="*Saddhābalaṃ, hirībalaṃ, ottappabalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, paññābalaṃ—**The powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[183]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca sekhabalāni.**These are the five powers of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[184]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ sekhabalānaṃ etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ paññābalaṃ.**Of these five powers of a trainee, the power of wisdom is the chief. It holds and binds everything together.*";
P_HTM[185]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kūṭāgārassa etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ kūṭaṃ.**It’s like a bungalow. The roof-peak is the chief point, which holds and binds everything together.*";
P_HTM[186]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ sekhabalānaṃ etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ paññābalaṃ.**In the same way, of these five powers of a trainee, the power of wisdom is the chief. It holds and binds everything together.*";
P_HTM[187]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[188]="*‘saddhābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalena, hirībalena … ottappabalena … vīriyabalena … paññābalena samannāgatā bhavissāma sekhabalenā’ti.**‘We will have the trainee’s powers of faith, conscience, prudence, energy, and wisdom.’*";
P_HTM[189]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[190]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[191]="*3. Saṃkhittasuttaṃ**In Brief*";
P_HTM[192]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers.*";
P_HTM[193]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[194]="*Saddhābalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ—**The powers of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[195]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca balānī”ti.**These are the five powers.”*";
P_HTM[196]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[197]="*4. Vitthatasuttaṃ**In Detail*";
P_HTM[198]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers.*";
P_HTM[199]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[200]="*Saddhābalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ.**The powers of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[201]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhābalaṃ?**And what is the power of faith?*";
P_HTM[202]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[203]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[204]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhābalaṃ.**This is called the power of faith.*";
P_HTM[205]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, vīriyabalaṃ?**And what is the power of energy?*";
P_HTM[206]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**It’s when a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[207]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, vīriyabalaṃ.**This is called the power of energy.*";
P_HTM[208]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, satibalaṃ?**And what is the power of mindfulness?*";
P_HTM[209]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako satimā hoti paramena satinepakkena samannāgato, cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**It’s when a noble disciple is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[210]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, satibalaṃ.**This is called the power of mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[211]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, samādhibalaṃ?**And what is the power of immersion?*";
P_HTM[212]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati;**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[213]="*vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati;**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[214]="*pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati;**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[215]="*sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[216]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, samādhibalaṃ.**This is called the power of immersion.*";
P_HTM[217]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññābalaṃ?**And what is the power of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[218]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[219]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññābalaṃ.**This is called the power of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[220]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca balānī”ti.**These are the five powers.”*";
P_HTM[221]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[222]="*5. Daṭṭhabbasuttaṃ**Should Be Seen*";
P_HTM[223]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[225]="*Saddhābalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ.**The powers of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[226]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, saddhābalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the power of faith be seen?*";
P_HTM[227]="*Catūsu sotāpattiyaṅgesu.**In the four factors of stream-entry.*";
P_HTM[228]="*Ettha saddhābalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[229]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, vīriyabalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the power of energy be seen?*";
P_HTM[230]="*Catūsu sammappadhānesu.**In the four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[231]="*Ettha vīriyabalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[232]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, satibalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the power of mindfulness be seen?*";
P_HTM[233]="*Catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu.**In the four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[234]="*Ettha satibalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[235]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, samādhibalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the power of immersion be seen?*";
P_HTM[236]="*Catūsu jhānesu.**In the four absorptions.*";
P_HTM[237]="*Ettha samādhibalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[238]="*Kattha ca, bhikkhave, paññābalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ?**And where should the power of wisdom be seen?*";
P_HTM[239]="*Catūsu ariyasaccesu.**In the four noble truths.*";
P_HTM[240]="*Ettha paññābalaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[241]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca balānī”ti.**These are the five powers.”*";
P_HTM[242]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[243]="*6. Punakūṭasuttaṃ**The Peak, Again*";
P_HTM[244]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, balāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five powers.*";
P_HTM[245]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[246]="*Saddhābalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ—**The powers of faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[247]="*imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca balāni.**These are the five powers.*";
P_HTM[248]="*Imesaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcannaṃ balānaṃ etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ paññābalaṃ.**Of these five powers, the power of wisdom is the chief. It holds and binds everything together.*";
P_HTM[249]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, kūṭāgārassa etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ kūṭaṃ.**It’s like a bungalow. The roof-peak is the chief point, which holds and binds everything together.*";
P_HTM[250]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, imesaṃ pañcannaṃ balānaṃ etaṃ aggaṃ etaṃ saṅgāhikaṃ etaṃ saṅghātaniyaṃ, yadidaṃ paññābalan”ti.**In the same way, of these five powers, the power of wisdom is the chief. It holds and binds everything together.”*";
P_HTM[251]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[252]="*7. Paṭhamahitasuttaṃ**One’s Own Welfare*";
P_HTM[253]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu attahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no parahitāya.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is practicing for their own welfare, but not that of others.*";
P_HTM[254]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[255]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā sīlasampanno hoti, no paraṃ sīlasampadāya samādapeti;**It’s when a mendicant is personally accomplished in ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and the knowledge and vision of freedom. But they don’t encourage others in these qualities.*";
P_HTM[256]="*attanā samādhisampanno hoti, no paraṃ samādhisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[257]="*attanā paññāsampanno hoti, no paraṃ paññāsampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[258]="*attanā vimuttisampanno hoti, no paraṃ vimuttisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[259]="*attanā vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, no paraṃ vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya samādapeti.* **";
P_HTM[260]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgato bhikkhu attahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no parahitāyā”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is practicing for their own welfare, but not that of others.”*";
P_HTM[261]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[262]="*8. Dutiyahitasuttaṃ**Welfare of Others (2nd)*";
P_HTM[263]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu parahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no attahitāya.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is practicing for the welfare of others, but not their own.*";
P_HTM[264]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[265]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā na sīlasampanno hoti, paraṃ sīlasampadāya samādapeti;**It’s when a mendicant is not personally accomplished in ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, or the knowledge and vision of freedom. But they encourage others in these qualities.*";
P_HTM[266]="*attanā na samādhisampanno hoti, paraṃ samādhisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[267]="*attanā na paññāsampanno hoti, paraṃ paññāsampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[268]="*attanā na vimuttisampanno hoti, paraṃ vimuttisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[269]="*attanā na vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, paraṃ vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya samādapeti.* **";
P_HTM[270]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu parahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no attahitāyā”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is practicing for the welfare of others, but not their own.”*";
P_HTM[271]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[272]="*9. Tatiyahitasuttaṃ**The Welfare of Neither*";
P_HTM[273]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu neva attahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no parahitāya.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is practicing neither for their own welfare, nor that of others.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[275]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā na sīlasampanno hoti, no paraṃ sīlasampadāya samādapeti;**It’s when a mendicant is not personally accomplished in ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, or the knowledge and vision of freedom. Nor do they encourage others in these qualities.*";
P_HTM[276]="*attanā na samādhisampanno hoti, no paraṃ samādhisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[277]="*attanā na paññāsampanno hoti, no paraṃ paññāsampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[278]="*attanā na vimuttisampanno hoti, no paraṃ vimuttisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[279]="*attanā na vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, no paraṃ vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya samādapeti.* **";
P_HTM[280]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu neva attahitāya paṭipanno hoti, no parahitāyā”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is practicing neither for their own welfare, nor that of others.”*";
P_HTM[281]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[282]="*10. Catutthahitasuttaṃ**The Welfare of Both*";
P_HTM[283]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu attahitāya ca paṭipanno hoti parahitāya ca.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is practicing for both their own welfare and that of others.*";
P_HTM[284]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[285]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā ca sīlasampanno hoti, parañca sīlasampadāya samādapeti;**It’s when a mendicant is personally accomplished in ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and the knowledge and vision of freedom. And they encourage others in these qualities.*";
P_HTM[286]="*attanā ca samādhisampanno hoti, parañca samādhisampadāya samādapeti, attanā ca paññāsampanno hoti, parañca paññāsampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[287]="*attanā ca vimuttisampanno hoti, parañca vimuttisampadāya samādapeti;* **";
P_HTM[288]="*attanā ca vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, parañca vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya samādapeti.* **";
P_HTM[289]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu attahitāya ca paṭipanno hoti parahitāya cā”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is practicing both for their own welfare and that of others.”*";
P_HTM[290]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[291]="*Balavaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[292]="*Ananussutakūṭañca,* **";
P_HTM[293]="*saṅkhittaṃ vitthatena ca;* **";
P_HTM[294]="*Daṭṭhabbañca puna kūṭaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[295]="*cattāropi hitena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[296]="*4. Catutthapaṇṇāsakaṃ**With Five Factors*";
P_HTM[297]="*1. Paṭhamaagāravasuttaṃ**Disrespect (1st)*";
P_HTM[298]="*“So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso asabhāgavuttiko ‘sabrahmacārīsu ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Mendicants, it’s simply impossible for a disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with incompatible lifestyle to fulfill the practice dealing with supplementary regulations regarding their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[299]="*‘Ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ aparipūretvā sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the practice dealing with supplementary regulations, it’s impossible to fulfill the practice of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[300]="*‘Sekhaṃ dhammaṃ aparipūretvā sīlāni paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the practice of a trainee, it’s impossible to fulfill ethics.*";
P_HTM[301]="*‘Sīlāni aparipūretvā sammādiṭṭhiṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling ethics, it’s impossible to fulfill right view.*";
P_HTM[302]="*‘Sammādiṭṭhiṃ aparipūretvā sammāsamādhiṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling right view, it’s impossible to fulfill right immersion.*";
P_HTM[303]="*So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso sabhāgavuttiko ‘sabrahmacārīsu ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**But it is possible for a respectful and reverent mendicant with compatible lifestyle to fulfill the practice dealing with supplementary regulations regarding their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[304]="*‘Ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūretvā sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled the practice dealing with supplementary regulations, it’s possible to fulfill the practice of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[305]="*‘Sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūretvā sīlāni paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled the practice of a trainee, it’s possible to fulfill ethics.*";
P_HTM[306]="*‘Sīlāni paripūretvā sammādiṭṭhiṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled ethics, it’s possible to fulfill right view.*";
P_HTM[307]="*‘Sammādiṭṭhiṃ paripūretvā sammāsamādhiṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī”ti.**Having fulfilled right view, it’s possible to fulfill right immersion.”*";
P_HTM[308]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[309]="*2. Dutiyaagāravasuttaṃ**Disrespect (2nd)*";
P_HTM[310]="*“So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu agāravo appatisso asabhāgavuttiko ‘sabrahmacārīsu ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Mendicants, it’s simply impossible for a disrespectful and irreverent mendicant with incompatible lifestyle to fulfill the practice dealing with supplementary regulations regarding their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[311]="*‘Ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ aparipūretvā sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the practice dealing with supplementary regulations, it’s impossible to fulfill the practice of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[312]="*‘Sekhaṃ dhammaṃ aparipūretvā sīlakkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the practice of a trainee, it’s impossible to fulfill the entire spectrum of ethics.*";
P_HTM[313]="*‘Sīlakkhandhaṃ aparipūretvā samādhikkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the entire spectrum of ethics, it’s impossible to fulfill the entire spectrum of immersion.*";
P_HTM[314]="*‘Samādhikkhandhaṃ aparipūretvā paññākkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Without fulfilling the entire spectrum of immersion, it’s impossible to fulfill the entire spectrum of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[315]="*So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sagāravo sappatisso sabhāgavuttiko ‘sabrahmacārīsu ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**But it is possible for a respectful and reverent mendicant with compatible lifestyle to fulfill the practice dealing with supplementary regulations regarding their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[316]="*‘Ābhisamācārikaṃ dhammaṃ paripūretvā sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled the practice dealing with supplementary regulations, it’s possible to fulfill the practice of a trainee.*";
P_HTM[317]="*‘Sekhaṃ dhammaṃ paripūretvā sīlakkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled the practice of a trainee, it’s possible to fulfill the entire spectrum of ethics.*";
P_HTM[318]="*‘Sīlakkhandhaṃ paripūretvā samādhikkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Having fulfilled the entire spectrum of ethics, it’s possible to fulfill the entire spectrum of immersion.*";
P_HTM[319]="*‘Samādhikkhandhaṃ paripūretvā paññākkhandhaṃ paripūressatī’ti ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī”ti.**Having fulfilled the entire spectrum of immersion, it’s possible to fulfill the entire spectrum of wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[320]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[321]="*3. Upakkilesasuttaṃ**Corruptions*";
P_HTM[322]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, jātarūpassa upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhaṃ jātarūpaṃ na ceva mudu hoti na ca kammaniyaṃ na ca pabhassaraṃ pabhaṅgu ca na ca sammā upeti kammāya.**“Mendicants, there are these five corruptions of gold. When gold is corrupted by these it’s not pliable, workable, or radiant, but is brittle and not completely ready for working.*";
P_HTM[323]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[324]="*Ayo, lohaṃ, tipu, sīsaṃ, sajjhaṃ—**Iron, copper, tin, lead, and silver.*";
P_HTM[325]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca jātarūpassa upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhaṃ jātarūpaṃ na ceva mudu hoti na ca kammaniyaṃ na ca pabhassaraṃ pabhaṅgu ca na ca sammā upeti kammāya.**When gold is corrupted by these five corruptions it’s not pliable, workable, or radiant, but is brittle and not completely ready for working.*";
P_HTM[326]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, jātarūpaṃ imehi pañcahi upakkilesehi vimuttaṃ hoti, taṃ hoti jātarūpaṃ mudu ca kammaniyañca pabhassarañca na ca pabhaṅgu sammā upeti kammāya.**But when gold is free of these five corruptions it becomes pliable, workable, and radiant, not brittle, and ready to be worked.*";
P_HTM[327]="*Yassā yassā ca piḷandhanavikatiyā ākaṅkhati—yadi muddikāya yadi kuṇḍalāya yadi gīveyyakāya yadi suvaṇṇamālāya—tañcassa atthaṃ anubhoti.**Then the goldsmith can successfully create any kind of ornament they want, whether a ring, earrings, a necklace, or a golden garland.*";
P_HTM[328]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcime cittassa upakkilesā, yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhaṃ cittaṃ na ceva mudu hoti na ca kammaniyaṃ na ca pabhassaraṃ pabhaṅgu ca na ca sammā samādhiyati āsavānaṃ khayāya.**In the same way, there are these five corruptions of the mind. When the mind is corrupted by these it’s not pliable, workable, or radiant. It’s brittle, and not completely immersed in samādhi for the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[329]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[330]="*Kāmacchando, byāpādo, thinamiddhaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccaṃ, vicikicchā—**Sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[331]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca cittassa upakkilesā yehi upakkilesehi upakkiliṭṭhaṃ cittaṃ na ceva mudu hoti na ca kammaniyaṃ na ca pabhassaraṃ pabhaṅgu ca na ca sammā samādhiyati āsavānaṃ khayāya.**These are the five corruptions of the mind. When the mind is corrupted by these it’s not pliable, workable, or radiant. It’s brittle, and not completely immersed in samādhi for the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[332]="*Yato ca kho, bhikkhave, cittaṃ imehi pañcahi upakkilesehi vimuttaṃ hoti, taṃ hoti cittaṃ mudu ca kammaniyañca pabhassarañca na ca pabhaṅgu sammā samādhiyati āsavānaṃ khayāya.**But when the mind is free of these five corruptions it’s pliable, workable, and radiant. It’s not brittle, and is completely immersed in samādhi for the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[333]="*Yassa yassa ca abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You become capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which you extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[334]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhaveyyaṃ—ekopi hutvā bahudhā assaṃ, bahudhāpi hutvā eko assaṃ; āvibhāvaṃ, tirobhāvaṃ; tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gaccheyyaṃ, seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ kareyyaṃ, seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāno gaccheyyaṃ, seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kameyyaṃ, seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parimaseyyaṃ parimajjeyyaṃ yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I wield the many kinds of psychic power—multiplying myself and becoming one again; appearing and disappearing; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful, controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.’*";
P_HTM[335]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[336]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇeyyaṃ—dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike cā’ti,**If you wish: ‘With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, may I hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.’*";
P_HTM[337]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[338]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajāneyyaṃ—**If you wish: ‘May I understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with my mind.*";
P_HTM[339]="*sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ sarāgaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ vītarāgaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ sadosaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ vītadosaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, samohaṃ vā cittaṃ samohaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ vītamohaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ saṅkhittaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ vikkhittaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ mahaggataṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ amahaggataṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ sauttaraṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ anuttaraṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ samāhitaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ asamāhitaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ avimuttaṃ cittanti pajāneyyan’ti,**May I understand mind with greed as “mind with greed”, and mind without greed as “mind without greed”; mind with hate as “mind with hate”, and mind without hate as “mind without hate”; mind with delusion as “mind with delusion”, and mind without delusion as “mind without delusion”; constricted mind as “constricted mind”, and scattered mind as “scattered mind”; expansive mind as “expansive mind”, and unexpansive mind as “unexpansive mind”; mind that is not supreme as “mind that is not supreme”, and mind that is supreme as “mind that is supreme”; mind immersed in samādhi as “mind immersed in samādhi”, and mind not immersed in samādhi as “mind not immersed in samādhi”; freed mind as “freed mind”, and unfreed mind as “unfreed mind”.’*";
P_HTM[340]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[341]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussareyyaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattārīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe—amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapannoti, iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussareyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I recollect many kinds of past lives. That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. May I remember: “There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.” May I recollect my many past lives, with features and details.’*";
P_HTM[342]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[343]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passeyyaṃ cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajāneyyaṃ—ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā; ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannāti, iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passeyyaṃ cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe, sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajāneyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, may I see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place—and understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: “These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they acted out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they acted out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.” And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, may I see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. And may I understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.’*";
P_HTM[344]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[345]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihareyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with my own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[346]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane”ti.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.”*";
P_HTM[347]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[348]="*4. Dussīlasuttaṃ**Unethical*";
P_HTM[349]="*“Dussīlassa, bhikkhave, sīlavipannassa hatūpaniso hoti sammāsamādhi;**“Mendicants, an unethical person, who lacks ethics, has destroyed a vital condition for right immersion.*";
P_HTM[350]="*sammāsamādhimhi asati sammāsamādhivipannassa hatūpanisaṃ hoti yathābhūtañāṇadassanaṃ;**When there is no right immersion, one who lacks right immersion has destroyed a vital condition for true knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[351]="*yathābhūtañāṇadassane asati yathābhūtañāṇadassanavipannassa hatūpaniso hoti nibbidāvirāgo;**When there is no true knowledge and vision, one who lacks true knowledge and vision has destroyed a vital condition for disillusionment and dispassion.*";
P_HTM[352]="*nibbidāvirāge asati nibbidāvirāgavipannassa hatūpanisaṃ hoti vimuttiñāṇadassanaṃ.**When there is no disillusionment and dispassion, one who lacks disillusionment and dispassion has destroyed a vital condition for knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[353]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, rukkho sākhāpalāsavipanno.**Suppose there was a tree that lacked branches and foliage.*";
P_HTM[354]="*Tassa papaṭikāpi na pāripūriṃ gacchati, tacopi na pāripūriṃ gacchati, pheggupi na pāripūriṃ gacchati, sāropi na pāripūriṃ gacchati;**Its shoots, bark, softwood, and heartwood would not grow to fullness.*";
P_HTM[355]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, dussīlassa sīlavipannassa hatūpaniso hoti sammāsamādhi;**In the same way, an unethical person, who lacks ethics, has destroyed a vital condition for right immersion.*";
P_HTM[356]="*sammāsamādhimhi asati sammāsamādhivipannassa hatūpanisaṃ hoti yathābhūtañāṇadassanaṃ;**When there is no right immersion, one who lacks right immersion has destroyed a vital condition for true knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[357]="*yathābhūtañāṇadassane asati yathābhūtañāṇadassanavipannassa hatūpaniso hoti nibbidāvirāgo;**When there is no true knowledge and vision, one who lacks true knowledge and vision has destroyed a vital condition for disillusionment and dispassion.*";
P_HTM[358]="*nibbidāvirāge asati nibbidāvirāgavipannassa hatūpanisaṃ hoti vimuttiñāṇadassanaṃ.**When there is no disillusionment and dispassion, one who lacks disillusionment and dispassion has destroyed a vital condition for knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[359]="*Sīlavato, bhikkhave, sīlasampannassa upanisasampanno hoti sammāsamādhi;**An ethical person, who has fulfilled ethics, has fulfilled a vital condition for right immersion.*";
P_HTM[360]="*sammāsamādhimhi sati sammāsamādhisampannassa upanisasampannaṃ hoti yathābhūtañāṇadassanaṃ;**When there is right immersion, one who has fulfilled right immersion has fulfilled a vital condition for true knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[361]="*yathābhūtañāṇadassane sati yathābhūtañāṇadassanasampannassa upanisasampanno hoti nibbidāvirāgo;**When there is true knowledge and vision, one who has fulfilled true knowledge and vision has fulfilled a vital condition for disillusionment and dispassion.*";
P_HTM[362]="*nibbidāvirāge sati nibbidāvirāgasampannassa upanisasampannaṃ hoti vimuttiñāṇadassanaṃ.**When there is disillusionment and dispassion, one who has fulfilled disillusionment and dispassion has fulfilled a vital condition for knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[363]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, rukkho sākhāpalāsasampanno. Tassa papaṭikāpi pāripūriṃ gacchati, tacopi pāripūriṃ gacchati, pheggupi pāripūriṃ gacchati, sāropi pāripūriṃ gacchati;**Suppose there was a tree that was complete with branches and foliage. Its shoots, bark, softwood, and heartwood would all grow to fullness.*";
P_HTM[364]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sīlavato sīlasampannassa upanisasampanno hoti sammāsamādhi;**In the same way, an ethical person, who has fulfilled ethics, has fulfilled a vital condition for right immersion.*";
P_HTM[365]="*sammāsamādhimhi sati sammāsamādhisampannassa upanisasampannaṃ hoti yathābhūtañāṇadassanaṃ;**When there is right immersion, one who has fulfilled right immersion has fulfilled a vital condition for true knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[366]="*yathābhūtañāṇadassane sati yathābhūtañāṇadassanasampannassa upanisasampanno hoti nibbidāvirāgo;**When there is true knowledge and vision, one who has fulfilled true knowledge and vision has fulfilled a vital condition for disillusionment and dispassion.*";
P_HTM[367]="*nibbidāvirāge sati nibbidāvirāgasampannassa upanisasampannaṃ hoti vimuttiñāṇadassanan”ti.**When there is disillusionment and dispassion, one who has fulfilled disillusionment and dispassion has fulfilled a vital condition for knowledge and vision of freedom.”*";
P_HTM[368]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[369]="*5. Anuggahitasuttaṃ**Supported*";
P_HTM[370]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, aṅgehi anuggahitā sammādiṭṭhi cetovimuttiphalā ca hoti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca hoti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca.**“Mendicants, when right view is supported by five factors it has freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as its fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[371]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[372]="*Idha, bhikkhave, sammādiṭṭhi sīlānuggahitā ca hoti, sutānuggahitā ca hoti, sākacchānuggahitā ca hoti, samathānuggahitā ca hoti, vipassanānuggahitā ca hoti.**It’s when right view is supported by ethics, learning, discussion, serenity, and discernment.*";
P_HTM[373]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi aṅgehi anuggahitā sammādiṭṭhi cetovimuttiphalā ca hoti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca hoti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā cā”ti.**When right view is supported by these five factors it has freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as its fruit and benefit.”*";
P_HTM[374]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[375]="*6. Vimuttāyatanasuttaṃ**Opportunities for Freedom*";
P_HTM[376]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, vimuttāyatanāni yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti.**“Mendicants, there are these five opportunities for freedom. If a mendicant stays diligent, keen, and resolute at these times, their mind is freed, their defilements are ended, and they arrive at the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[377]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[378]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī.**Firstly, the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[379]="*Yathā yathā, bhikkhave, tassa bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches it.*";
P_HTM[380]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[381]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[382]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[383]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[384]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti. (1)**This is the first opportunity for freedom. If a mendicant stays diligent, keen, and resolute at this time, their mind is freed, their defilements are ended, and they arrive at the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[386]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti.**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant. But the mendicant teaches Dhamma in detail to others as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[387]="*Yathā yathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they teach it in detail to others as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[388]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[389]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[390]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[391]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[392]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[393]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti. (2)**This is the second opportunity for freedom. …*";
P_HTM[394]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma. But the mendicant recites the teaching in detail as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[395]="*Yathā yathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they recite it in detail as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[396]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[397]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[398]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[399]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[400]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[401]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino … pe … yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti. (3)**This is the third opportunity for freedom. …*";
P_HTM[402]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti;**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma … nor does the mendicant recite the teaching.*";
P_HTM[403]="*api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati.**But the mendicant thinks about and considers the teaching in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[404]="*Yathā yathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they think about and consider it in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[405]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[406]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[407]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[408]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[409]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[410]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti. (4)**This is the fourth opportunity for freedom. …*";
P_HTM[411]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati;**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma … nor does the mendicant recite the teaching … or think about it.*";
P_HTM[412]="*api ca khvassa aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya.**But a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[413]="*Yathā yathā, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[414]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up.*";
P_HTM[415]="*Pamuditassa pīti jāyati.**Being joyful, rapture springs up.*";
P_HTM[416]="*Pītimanassa kāyo passambhati.**When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil.*";
P_HTM[417]="*Passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti.**When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss.*";
P_HTM[418]="*Sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed in samādhi.*";
P_HTM[419]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇāti. (5)**This is the fifth opportunity for freedom. …*";
P_HTM[420]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca vimuttāyatanāni yattha bhikkhuno appamattassa ātāpino pahitattassa viharato avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ vimuccati, aparikkhīṇā vā āsavā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, ananuppattaṃ vā anuttaraṃ yogakkhemaṃ anupāpuṇātī”ti.**These are the five opportunities for freedom. If a mendicant stays diligent, keen, and resolute at these times, their mind is freed, their defilements are ended, and they arrive at the supreme sanctuary.”*";
P_HTM[421]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[422]="*7. Samādhisuttaṃ**Immersion*";
P_HTM[423]="*“Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha appamāṇaṃ nipakā patissatā.**“Mendicants, develop limitless immersion, alert and mindful.*";
P_HTM[424]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvayataṃ appamāṇaṃ nipakānaṃ patissatānaṃ pañca ñāṇāni paccattaññeva uppajjanti.**When you develop limitless immersion, alert and mindful, five knowledges arise for you personally.*";
P_HTM[425]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[426]="*‘Ayaṃ samādhi paccuppannasukho ceva āyatiñca sukhavipāko’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati,**‘This immersion is blissful now, and results in bliss in the future.’ …*";
P_HTM[427]="*‘ayaṃ samādhi ariyo nirāmiso’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati,**‘This immersion is noble and spiritual.’ …*";
P_HTM[428]="*‘ayaṃ samādhi akāpurisasevito’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati,**‘This immersion is not cultivated by sinners.’ …*";
P_HTM[429]="*‘ayaṃ samādhi santo paṇīto paṭippassaddhaladdho ekodibhāvādhigato, na sasaṅkhāraniggayhavāritagato’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati,**‘This immersion is peaceful and sublime and tranquil and unified, not held in place by forceful suppression.’ …*";
P_HTM[430]="*‘sato kho panāhaṃ imaṃ samāpajjāmi sato vuṭṭhahāmī’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**‘I mindfully enter into and emerge from this immersion.’ …*";
P_HTM[431]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvetha appamāṇaṃ nipakā patissatā.**Develop limitless immersion, alert and mindful.*";
P_HTM[432]="*Samādhiṃ, bhikkhave, bhāvayataṃ appamāṇaṃ nipakānaṃ patissatānaṃ imāni pañca ñāṇāni paccattaññeva uppajjantī”ti.**When you develop limitless immersion, alert and mindful, these five knowledges arise for you personally.”*";
P_HTM[433]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[434]="*8. Pañcaṅgikasuttaṃ**With Five Factors*";
P_HTM[435]="*“Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa bhāvanaṃ desessāmi.**“Mendicants, I will teach you how to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[436]="*Taṃ suṇātha, sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[437]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[438]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[439]="*“Katamā ca, bhikkhave, ariyassa pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa bhāvanā?**“And how do you develop noble right immersion with five factors?*";
P_HTM[440]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi … pe … paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Firstly, a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption. It has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[441]="*So imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[442]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dakkho nhāpako vā nhāpakantevāsī vā kaṃsathāle nhānīyacuṇṇāni ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ sanneyya. Sāyaṃ nhānīyapiṇḍi snehānugatā snehaparetā santarabāhirā phuṭā snehena, na ca paggharinī.**It’s like when a deft bathroom attendant or their apprentice pours bath powder into a bronze dish, sprinkling it little by little with water. They knead it until the ball of bath powder is soaked and saturated with moisture, spread through inside and out; yet no moisture oozes out.*";
P_HTM[443]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati;**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[444]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[445]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa ayaṃ paṭhamā bhāvanā. (1)**This is the first way to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[446]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption. It has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[447]="*So imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati;**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[448]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[449]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakarahado gambhīro ubbhidodako. Tassa nevassa puratthimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na pacchimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na uttarāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na dakkhiṇāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, devo ca kālena kālaṃ sammā dhāraṃ nānuppaveccheyya.**It’s like a deep lake fed by spring water. There’s no inlet to the east, west, north, or south, and no rainfall to replenish it from time to time.*";
P_HTM[450]="*Atha kho tamhāva udakarahadā sītā vāridhārā ubbhijjitvā tameva udakarahadaṃ sītena vārinā abhisandeyya parisandeyya paripūreyya paripphareyya; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato udakarahadassa sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa.**But the stream of cool water welling up in the lake drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads throughout the lake. There’s no part of the lake that’s not spread through with cool water.*";
P_HTM[451]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati;**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[452]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[453]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa ayaṃ dutiyā bhāvanā. (2)**This is the second way to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[454]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption. They meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[455]="*So imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati;**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[456]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[457]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, uppaliniyaṃ vā paduminiyaṃ vā puṇḍarīkiniyaṃ vā appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakānuggatāni anto nimuggaposīni.**It’s like a pool with blue water lilies, or pink or white lotuses. Some of them sprout and grow in the water without rising above it, thriving underwater.*";
P_HTM[458]="*Tāni yāva caggā yāva ca mūlā sītena vārinā abhisannāni parisannāni paripūrāni paripphuṭāni;**From the tip to the root they’re drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with cool water.*";
P_HTM[459]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvataṃ uppalānaṃ vā padumānaṃ vā puṇḍarīkānaṃ vā sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa.**There’s no part of them that’s not spread through with cool water.*";
P_HTM[460]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati;**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[461]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[462]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa ayaṃ tatiyā bhāvanā. (3)**This is the third way to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[463]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption. It is without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[464]="*So imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti;**They sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[465]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[466]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, puriso odātena vatthena sasīsaṃ pārupitvā nisinno assa;**It’s like someone sitting wrapped from head to foot with white cloth.*";
P_HTM[467]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa odātena vatthena apphuṭaṃ assa.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread over with white cloth.*";
P_HTM[468]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti;**In the same way, they sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[469]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[470]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa ayaṃ catutthā bhāvanā. (4)**This is the fourth way to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[471]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇānimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya.**Furthermore, the meditation that is a foundation for reviewing is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom by a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[472]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, aññova aññaṃ paccavekkheyya, ṭhito vā nisinnaṃ paccavekkheyya, nisinno vā nipannaṃ paccavekkheyya.**It’s like when someone views someone else. Someone standing might view someone sitting, or someone sitting might view someone lying down.*";
P_HTM[473]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno paccavekkhaṇānimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya.**In the same way, the meditation that is a foundation for reviewing is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom by a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[474]="*Ariyassa, bhikkhave, pañcaṅgikassa sammāsamādhissa ayaṃ pañcamā bhāvanā. (5)**This is the fifth way to develop noble right immersion with five factors.*";
P_HTM[475]="*Evaṃ bhāvite kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariye pañcaṅgike sammāsamādhimhi evaṃ bahulīkate yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**When the noble right immersion with five factors is cultivated in this way, a mendicant becomes capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[476]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, udakamaṇiko ādhāre ṭhapito pūro udakassa samatittiko kākapeyyo.**Suppose a water jar was placed on a stand, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[477]="*Tamenaṃ balavā puriso yato yato āvajjeyya, āgaccheyya udakan”ti?**If a strong man was to tip it any which way, would water pour out?”*";
P_HTM[478]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[479]="*“Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ bhāvite ariye pañcaṅgike sammāsamādhimhi evaṃ bahulīkate yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya, tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**“In the same way, when noble right immersion with five factors is cultivated in this way, a mendicant becomes capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[480]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, same bhūmibhāge pokkharaṇī caturaṃsā ālibaddhā pūrā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Suppose there was a square, walled lotus pond on level ground, full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[481]="*Tamenaṃ balavā puriso yato yato āliṃ muñceyya, āgaccheyya udakan”ti?**If a strong man was to open the wall on any side, would water pour out?”*";
P_HTM[482]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[483]="*“Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ bhāvite ariye pañcaṅgike sammāsamādhimhi evaṃ bahulīkate yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa … pe … sati sati āyatane.**“In the same way, when noble right immersion with five factors is cultivated in this way, a mendicant becomes capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[484]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, subhūmiyaṃ catumahāpathe ājaññaratho yutto assa ṭhito odhastapatodo.**Suppose a chariot stood harnessed to thoroughbreds at a level crossroads, with a goad ready.*";
P_HTM[485]="*Tamenaṃ dakkho yoggācariyo assadammasārathi abhiruhitvā vāmena hatthena rasmiyo gahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena patodaṃ gahetvā yenicchakaṃ yadicchakaṃ sāreyyapi paccāsāreyyapi.**Then a deft horse trainer, a master charioteer, might mount the chariot, taking the reins in his right hand and goad in the left. He’d drive out and back wherever he wishes, whenever he wishes.*";
P_HTM[486]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu evaṃ bhāvite ariye pañcaṅgike sammāsamādhimhi evaṃ bahulīkate yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmeti abhiññāsacchikiriyāya,**In the same way, when noble right immersion with five factors is cultivated in this way,*";
P_HTM[487]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**a mendicant becomes capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which they extend the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[488]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhaveyyaṃ—ekopi hutvā bahudhā assaṃ … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I wield the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying myself and becoming one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.’*";
P_HTM[489]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[490]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇeyyaṃ—dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike cā’ti,**If you wish: ‘With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, may I hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.’*";
P_HTM[491]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[492]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajāneyyaṃ—sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ sarāgaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ vītarāgaṃ cittanti pajāneyyaṃ, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ … vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ … samohaṃ vā cittaṃ … vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ … saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ … vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ … mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ … amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ … sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ … anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ … samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ … asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ … vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ … avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ avimuttaṃ cittanti pajāneyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with my mind. May I understand mind with greed as “mind with greed”, and mind without greed as “mind without greed”; mind with hate as “mind with hate”, and mind without hate as “mind without hate”; mind with delusion as “mind with delusion”, and mind without delusion as “mind without delusion”; constricted mind as “constricted mind”, and scattered mind as “scattered mind”; expansive mind as “expansive mind”, and unexpansive mind as “unexpansive mind”; mind that is not supreme as “mind that is not supreme”, and mind that is supreme as “mind that is supreme”; mind immersed in samādhi as “mind immersed in samādhi”, and mind not immersed in samādhi as “mind not immersed in samādhi”; freed mind as “freed mind”, and unfreed mind as “unfreed mind”.’*";
P_HTM[493]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[494]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussareyyaṃ, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ, dvepi jātiyo … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussareyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I recollect many kinds of past lives, with features and details.’*";
P_HTM[495]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[496]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena … pe … yathākammūpage satte pajāneyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, may I see sentient beings passing away and being reborn according to their deeds.’*";
P_HTM[497]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[498]="*So sace ākaṅkhati: ‘āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihareyyan’ti,**If you wish: ‘May I realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with my own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[499]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇāti sati sati āyatane”ti.**You’re capable of realizing it, in each and every case.”*";
P_HTM[500]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[501]="*9. Caṅkamasuttaṃ**Walking Meditation*";
P_HTM[502]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, caṅkame ānisaṃsā.**“Mendicants, there are five benefits of walking meditation.*";
P_HTM[503]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[504]="*Addhānakkhamo hoti, padhānakkhamo hoti, appābādho hoti, asitaṃ pītaṃ khāyitaṃ sāyitaṃ sammā pariṇāmaṃ gacchati, caṅkamādhigato samādhi ciraṭṭhitiko hoti.**You get fit for traveling, fit for striving in meditation, and healthy. What’s eaten, drunk, chewed, and tasted is properly digested. And immersion gained while walking lasts long.*";
P_HTM[505]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca caṅkame ānisaṃsā”ti.**These are the five benefits of walking meditation.”*";
P_HTM[506]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[507]="*10. Nāgitasuttaṃ**With Nāgita*";
P_HTM[508]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[509]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ yena icchānaṅgalaṃ nāma kosalānaṃ brāhmaṇagāmo tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of mendicants when he arrived at a village of the Kosalan brahmins named Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe.**He stayed in a forest near Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[511]="*Assosuṃ kho icchānaṅgalakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā:**The brahmins and householders of Icchānaṅgala heard:*";
P_HTM[512]="*“samaṇo khalu bho gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito icchānaṅgalaṃ anuppatto; icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Icchānaṅgala. He is staying in a forest near Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[513]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[514]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi, satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti’.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[515]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[516]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[517]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[518]="*Atha kho icchānaṅgalakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā tassā rattiyā accayena pahūtaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ ādāya yena icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bahidvārakoṭṭhake aṭṭhaṃsu uccāsaddamahāsaddā.**Then, when the night had passed, they took many different foods and went to the forest near Icchānaṅgala, where they stood outside the gates making a dreadful racket.*";
P_HTM[519]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā nāgito bhagavato upaṭṭhāko hoti.**Now, at that time Venerable Nāgita was the Buddha’s attendant.*";
P_HTM[520]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Nāgita,*";
P_HTM[521]="*“ke pana kho, nāgita, uccāsaddamahāsaddā, kevaṭṭā maññe macchavilope”ti?**“Nāgita, who’s making that dreadful racket? You’d think it was fishermen hauling in a catch!”*";
P_HTM[522]="*“Ete, bhante, icchānaṅgalakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā pahūtaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ ādāya bahidvārakoṭṭhake ṭhitā bhagavantaññeva uddissa bhikkhusaṃghañcā”ti.**“Sir, it’s these brahmins and householders of Icchānaṅgala. They’ve brought many different foods, and they’re standing outside the gates wanting to offer it specially to the Buddha and the mendicant Saṅgha.”*";
P_HTM[523]="*“Māhaṃ, nāgita, yasena samāgamaṃ, mā ca mayā yaso.**“Nāgita, may I never become famous. May fame not come to me.*";
P_HTM[524]="*Yo kho, nāgita, nayimassa nekkhammasukhassa pavivekasukhassa upasamasukhassa sambodhasukhassa nikāmalābhī assa akicchalābhī akasiralābhī, yassāhaṃ nekkhammasukhassa pavivekasukhassa upasamasukhassa sambodhasukhassa nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**There are those who can’t get the bliss of renunciation, the bliss of seclusion, the bliss of peace, the bliss of awakening when they want, without trouble or difficulty like I can.*";
P_HTM[525]="*So taṃ mīḷhasukhaṃ middhasukhaṃ lābhasakkārasilokasukhaṃ sādiyeyyā”ti.**Let them enjoy the filthy, lazy pleasure of possessions, honor, and popularity.”*";
P_HTM[526]="*“Adhivāsetu dāni, bhante, bhagavā, adhivāsetu sugato;**“Sir, may the Blessed One please relent now! May the Holy One relent!*";
P_HTM[527]="*adhivāsanakālo dāni, bhante, bhagavato.**Now is the time for the Buddha to relent.*";
P_HTM[528]="*Yena yeneva dāni bhagavā gamissati taṃninnāva gamissanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**Wherever the Buddha now goes, the brahmins and householders will incline the same way, as will the people of town and country.*";
P_HTM[529]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, thullaphusitake deve vassante yathāninnaṃ udakāni pavattanti;**It’s like when it rains heavily and the water flows downhill.*";
P_HTM[530]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhante, yena yeneva dāni bhagavā gamissati, taṃninnāva gamissanti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**In the same way, wherever the Buddha now goes, the brahmins and householders will incline the same way, as will the people of town and country.*";
P_HTM[531]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[532]="*Tathā hi, bhante, bhagavato sīlapaññāṇan”ti.**Because of the Buddha’s ethics and wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[533]="*“Māhaṃ, nāgita, yasena samāgamaṃ, mā ca mayā yaso.**“Nāgita, may I never become famous. May fame not come to me.*";
P_HTM[534]="*Yo kho, nāgita, nayimassa nekkhammasukhassa pavivekasukhassa upasamasukhassa sambodhasukhassa nikāmalābhī assa akicchalābhī akasiralābhī, yassāhaṃ nekkhammasukhassa pavivekasukhassa upasamasukhassa sambodhasukhassa nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**There are those who can’t get the bliss of renunciation, the bliss of seclusion, the bliss of peace, the bliss of awakening when they want, without trouble or difficulty like I can.*";
P_HTM[535]="*So taṃ mīḷhasukhaṃ middhasukhaṃ lābhasakkārasilokasukhaṃ sādiyeyya.**Let them enjoy the filthy, lazy pleasure of possessions, honor, and popularity.*";
P_HTM[536]="*Asitapītakhāyitasāyitassa kho, nāgita, uccārapassāvo—**What you eat, drink, chew, and taste ends up as excrement and urine.*";
P_HTM[537]="*eso tassa nissando.**This is its outcome.*";
P_HTM[538]="*Piyānaṃ kho, nāgita, vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā—**When loved ones decay and perish, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress arise.*";
P_HTM[539]="*eso tassa nissando.**This is its outcome.*";
P_HTM[540]="*Asubhanimittānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa kho, nāgita, subhanimitte pāṭikulyatā saṇṭhāti—**When you pursue meditation on the feature of ugliness, revulsion at the feature of beauty becomes stabilized.*";
P_HTM[541]="*eso tassa nissando.**This is its outcome.*";
P_HTM[542]="*Chasu kho, nāgita, phassāyatanesu aniccānupassino viharato phasse pāṭikulyatā saṇṭhāti—**When you meditate observing impermanence in the six fields of contact, revulsion at contact becomes stabilized.*";
P_HTM[543]="*eso tassa nissando.**This is its outcome.*";
P_HTM[544]="*Pañcasu kho, nāgita, upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassino viharato upādāne pāṭikulyatā saṇṭhāti—**When you meditate observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates, revulsion at grasping becomes stabilized.*";
P_HTM[545]="*eso tassa nissando”ti.**This is its outcome.”*";
P_HTM[546]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[547]="*Pañcaṅgikavaggo tatiyo.* **";
P_HTM[548]="*Dve agāravupakkilesā,* **";
P_HTM[549]="*Dussīlānuggahitena ca;* **";
P_HTM[550]="*Vimuttisamādhipañcaṅgikā,* **";
P_HTM[551]="*Caṅkamaṃ nāgitena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[552]="*5. Pañcamapaṇṇāsakaṃ**With Sumanā*";
P_HTM[553]="*1. Sumanasuttaṃ**With Sumanā*";
P_HTM[554]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ … pe … anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Atha kho sumanā rājakumārī pañcahi rathasatehi pañcahi rājakumārisatehi parivutā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho sumanā rājakumārī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Princess Sumanā, escorted by five hundred chariots and five hundred royal maidens, went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[556]="*“Idhassu, bhante, bhagavato dve sāvakā samasaddhā samasīlā samapaññā—**“Sir, suppose there were two disciples equal in faith, ethics, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[557]="*eko dāyako, eko adāyako.**One is a giver, one is not.*";
P_HTM[558]="*Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjeyyuṃ.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[559]="*Devabhūtānaṃ pana nesaṃ, bhante, siyā viseso, siyā nānākaraṇan”ti?**When they have become gods, would there be any distinction or difference between them?”*";
P_HTM[560]="*“Siyā, sumane”ti bhagavā avoca:**“There would be, Sumanā,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[561]="*“yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ devabhūto samāno pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti—**“As a god, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in five respects:*";
P_HTM[562]="*dibbena āyunā, dibbena vaṇṇena, dibbena sukhena, dibbena yasena, dibbena ādhipateyyena.**divine lifespan, beauty, happiness, fame, and sovereignty.*";
P_HTM[563]="*Yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ devabhūto samāno imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti”.**As a god, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in these five respects.”*";
P_HTM[564]="*“Sace pana te, bhante, tato cutā itthattaṃ āgacchanti, manussabhūtānaṃ pana nesaṃ, bhante, siyā viseso, siyā nānākaraṇan”ti?**“But sir, if they pass away from there and come back to this state of existence as human beings, would there still be any distinction or difference between them?”*";
P_HTM[565]="*“Siyā, sumane”ti bhagavā avoca:**“There would be, Sumanā,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[566]="*“yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ manussabhūto samāno pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti—**“As a human being, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in five respects:*";
P_HTM[567]="*mānusakena āyunā, mānusakena vaṇṇena, mānusakena sukhena, mānusakena yasena, mānusakena ādhipateyyena.**human lifespan, beauty, happiness, fame, and sovereignty.*";
P_HTM[568]="*Yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ manussabhūto samāno imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti”.**As a human being, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in these five respects.”*";
P_HTM[569]="*“Sace pana te, bhante, ubho agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, pabbajitānaṃ pana nesaṃ, bhante, siyā viseso, siyā nānākaraṇan”ti?**“But sir, if they both go forth from the lay life to homelessness, would there still be any distinction or difference between them?”*";
P_HTM[570]="*“Siyā, sumane”ti bhagavā avoca:**“There would be, Sumanā,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[571]="*“yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ pabbajito samāno pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti—**“As a renunciate, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in five respects.*";
P_HTM[572]="*yācitova bahulaṃ cīvaraṃ paribhuñjati appaṃ ayācito, yācitova bahulaṃ piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjati appaṃ ayācito, yācitova bahulaṃ senāsanaṃ paribhuñjati appaṃ ayācito, yācitova bahulaṃ gilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhāraṃ paribhuñjati appaṃ ayācito.**They’d usually use only what they’ve been invited to accept—robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick—rarely using them without invitation.*";
P_HTM[573]="*Yehi kho pana sabrahmacārīhi saddhiṃ viharati tyassa manāpeneva bahulaṃ kāyakammena samudācaranti appaṃ amanāpena, manāpeneva bahulaṃ vacīkammena samudācaranti appaṃ amanāpena, manāpeneva bahulaṃ manokammena samudācaranti appaṃ amanāpena, manāpaṃyeva bahulaṃ upahāraṃ upaharanti appaṃ amanāpaṃ.**When living with other spiritual practitioners, they usually treat them agreeably by way of body, speech, and mind, rarely disagreeably.*";
P_HTM[574]="*Yo so, sumane, dāyako so amuṃ adāyakaṃ pabbajito samāno imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhātī”ti.**As a renunciate, the one who was a giver would surpass the other in these five respects.”*";
P_HTM[575]="*“Sace pana te, bhante, ubho arahattaṃ pāpuṇanti, arahattappattānaṃ pana nesaṃ, bhante, siyā viseso, siyā nānākaraṇan”ti?**“But sir, if they both attain perfection, as perfected ones would there still be any distinction or difference between them?”*";
P_HTM[576]="*“Ettha kho panesāhaṃ, sumane, na kiñci nānākaraṇaṃ vadāmi, yadidaṃ vimuttiyā vimuttin”ti.**“In that case, I say there is no difference between the freedom of one and the freedom of the other.”*";
P_HTM[577]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[578]="*Yāvañcidaṃ, bhante, alameva dānāni dātuṃ alaṃ puññāni kātuṃ;**Just this much is quite enough to justify giving gifts and making merit.*";
P_HTM[579]="*yatra hi nāma devabhūtassāpi upakārāni puññāni, manussabhūtassāpi upakārāni puññāni, pabbajitassāpi upakārāni puññānī”ti.**For merit is helpful for those who have become gods, human beings, and renunciates.”*";
P_HTM[580]="*“Evametaṃ, sumane.**“That’s so true, Sumanā.*";
P_HTM[581]="*Alañhi, sumane, dānāni dātuṃ alaṃ puññāni kātuṃ.**It’s quite enough to justify giving gifts and making merit.*";
P_HTM[582]="*Devabhūtassāpi upakārāni puññāni, manussabhūtassāpi upakārāni puññāni, pabbajitassāpi upakārāni puññānī”ti.**For merit is helpful for those who have become gods, human beings, and renunciates.”*";
P_HTM[583]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[584]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[585]="*“Yathāpi cando vimalo,**“The moon so immaculate,*";
P_HTM[586]="*gacchaṃ ākāsadhātuyā;**journeying across the dimension of space;*";
P_HTM[587]="*Sabbe tārāgaṇe loke,**outshines with its radiance*";
P_HTM[588]="*ābhāya atirocati.**all the world’s stars.*";
P_HTM[589]="*Tatheva sīlasampanno,**So too, a faithful individual,*";
P_HTM[590]="*saddho purisapuggalo;**perfect in ethics,*";
P_HTM[591]="*Sabbe maccharino loke,**outshines with their generosity*";
P_HTM[592]="*cāgena atirocati.**all the world’s stingy people.*";
P_HTM[593]="*Yathāpi megho thanayaṃ,**The thundering rain cloud,*";
P_HTM[594]="*vijjumālī satakkaku;**its hundred peaks wreathed in lightning,*";
P_HTM[595]="*Thalaṃ ninnañca pūreti,**pours down over the rich earth,*";
P_HTM[596]="*abhivassaṃ vasundharaṃ.**soaking the plains and lowlands.*";
P_HTM[597]="*Evaṃ dassanasampanno,**Even so, an astute person accomplished in vision,*";
P_HTM[598]="*sammāsambuddhasāvako;**a disciple of the fully awakened Buddha,*";
P_HTM[599]="*Macchariṃ adhigaṇhāti,**surpasses a stingy person*";
P_HTM[600]="*pañcaṭhānehi paṇḍito.**in five respects:*";
P_HTM[601]="*Āyunā yasasā ceva,**long life and fame,*";
P_HTM[602]="*vaṇṇena ca sukhena ca;**beauty and happiness.*";
P_HTM[603]="*Sa ve bhogaparibyūḷho,**Blessed with riches,*";
P_HTM[604]="*pecca sagge pamodatī”ti.**they depart to rejoice in heaven.”*";
P_HTM[605]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[606]="*2. Cundīsuttaṃ**With Cundī*";
P_HTM[607]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[608]="*Atha kho cundī rājakumārī pañcahi rathasatehi pañcahi ca kumārisatehi parivutā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho cundī rājakumārī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Princess Cundī, escorted by five hundred chariots and five hundred royal maidens, went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[609]="*“Amhākaṃ, bhante, bhātā cundo nāma rājakumāro, so evamāha:**“Sir, my brother, Prince Cunda, says this:*";
P_HTM[610]="*‘yadeva so hoti itthī vā puriso vā buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gato, pāṇātipātā paṭivirato, adinnādānā paṭivirato, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato, musāvādā paṭivirato, surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato, so kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃyeva upapajjati, no duggatin’ti.**‘Take a woman or man who goes for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or take alcoholic drinks that cause negligence. Only then do they get reborn in a good place, not a bad place, when their body breaks up, after death.’*";
P_HTM[611]="*Sāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ pucchāmi:**And so I ask the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[612]="*‘kathaṃrūpe kho, bhante, satthari pasanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃyeva upapajjati, no duggatiṃ?**Sir, what kind of teacher should you have confidence in so as to be reborn in a good place, not a bad place, when the body breaks up, after death?*";
P_HTM[613]="*Kathaṃrūpe dhamme pasanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃyeva upapajjati, no duggatiṃ?**Sir, what kind of teaching should you have confidence in so as to be reborn in a good place, not a bad place, when the body breaks up, after death?*";
P_HTM[614]="*Kathaṃrūpe saṅghe pasanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃyeva upapajjati, no duggatiṃ?**Sir, what kind of Saṅgha should you have confidence in so as to be reborn in a good place, not a bad place, when the body breaks up, after death?*";
P_HTM[615]="*Kathaṃrūpesu sīlesu paripūrakārī kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃyeva upapajjati, no duggatin’”ti?**Sir, what kind of ethics should you fulfill so as to be reborn in a good place, not a bad place, when the body breaks up, after death?”*";
P_HTM[616]="*“Yāvatā, cundi, sattā apadā vā dvipadā vā catuppadā vā bahuppadā vā rūpino vā arūpino vā saññino vā asaññino vā nevasaññināsaññino vā, tathāgato tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**“Cundī, the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, is said to be the best of all sentient beings—be they footless, with two feet, four feet, or many feet; with form or formless; with perception or without perception or with neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[617]="*Ye kho, cundi, buddhe pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the Buddha have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[618]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[619]="*Yāvatā, cundi, dhammā saṅkhatā, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati.**The noble eightfold path is said to be the best of all conditioned things.*";
P_HTM[620]="*Ye, cundi, ariye aṭṭhaṅgike magge pasannā, agge te pasannā, agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Those who have confidence in the noble eightfold path have confidence in the best. Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[621]="*Yāvatā, cundi, dhammā saṅkhatā vā asaṅkhatā vā, virāgo tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yadidaṃ—**Fading away is said to be the best of all things whether conditioned or unconditioned.*";
P_HTM[622]="*madanimmadano pipāsavinayo ālayasamugghāto vaṭṭupacchedo taṇhākkhayo virāgo nirodho nibbānaṃ.**That is, the quelling of vanity, the removing of thirst, the uprooting of clinging, the breaking of the round, the ending of craving, fading away, cessation, extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[623]="*Ye kho, cundi, virāge dhamme pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the teaching of fading away have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[624]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[625]="*Yāvatā, cundi, saṅghā vā gaṇā vā, tathāgatasāvakasaṅgho tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yadidaṃ—**The Saṅgha of the Realized One’s disciples is said to be the best of all communities and groups.*";
P_HTM[626]="*cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā, esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassa.**It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.*";
P_HTM[627]="*Ye kho, cundi, saṅghe pasannā, agge te pasannā.**Those who have confidence in the Saṅgha have confidence in the best.*";
P_HTM[628]="*Agge kho pana pasannānaṃ aggo vipāko hoti.**Having confidence in the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[629]="*Yāvatā, cundi, sīlāni, ariyakantāni sīlāni tesaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yadidaṃ—**The ethical conduct loved by the noble ones is said to be the best of all ethics.*";
P_HTM[630]="*akhaṇḍāni acchiddāni asabalāni akammāsāni bhujissāni viññuppasatthāni aparāmaṭṭhāni samādhisaṃvattanikāni.**It is unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[631]="*Ye kho, cundi, ariyakantesu sīlesu paripūrakārino, agge te paripūrakārino.**Those who fulfill the ethics loved by the noble ones fulfill the best.*";
P_HTM[632]="*Agge kho pana paripūrakārīnaṃ aggo vipāko hotīti.**Fulfilling the best, the result is the best.*";
P_HTM[633]="*Aggato ve pasannānaṃ,**For those who, knowing the best teaching,*";
P_HTM[634]="*aggaṃ dhammaṃ vijānataṃ;**base their confidence on the best—*";
P_HTM[635]="*Agge buddhe pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[636]="*dakkhiṇeyye anuttare.**supremely worthy of a religious donation;*";
P_HTM[637]="*Agge dhamme pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best teaching,*";
P_HTM[638]="*virāgūpasame sukhe;**the bliss of fading and stilling;*";
P_HTM[639]="*Agge saṅghe pasannānaṃ,**confident in the best Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[640]="*puññakkhette anuttare.**the supreme field of merit—*";
P_HTM[641]="*Aggasmiṃ dānaṃ dadataṃ,**giving gifts to the best,*";
P_HTM[642]="*aggaṃ puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati;**the best of merit grows:*";
P_HTM[643]="*Aggaṃ āyu ca vaṇṇo ca,**the best lifespan, beauty,*";
P_HTM[644]="*yaso kitti sukhaṃ balaṃ.**fame, reputation, happiness, and strength.*";
P_HTM[645]="*Aggassa dātā medhāvī,**An intelligent person gives to the best,*";
P_HTM[646]="*aggadhammasamāhito;**settled on the best teaching.*";
P_HTM[647]="*Devabhūto manusso vā,**When they become a god or human,*";
P_HTM[648]="*aggappatto pamodatī”ti.**they rejoice at reaching the best.”*";
P_HTM[649]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[650]="*3. Uggahasuttaṃ**With Uggaha*";
P_HTM[651]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā bhaddiye viharati jātiyā vane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Bhaddiya, in Jātiyā Wood.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Atha kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Uggaha, Meṇḍaka’s grandson, went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[653]="*“Adhivāsetu me, bhante, bhagavā svātanāya attacatuttho bhattan”ti.**“Sir, may the Buddha please accept tomorrow’s meal from me, together with three other monks.”*";
P_HTM[654]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[655]="*Atha kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Uggaha got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[656]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena uggahassa meṇḍakanattuno nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then when the night had passed, the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to Uggaha’s home, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[657]="*Atha kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā bhagavantaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Uggaha served and satisfied the Buddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[658]="*Atha kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Uggaha sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[659]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho uggaho meṇḍakanattā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[660]="*“imā me, bhante, kumāriyo patikulāni gamissanti.**“Sir, these girls of mine will be going to their husbands’ families.*";
P_HTM[661]="*Ovadatu tāsaṃ, bhante, bhagavā;**May the Buddha please advise*";
P_HTM[662]="*anusāsatu tāsaṃ, bhante, bhagavā, yaṃ tāsaṃ assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**and instruct them. It will be for their lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[663]="*Atha kho bhagavā tā kumāriyo etadavoca:**Then the Buddha said to those girls:*";
P_HTM[664]="*“tasmātiha, kumāriyo, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**“So, girls, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[665]="*‘yassa vo mātāpitaro bhattuno dassanti atthakāmā hitesino anukampakā anukampaṃ upādāya, tassa bhavissāma pubbuṭṭhāyiniyo pacchānipātiniyo kiṃkārapaṭissāviniyo manāpacāriniyo piyavādiniyo’ti.**‘Our parents will give us to a husband wanting what’s best, out of kindness and compassion. We will get up before him and go to bed after him, and be obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely.’*";
P_HTM[666]="*Evañhi vo, kumāriyo, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[667]="*Tasmātiha, kumāriyo, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So, girls, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[668]="*‘ye te bhattu garuno bhavissanti mātāti vā pitāti vā samaṇabrāhmaṇāti vā, te sakkarissāma garuṃ karissāma mānessāma pūjessāma abbhāgate ca āsanodakena paṭipūjessāmā’ti.**‘Those our husband respects—mother and father, ascetics and brahmins—we will honor, respect, revere, and venerate, and serve with a seat and a drink when they come as guests.’*";
P_HTM[669]="*Evañhi vo, kumāriyo, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[670]="*Tasmātiha, kumāriyo, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So, girls, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[671]="*‘ye te bhattu abbhantarā kammantā uṇṇāti vā kappāsāti vā, tattha dakkhā bhavissāma analasā, tatrupāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgatā, alaṃ kātuṃ alaṃ saṃvidhātun’ti.**‘We will be skilled and tireless in doing domestic duties for our husband, such as knitting and sewing. We will have an understanding of how to go about things in order to complete and organize the work.’*";
P_HTM[672]="*Evañhi vo, kumāriyo, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[673]="*Tasmātiha, kumāriyo, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So, girls, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[674]="*‘yo so bhattu abbhantaro antojano dāsāti vā pessāti vā kammakarāti vā, tesaṃ katañca katato jānissāma akatañca akatato jānissāma, gilānakānañca balābalaṃ jānissāma, khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyañcassa paccaṃsena saṃvibhajissāmā’ti.**‘We will know what work our husband’s domestic bondservants, workers, and staff have completed, and what they’ve left incomplete. We will know who is sick, and who is fit or unwell. We will distribute to each a fair portion of various foods.’*";
P_HTM[675]="*Evañhi vo, kumāriyo, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[676]="*Tasmātiha, kumāriyo, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So, girls, you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[677]="*‘yaṃ bhattā āharissati dhanaṃ vā dhaññaṃ vā rajataṃ vā jātarūpaṃ vā, taṃ ārakkhena guttiyā sampādessāma, tattha ca bhavissāma adhuttī athenī asoṇḍī avināsikāyo’ti.**‘We will ensure that any income our husbands earn is guarded and protected, whether money, grain, silver, or gold. We will not overspend, steal, waste, or lose it.’*";
P_HTM[678]="*Evañhi vo, kumāriyo, sikkhitabbaṃ.**That’s how you should train.*";
P_HTM[679]="*Imehi kho, kumāriyo, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato mātugāmo kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā manāpakāyikānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjatīti.**When they have these five qualities, females—when their body breaks up, after death—are reborn in company with the Gods of the Lovable Host.*";
P_HTM[680]="*Yo naṃ bharati sabbadā,**She’d never look down on her husband,*";
P_HTM[681]="*niccaṃ ātāpi ussuko;**who’s always keen to work hard,*";
P_HTM[682]="*Sabbakāmaharaṃ posaṃ,**always looking after her,*";
P_HTM[683]="*bhattāraṃ nātimaññati.**and bringing whatever she wants.*";
P_HTM[684]="*Na cāpi sotthi bhattāraṃ,**And a good woman never scolds her husband*";
P_HTM[685]="*issācārena rosaye;**with jealous words.*";
P_HTM[686]="*Bhattu ca garuno sabbe,**Being astute, she reveres*";
P_HTM[687]="*paṭipūjeti paṇḍitā.**those respected by her husband.*";
P_HTM[688]="*Uṭṭhāhikā analasā,**She gets up early, works tirelessly,*";
P_HTM[689]="*saṅgahitaparijjanā;**and manages the domestic help.*";
P_HTM[690]="*Bhattu manāpaṃ carati,**She’s loveable to her husband,*";
P_HTM[691]="*sambhataṃ anurakkhati.**and preserves his wealth.*";
P_HTM[692]="*Yā evaṃ vattatī nārī,**A lady who fulfills these duties*";
P_HTM[693]="*bhattuchandavasānugā;**according to her husband’s desire,*";
P_HTM[694]="*Manāpā nāma te devā,**is reborn among the gods*";
P_HTM[695]="*yattha sā upapajjatī”ti.**called ‘Loveable’.”*";
P_HTM[696]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[697]="*4. Sīhasenāpatisuttaṃ**With General Sīha*";
P_HTM[698]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[699]="*Atha kho sīho senāpati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sīho senāpati bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then General Sīha went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and asked him,*";
P_HTM[700]="*“sakkā nu kho, bhante, bhagavā sandiṭṭhikaṃ dānaphalaṃ paññāpetun”ti?**“Sir, can you point out a fruit of giving that’s apparent in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[701]="*“Sakkā, sīhā”ti bhagavā avoca:**“I can, Sīha,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[702]="*“dāyako, sīha, dānapati bahuno janassa piyo hoti manāpo.**“A giver, a donor is dear and beloved to many people.*";
P_HTM[703]="*Yampi, sīha, dāyako dānapati bahuno janassa piyo hoti manāpo, idampi sandiṭṭhikaṃ dānaphalaṃ.**This is a fruit of giving that’s apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[704]="*Puna caparaṃ, sīha, dāyakaṃ dānapatiṃ santo sappurisā bhajanti.**Furthermore, good people associate with a giver.*";
P_HTM[705]="*Yampi, sīha, dāyakaṃ dānapatiṃ santo sappurisā bhajanti, idampi sandiṭṭhikaṃ dānaphalaṃ.**This is another fruit of giving that’s apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[706]="*Puna caparaṃ, sīha, dāyakassa dānapatino kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati.**Furthermore, a giver gains a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[707]="*Yampi, sīha, dāyakassa dānapatino kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati, idampi sandiṭṭhikaṃ dānaphalaṃ.**This is another fruit of giving that’s apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[708]="*Puna caparaṃ, sīha, dāyako dānapati yaṃ yadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati—yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ—visārado upasaṅkamati amaṅkubhūto.**Furthermore, a giver enters any kind of assembly bold and assured, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[709]="*Yampi, sīha, dāyako dānapati yaṃ yadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati—yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ—visārado upasaṅkamati amaṅkubhūto, idampi sandiṭṭhikaṃ dānaphalaṃ.**This is another fruit of giving that’s apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[710]="*Puna caparaṃ, sīha, dāyako dānapati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Furthermore, when a giver’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[711]="*Yampi, sīha, dāyako dānapati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati, idaṃ samparāyikaṃ dānaphalan”ti.**This is a fruit of giving to do with lives to come.”*";
P_HTM[712]="*Evaṃ vutte, sīho senāpati bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, General Sīha said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[713]="*“yānimāni, bhante, bhagavatā cattāri sandiṭṭhikāni dānaphalāni akkhātāni, nāhaṃ ettha bhagavato saddhāya gacchāmi; ahaṃ petāni jānāmi.**“When it comes to those four fruits of giving that are apparent in the present life, I don’t have to rely on faith in the Buddha, for I know them too.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Ahaṃ, bhante, dāyako dānapati bahuno janassa piyo manāpo.**I’m a giver, a donor, and am dear and beloved to many people.*";
P_HTM[715]="*Ahaṃ, bhante, dāyako dānapati; maṃ santo sappurisā bhajanti.**I’m a giver, and good people associate with me.*";
P_HTM[716]="*Ahaṃ, bhante, dāyako dānapati; mayhaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato: ‘sīho senāpati dāyako kārako saṅghupaṭṭhāko’ti.**I’m a giver, and I have this good reputation: ‘General Sīha gives, serves, and attends on the Saṅgha.’*";
P_HTM[717]="*Ahaṃ, bhante, dāyako dānapati yaṃ yadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamāmi—yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ—visārado upasaṅkamāmi amaṅkubhūto.**I’m a giver, and I enter any kind of assembly bold and assured, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[718]="*Yānimāni, bhante, bhagavatā cattāri sandiṭṭhikāni dānaphalāni akkhātāni, nāhaṃ ettha bhagavato saddhāya gacchāmi; ahaṃ petāni jānāmi.**When it comes to these four fruits of giving that are apparent in the present life, I don’t have to rely on faith in the Buddha, for I know them too.*";
P_HTM[719]="*Yañca kho maṃ, bhante, bhagavā evamāha:**But when the Buddha says:*";
P_HTM[720]="*‘dāyako, sīha, dānapati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatī’ti, etāhaṃ na jānāmi; ettha ca panāhaṃ bhagavato saddhāya gacchāmī”ti.**‘When a giver’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ I don’t know this, so I have to rely on faith in the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[721]="*“Evametaṃ, sīha, evametaṃ, sīha.**“That’s so true, Sīha! That’s so true!*";
P_HTM[722]="*Dāyako dānapati kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjatīti.**When a giver’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[723]="*Dadaṃ piyo hoti bhajanti naṃ bahū,**Giving, you’re loved and befriended by many people.*";
P_HTM[724]="*Kittiñca pappoti yaso ca vaḍḍhati;**You get a good reputation, and your fame grows.*";
P_HTM[725]="*Amaṅkubhūto parisaṃ vigāhati,**A generous man enters an assembly*";
P_HTM[726]="*Visārado hoti naro amaccharī.**bold and assured.*";
P_HTM[727]="*Tasmā hi dānāni dadanti paṇḍitā,**So an astute person, seeking happiness, would give gifts,*";
P_HTM[728]="*Vineyya maccheramalaṃ sukhesino;**having driven out the stain of stinginess.*";
P_HTM[729]="*Te dīgharattaṃ tidive patiṭṭhitā,**They live long in the heaven of the Three and Thirty,*";
P_HTM[730]="*Devānaṃ sahabyagatā ramanti te.**enjoying the company of the gods.*";
P_HTM[731]="*Katāvakāsā katakusalā ito cutā,**Having taken the opportunity to do good, when they pass from here*";
P_HTM[732]="*Sayaṃpabhā anuvicaranti nandanaṃ;**they wander radiant in the Garden of Delight.*";
P_HTM[733]="*Te tattha nandanti ramanti modare,**There they delight, rejoice, and enjoy themselves,*";
P_HTM[734]="*Samappitā kāmaguṇehi pañcahi;**provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[735]="*Katvāna vākyaṃ asitassa tādino,**Doing what the unattached, the poised one says,*";
P_HTM[736]="*Ramanti sagge sugatassa sāvakā”ti.**disciples of the Holy One rejoice in heaven.”*";
P_HTM[737]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[738]="*5. Dānānisaṃsasuttaṃ**The Benefits of Giving*";
P_HTM[739]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, dāne ānisaṃsā.**“Mendicants, there are five benefits of giving.*";
P_HTM[740]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[741]="*Bahuno janassa piyo hoti manāpo;**A giver, a donor is dear and beloved by many people.*";
P_HTM[742]="*santo sappurisā bhajanti;**Good people associate with them.*";
P_HTM[743]="*kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati;**They get a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[744]="*gihidhammā anapagato hoti;**They don’t neglect a layperson’s duties.*";
P_HTM[745]="*kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[746]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca dāne ānisaṃsāti.**These are the five benefits of giving.*";
P_HTM[747]="*Dadamāno piyo hoti,**Giving, one is loved,*";
P_HTM[748]="*sataṃ dhammaṃ anukkamaṃ;**and follows the way of the good.*";
P_HTM[749]="*Santo naṃ sadā bhajanti,**The good, disciplined spiritual practitioners*";
P_HTM[750]="*saññatā brahmacārayo.**associate with you.*";
P_HTM[751]="*Te tassa dhammaṃ desenti,**They teach you the Dhamma*";
P_HTM[752]="*Sabbadukkhāpanūdanaṃ;**that dispels all suffering.*";
P_HTM[753]="*Yaṃ so dhammaṃ idhaññāya,**Understanding this teaching,*";
P_HTM[754]="*Parinibbāti anāsavo”ti.**you’re extinguished without defilements.”*";
P_HTM[755]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[756]="*6. Kāladānasuttaṃ**Timely Gifts*";
P_HTM[757]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, kāladānāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five timely gifts.*";
P_HTM[758]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[759]="*Āgantukassa dānaṃ deti;**A gift to a visitor.*";
P_HTM[760]="*gamikassa dānaṃ deti;**A gift to someone setting out on a journey.*";
P_HTM[761]="*gilānassa dānaṃ deti;**A gift to someone who is sick.*";
P_HTM[762]="*dubbhikkhe dānaṃ deti;**A gift at a time of famine.*";
P_HTM[763]="*yāni tāni navasassāni navaphalāni tāni paṭhamaṃ sīlavantesu patiṭṭhāpeti.**Presenting the freshly harvested grains and fruits first to those who are ethical.*";
P_HTM[764]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca kāladānānīti.**These are the five timely gifts.*";
P_HTM[765]="*Kāle dadanti sappaññā,**The wise give at the right time,*";
P_HTM[766]="*vadaññū vītamaccharā;**being kind and rid of stinginess.*";
P_HTM[767]="*Kālena dinnaṃ ariyesu,**A religious donation at the right time*";
P_HTM[768]="*ujubhūtesu tādisu.**to the noble ones, upright and poised,*";
P_HTM[769]="*Vippasannamanā tassa,**given with a clear and confident mind,*";
P_HTM[770]="*vipulā hoti dakkhiṇā;**is indeed abundant.*";
P_HTM[771]="*Ye tattha anumodanti,**Those who rejoice at that,*";
P_HTM[772]="*veyyāvaccaṃ karonti vā;**or do other services,*";
P_HTM[773]="*Na tena dakkhiṇā ūnā,**don’t miss out on the offering;*";
P_HTM[774]="*tepi puññassa bhāgino.**they too have a share in the merit.*";
P_HTM[775]="*Tasmā dade appaṭivānacitto,**So you should give without holding back,*";
P_HTM[776]="*Yattha dinnaṃ mahapphalaṃ;**where a gift is very fruitful.*";
P_HTM[777]="*Puññāni paralokasmiṃ,**The good deeds of sentient beings*";
P_HTM[778]="*Patiṭṭhā honti pāṇinan”ti.**support them in the next world.”*";
P_HTM[779]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[780]="*9. Bhojanasuttaṃ**Food*";
P_HTM[781]="*“Bhojanaṃ, bhikkhave, dadamāno dāyako paṭiggāhakānaṃ pañca ṭhānāni deti.**“Mendicants, when a giver gives food, they give the recipients five things.*";
P_HTM[782]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[783]="*Āyuṃ deti, vaṇṇaṃ deti, sukhaṃ deti, balaṃ deti, paṭibhānaṃ deti.**Long life, beauty, happiness, strength, and eloquence.*";
P_HTM[784]="*Āyuṃ kho pana datvā āyussa bhāgī hoti dibbassa vā mānusassa vā;**Giving long life, they have long life as a god or human.*";
P_HTM[785]="*vaṇṇaṃ datvā vaṇṇassa bhāgī hoti dibbassa vā mānusassa vā;**Giving beauty, they have beauty as a god or human.*";
P_HTM[786]="*sukhaṃ datvā sukhassa bhāgī hoti dibbassa vā mānusassa vā;**Giving happiness, they have happiness as a god or human.*";
P_HTM[787]="*balaṃ datvā balassa bhāgī hoti dibbassa vā mānusassa vā;**Giving strength, they have strength as a god or human.*";
P_HTM[788]="*paṭibhānaṃ datvā paṭibhānassa bhāgī hoti dibbassa vā mānusassa vā.**Giving eloquence, they are eloquent as a god or human.*";
P_HTM[789]="*Bhojanaṃ, bhikkhave, dadamāno dāyako paṭiggāhakānaṃ imāni pañca ṭhānāni detīti.**When a giver gives food, they give the recipients five things.*";
P_HTM[790]="*Āyudo balado dhīro,**A wise one is a giver of life, strength,*";
P_HTM[791]="*vaṇṇado paṭibhānado;**beauty, and eloquence.*";
P_HTM[792]="*Sukhassa dātā medhāvī,**An intelligent giver of happiness*";
P_HTM[793]="*sukhaṃ so adhigacchati.**gains happiness in return.*";
P_HTM[794]="*Āyuṃ datvā balaṃ vaṇṇaṃ,**Giving life, strength, beauty,*";
P_HTM[795]="*sukhañca paṭibhānakaṃ;**happiness, and eloquence,*";
P_HTM[796]="*Dīghāyu yasavā hoti,**they’re long-lived and famous*";
P_HTM[797]="*yattha yatthūpapajjatī”ti.**wherever they’re reborn.”*";
P_HTM[798]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[799]="*8. Saddhasuttaṃ**Faith*";
P_HTM[800]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, saddhe kulaputte ānisaṃsā.**“Mendicants, a faithful gentleman gets five benefits.*";
P_HTM[801]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[802]="*Ye te, bhikkhave, loke santo sappurisā te saddhaññeva paṭhamaṃ anukampantā anukampanti, no tathā assaddhaṃ;**The good persons in the world show compassion first to the faithful, not so much to the unfaithful.*";
P_HTM[803]="*saddhaññeva paṭhamaṃ upasaṅkamantā upasaṅkamanti, no tathā assaddhaṃ;**They first approach the faithful, not so much the unfaithful.*";
P_HTM[804]="*saddhaññeva paṭhamaṃ paṭiggaṇhantā paṭiggaṇhanti, no tathā assaddhaṃ;**They first receive alms from the faithful, not so much the unfaithful.*";
P_HTM[805]="*saddhaññeva paṭhamaṃ dhammaṃ desentā desenti, no tathā assaddhaṃ;**They first teach Dhamma to the faithful, not so much the unfaithful.*";
P_HTM[806]="*saddho kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, the faithful are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca saddhe kulaputte ānisaṃsā.**A faithful gentleman gets these five benefits.*";
P_HTM[808]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, subhūmiyaṃ catumahāpathe mahānigrodho samantā pakkhīnaṃ paṭisaraṇaṃ hoti;**Suppose there was a great banyan tree at a level crossroads. It would become a refuge for birds from all around.*";
P_HTM[809]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, saddho kulaputto bahuno janassa paṭisaraṇaṃ hoti bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānanti.**In the same way, a faithful gentleman becomes a refuge for many people—monks, nuns, laywomen, and laymen.*";
P_HTM[810]="*Sākhāpattaphalūpeto,**With its branches, leaves, and fruit,*";
P_HTM[811]="*khandhimāva mahādumo;**a great tree with its strong trunk,*";
P_HTM[812]="*Mūlavā phalasampanno,**firmly-rooted and fruit-bearing,*";
P_HTM[813]="*patiṭṭhā hoti pakkhinaṃ.**supports many birds.*";
P_HTM[814]="*Manorame āyatane,**It’s a lovely place,*";
P_HTM[815]="*sevanti naṃ vihaṅgamā;**frequented by the sky-soarers.*";
P_HTM[816]="*Chāyaṃ chāyatthikā yanti,**Those that need shade go in the shade,*";
P_HTM[817]="*phalatthā phalabhojino.**those that need fruit enjoy the fruit.*";
P_HTM[818]="*Tatheva sīlasampannaṃ,**So too, a faithful individual*";
P_HTM[819]="*saddhaṃ purisapuggalaṃ;**is perfect in ethics,*";
P_HTM[820]="*Nivātavuttiṃ atthaddhaṃ,**humble and kind,*";
P_HTM[821]="*sorataṃ sakhilaṃ muduṃ.**sweet, friendly, and tender.*";
P_HTM[822]="*Vītarāgā vītadosā,**Those free of greed, freed of hate,*";
P_HTM[823]="*vītamohā anāsavā;**free of delusion, undefiled,*";
P_HTM[824]="*Puññakkhettāni lokasmiṃ,**fields of merit for the world,*";
P_HTM[825]="*sevanti tādisaṃ naraṃ.**associate with such a person.*";
P_HTM[826]="*Te tassa dhammaṃ desenti,**They teach them the Dhamma,*";
P_HTM[827]="*Sabbadukkhāpanūdanaṃ;**that dispels all suffering.*";
P_HTM[828]="*Yaṃ so dhammaṃ idhaññāya,**Understanding this teaching,*";
P_HTM[829]="*Parinibbāti anāsavo”ti.**they’re extinguished without defilements.”*";
P_HTM[830]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[831]="*9. Puttasuttaṃ**A Child*";
P_HTM[832]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, ṭhānāni sampassantā mātāpitaro puttaṃ icchanti kule jāyamānaṃ.**“Mendicants, parents see five reasons to wish for the birth of a child in the family.*";
P_HTM[833]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[834]="*Bhato vā no bharissati;**Since we looked after them, they’ll look after us.*";
P_HTM[835]="*kiccaṃ vā no karissati;**They’ll do their duty for us.*";
P_HTM[836]="*kulavaṃso ciraṃ ṭhassati;**The family traditions will last.*";
P_HTM[837]="*dāyajjaṃ paṭipajjissati;**They’ll take care of the inheritance.*";
P_HTM[838]="*atha vā pana petānaṃ kālaṅkatānaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ anuppadassatīti.**Or else when we have passed away they’ll give an offering on our behalf.*";
P_HTM[839]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca ṭhānāni sampassantā mātāpitaro puttaṃ icchanti kule jāyamānanti.**Parents see these five reasons to wish for the birth of a child in the family.*";
P_HTM[840]="*Pañca ṭhānāni sampassaṃ,**Seeing five reasons,*";
P_HTM[841]="*puttaṃ icchanti paṇḍitā;**astute people wish for a child.*";
P_HTM[842]="*Bhato vā no bharissati,**Since we looked after them, they’ll look after us.*";
P_HTM[843]="*kiccaṃ vā no karissati.**They’ll do their duty for us.*";
P_HTM[844]="*Kulavaṃso ciraṃ tiṭṭhe,**The family traditions will last.*";
P_HTM[845]="*dāyajjaṃ paṭipajjati;**They’ll take care of the inheritance.*";
P_HTM[846]="*Atha vā pana petānaṃ,**Or else when we have passed away*";
P_HTM[847]="*dakkhiṇaṃ anuppadassati.**they’ll give an offering on our behalf.*";
P_HTM[848]="*Ṭhānānetāni sampassaṃ,**Seeing these five reasons*";
P_HTM[849]="*puttaṃ icchanti paṇḍitā;**astute people wish for a child.*";
P_HTM[850]="*Tasmā santo sappurisā,**And so good people,*";
P_HTM[851]="*kataññū katavedino.**grateful and thankful,*";
P_HTM[852]="*Bharanti mātāpitaro,**look after their parents,*";
P_HTM[853]="*pubbe katamanussaraṃ;**remembering what was done for them in the past.*";
P_HTM[854]="*Karonti nesaṃ kiccāni,**They do for their parents,*";
P_HTM[855]="*yathā taṃ pubbakārinaṃ.**as their parents did for them in the past.*";
P_HTM[856]="*Ovādakārī bhataposī,**Following their advice, looking after those who raised them,*";
P_HTM[857]="*kulavaṃsaṃ ahāpayaṃ;**the family traditions are not lost.*";
P_HTM[858]="*Saddho sīlena sampanno,**Faithful, accomplished in ethics,*";
P_HTM[859]="*putto hoti pasaṃsiyo”ti.**such a child is praiseworthy.”*";
P_HTM[860]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[861]="*10. Mahāsālaputtasuttaṃ**Great Sal Trees*";
P_HTM[862]="*“Himavantaṃ, bhikkhave, pabbatarājaṃ nissāya mahāsālā pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhanti.**“Mendicants, great sal trees grow in five ways supported by the Himalayas, the king of mountains.*";
P_HTM[863]="*Katamāhi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[864]="*Sākhāpattapalāsena vaḍḍhanti;**The branches, leaves, and foliage;*";
P_HTM[865]="*tacena vaḍḍhanti;**the bark;*";
P_HTM[866]="*papaṭikāya vaḍḍhanti;**the shoots;*";
P_HTM[867]="*pheggunā vaḍḍhanti;**the softwood;*";
P_HTM[868]="*sārena vaḍḍhanti.**and the hardwood.*";
P_HTM[869]="*Himavantaṃ, bhikkhave, pabbatarājaṃ nissāya mahāsālā imāhi pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhanti.**Great sal trees grow in these five ways supported by the Himalayas, the king of mountains.*";
P_HTM[870]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, saddhaṃ kulaputtaṃ nissāya antojano pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhati.**In the same way, a family grows in five ways supported by a family head with faith.*";
P_HTM[871]="*Katamāhi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[872]="*Saddhāya vaḍḍhati;**Faith,*";
P_HTM[873]="*sīlena vaḍḍhati;**ethics,*";
P_HTM[874]="*sutena vaḍḍhati;**learning,*";
P_HTM[875]="*cāgena vaḍḍhati;**generosity,*";
P_HTM[876]="*paññāya vaḍḍhati.**and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[877]="*Saddhaṃ, bhikkhave, kulaputtaṃ nissāya antojano imāhi pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhatīti.**A family grows in these five ways supported by a family head with faith.*";
P_HTM[878]="*Yathā hi pabbato selo,**Supported by the mountain crags*";
P_HTM[879]="*araññasmiṃ brahāvane;**in the wilds, the formidable forest,*";
P_HTM[880]="*Taṃ rukkhā upanissāya,**the tree grows*";
P_HTM[881]="*vaḍḍhante te vanappatī.**to become lord of the forest.*";
P_HTM[882]="*Tatheva sīlasampannaṃ,**So too, when the family head*";
P_HTM[883]="*Saddhaṃ kulaputtaṃ imaṃ;**is ethical and faithful,*";
P_HTM[884]="*Upanissāya vaḍḍhanti,**supported by them, they grow:*";
P_HTM[885]="*Puttadārā ca bandhavā;**children, partners, and kin,*";
P_HTM[886]="*Amaccā ñātisaṅghā ca,**colleagues, relatives,*";
P_HTM[887]="*Ye cassa anujīvino.**and those dependent for their livelihood.*";
P_HTM[888]="*Tyassa sīlavato sīlaṃ,**Seeing the ethical conduct of the virtuous,*";
P_HTM[889]="*cāgaṃ sucaritāni ca;**the generosity and good deeds,*";
P_HTM[890]="*Passamānānukubbanti,**those who see clearly*";
P_HTM[891]="*ye bhavanti vicakkhaṇā.**do likewise.*";
P_HTM[892]="*Idha dhammaṃ caritvāna,**Having practiced the teaching here,*";
P_HTM[893]="*maggaṃ sugatigāminaṃ;**the path that goes to a good place,*";
P_HTM[894]="*Nandino devalokasmiṃ,**they delight in the heavenly realm,*";
P_HTM[895]="*modanti kāmakāmino”ti.**enjoying all the pleasures they desire.”*";
P_HTM[896]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[897]="*Sumanavaggo catuttho.* **";
P_HTM[898]="*Sumanā cundī uggaho,* **";
P_HTM[899]="*sīho dānānisaṃsako;* **";
P_HTM[900]="*Kālabhojanasaddhā ca,* **";
P_HTM[901]="*puttasālehi te dasāti.* **";
P_HTM[902]="*13. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**With King Muṇḍa*";
P_HTM[903]="*1. Ādiyasuttaṃ**Getting Rich*";
P_HTM[904]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[905]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then the householder Anāthapiṇḍika went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[906]="*“pañcime, gahapati, bhogānaṃ ādiyā.**“Householder, there are these five reasons to get rich.*";
P_HTM[907]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[908]="*Idha, gahapati, ariyasāvako uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti sammā sukhaṃ pariharati;**Firstly, with his legitimate wealth—earned by his efforts and initiative, built up with his own hands, gathered by the sweat of the brow—he makes himself happy and pleased, keeping himself properly happy.*";
P_HTM[909]="*mātāpitaro sukheti pīṇeti sammā sukhaṃ pariharati;**He makes his mother and father happy …*";
P_HTM[910]="*puttadāradāsakammakaraporise sukheti pīṇeti sammā sukhaṃ pariharati.**He makes his children, partners, bondservants, workers, and staff happy …*";
P_HTM[911]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo bhogānaṃ ādiyo.**This is the first reason to get rich.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, ariyasāvako uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi mittāmacce sukheti pīṇeti sammā sukhaṃ pariharati.**Furthermore, with his legitimate wealth he makes his friends and colleagues happy …*";
P_HTM[913]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo bhogānaṃ ādiyo.**This is the second reason to get rich.*";
P_HTM[914]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, ariyasāvako uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi yā tā honti āpadā—**Furthermore, with his legitimate wealth he protects himself against losses from such things as fire, water, kings, bandits, or unloved heirs.*";
P_HTM[915]="*aggito vā udakato vā rājato vā corato vā appiyato vā dāyādato—* **";
P_HTM[916]="*tathārūpāsu āpadāsu bhogehi pariyodhāya vattati, sotthiṃ attānaṃ karoti.**He keeps himself safe.*";
P_HTM[917]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo bhogānaṃ ādiyo.**This is the third reason to get rich.*";
P_HTM[918]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, ariyasāvako uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi pañcabaliṃ kattā hoti.**Furthermore, with his legitimate wealth he makes five spirit-offerings:*";
P_HTM[919]="*Ñātibaliṃ, atithibaliṃ, pubbapetabaliṃ, rājabaliṃ, devatābaliṃ—**to relatives, guests, ancestors, king, and deities.*";
P_HTM[920]="*ayaṃ catuttho bhogānaṃ ādiyo.**This is the fourth reason to get rich.*";
P_HTM[921]="*Puna caparaṃ, gahapati, ariyasāvako uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā madappamādā paṭiviratā khantisoracce niviṭṭhā ekamattānaṃ damenti ekamattānaṃ samenti ekamattānaṃ parinibbāpenti, tathārūpesu samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhāpeti sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikaṃ.**Furthermore, with his legitimate wealth he establishes an uplifting religious donation for ascetics and brahmins—those who avoid intoxication and negligence, are settled in patience and gentleness, and who tame, calm, and extinguish themselves—that’s conducive to heaven, ripens in happiness, and leads to heaven.*";
P_HTM[922]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo bhogānaṃ ādiyo.**This is the fifth reason to get rich.*";
P_HTM[923]="*Ime kho, gahapati, pañca bhogānaṃ ādiyā.**These are the five reasons to get rich.*";
P_HTM[924]="*Tassa ce, gahapati, ariyasāvakassa ime pañca bhogānaṃ ādiye ādiyato bhogā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti, tassa evaṃ hoti:**Now if the riches a noble disciple gets for these five reasons run out, he thinks:*";
P_HTM[925]="*‘ye vata bhogānaṃ ādiyā te cāhaṃ ādiyāmi bhogā ca me parikkhayaṃ gacchantī’ti.**‘So, the riches I have obtained for these reasons are running out.’*";
P_HTM[926]="*Itissa hoti avippaṭisāro.**And so he has no regrets.*";
P_HTM[927]="*Tassa ce, gahapati, ariyasāvakassa ime pañca bhogānaṃ ādiye ādiyato bhogā abhivaḍḍhanti, tassa evaṃ hoti:**But if the riches a noble disciple gets for these five reasons increase, he thinks:*";
P_HTM[928]="*‘ye vata bhogānaṃ ādiyā te cāhaṃ ādiyāmi bhogā ca me abhivaḍḍhantī’ti.**‘So, the riches I have obtained for these reasons are increasing.’*";
P_HTM[929]="*Itissa hoti ubhayeneva avippaṭisāroti.**And so he has no regrets in both cases.*";
P_HTM[930]="*Bhuttā bhogā bhatā bhaccā,**‘I’ve enjoyed my wealth, supporting those who depend on me;*";
P_HTM[931]="*vitiṇṇā āpadāsu me;**I’ve overcome losses;*";
P_HTM[932]="*Uddhaggā dakkhiṇā dinnā,**I’ve given uplifting religious donations;*";
P_HTM[933]="*atho pañcabalīkatā;**and made the five spirit-offerings.*";
P_HTM[934]="*Upaṭṭhitā sīlavanto,**I have looked after the ethical and*";
P_HTM[935]="*saññatā brahmacārayo.**disciplined spiritual practitioners.*";
P_HTM[936]="*Yadatthaṃ bhogaṃ iccheyya,**I’ve achieved the purpose*";
P_HTM[937]="*paṇḍito gharamāvasaṃ;**for which an astute lay person*";
P_HTM[938]="*So me attho anuppatto,**wishes to gain wealth.*";
P_HTM[939]="*kataṃ ananutāpiyaṃ.**I don’t regret what I’ve done.’*";
P_HTM[940]="*Etaṃ anussaraṃ macco,**A mortal person who recollects this*";
P_HTM[941]="*ariyadhamme ṭhito naro;**stands firm in the teaching of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[942]="*Idheva naṃ pasaṃsanti,**They’re praised in this life by the astute,*";
P_HTM[943]="*pecca sagge pamodatī”ti.**and they depart to rejoice in heaven.”*";
P_HTM[944]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[945]="*2. Sappurisasuttaṃ**A Good Person*";
P_HTM[946]="*“Sappuriso, bhikkhave, kule jāyamāno bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**“Mendicants, a good person is born in a family for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[947]="*mātāpitūnaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**For the benefit, welfare, and happiness of mother and father;*";
P_HTM[948]="*puttadārassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**children and partners;*";
P_HTM[949]="*dāsakammakaraporisassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**bondservants, workers, and staff;*";
P_HTM[950]="*mittāmaccānaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**friends and colleagues;*";
P_HTM[951]="*samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti.**and ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[952]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāmegho sabbasassāni sampādento bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**It’s like a great rain cloud, which nourishes all the crops for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[953]="*evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, sappuriso kule jāyamāno bahuno janassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;**In the same way, a good person is born in a family for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of the people. …*";
P_HTM[954]="*mātāpitūnaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;* **";
P_HTM[955]="*puttadārassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;* **";
P_HTM[956]="*dāsakammakaraporisassa atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;* **";
P_HTM[957]="*mittāmaccānaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hoti;* **";
P_HTM[958]="*samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ atthāya hitāya sukhāya hotīti.* **";
P_HTM[959]="*Hito bahunnaṃ paṭipajja bhoge,**The gods protect one who is guarded by principle,*";
P_HTM[960]="*Taṃ devatā rakkhati dhammaguttaṃ;**who uses their wealth for the welfare of the many.*";
P_HTM[961]="*Bahussutaṃ sīlavatūpapannaṃ,**One who is learned, with precepts and observances intact,*";
P_HTM[962]="*Dhamme ṭhitaṃ na vijahati kitti.**and steady in principle, doesn’t lose their reputation.*";
P_HTM[963]="*Dhammaṭṭhaṃ sīlasampannaṃ,**Firm in principle, accomplished in ethical conduct,*";
P_HTM[964]="*saccavādiṃ hirīmanaṃ;**truthful, conscientious,*";
P_HTM[965]="*Nekkhaṃ jambonadasseva,**like a coin of mountain gold:*";
P_HTM[966]="*ko taṃ ninditumarahati;**who is worthy of criticizing them?*";
P_HTM[967]="*Devāpi naṃ pasaṃsanti,**Even the gods praise them,*";
P_HTM[968]="*brahmunāpi pasaṃsito”ti.**and by Brahmā, too, they’re praised.”*";
P_HTM[969]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[970]="*3. Iṭṭhasuttaṃ**Likable*";
P_HTM[971]="*Atha kho anāthapiṇḍiko gahapati yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho anāthapiṇḍikaṃ gahapatiṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then the householder Anāthapiṇḍika went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. The Buddha said to him:*";
P_HTM[972]="*“Pañcime, gahapati, dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā dullabhā lokasmiṃ.**“Householder, these five things that are likable, desirable, and agreeable are hard to get in the world.*";
P_HTM[973]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[974]="*Āyu, gahapati, iṭṭho kanto manāpo dullabho lokasmiṃ;**Long life,*";
P_HTM[975]="*vaṇṇo iṭṭho kanto manāpo dullabho lokasmiṃ;**beauty,*";
P_HTM[976]="*sukhaṃ iṭṭhaṃ kantaṃ manāpaṃ dullabhaṃ lokasmiṃ;**happiness,*";
P_HTM[977]="*yaso iṭṭho kanto manāpo dullabho lokasmiṃ;**fame,*";
P_HTM[978]="*saggā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā dullabhā lokasmiṃ.**and heaven.*";
P_HTM[979]="*Ime kho, gahapati, pañca dhammā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā dullabhā lokasmiṃ.**These are the five things that are likable, desirable, and agreeable, but hard to get in the world.*";
P_HTM[980]="*Imesaṃ kho, gahapati, pañcannaṃ dhammānaṃ iṭṭhānaṃ kantānaṃ manāpānaṃ dullabhānaṃ lokasmiṃ na āyācanahetu vā patthanāhetu vā paṭilābhaṃ vadāmi.**And I say that these five things are not got by praying or wishing for them.*";
P_HTM[981]="*Imesaṃ kho, gahapati, pañcannaṃ dhammānaṃ iṭṭhānaṃ kantānaṃ manāpānaṃ dullabhānaṃ lokasmiṃ āyācanahetu vā patthanāhetu vā paṭilābho abhavissa, ko idha kena hāyetha?**If they were, who would lack them?*";
P_HTM[982]="*Na kho, gahapati, arahati ariyasāvako āyukāmo āyuṃ āyācituṃ vā abhinandituṃ vā āyussa vāpi hetu.**A noble disciple who wants to live long ought not pray for it, or hope for it, or pine for it.*";
P_HTM[983]="*Āyukāmena, gahapati, ariyasāvakena āyusaṃvattanikā paṭipadā paṭipajjitabbā.**Instead, they should practice the way that leads to long life.*";
P_HTM[984]="*Āyusaṃvattanikā hissa paṭipadā paṭipannā āyupaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**For by practicing that way they gain long life*";
P_HTM[985]="*So lābhī hoti āyussa dibbassa vā mānusassa vā.**as a god or a human being.*";
P_HTM[986]="*Na kho, gahapati, arahati ariyasāvako vaṇṇakāmo vaṇṇaṃ āyācituṃ vā abhinandituṃ vā vaṇṇassa vāpi hetu.**A noble disciple who wants to be beautiful ought not pray for it, or hope for it, or pine for it.*";
P_HTM[987]="*Vaṇṇakāmena, gahapati, ariyasāvakena vaṇṇasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā paṭipajjitabbā.**Instead, they should practice the way that leads to beauty.*";
P_HTM[988]="*Vaṇṇasaṃvattanikā hissa paṭipadā paṭipannā vaṇṇapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**For by practicing that way they gain beauty*";
P_HTM[989]="*So lābhī hoti vaṇṇassa dibbassa vā mānusassa vā.**as a god or a human being.*";
P_HTM[990]="*Na kho, gahapati, arahati ariyasāvako sukhakāmo sukhaṃ āyācituṃ vā abhinandituṃ vā sukhassa vāpi hetu.**A noble disciple who wants to be happy ought not pray for it, or hope for it, or pine for it.*";
P_HTM[991]="*Sukhakāmena, gahapati, ariyasāvakena sukhasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā paṭipajjitabbā.**Instead, they should practice the way that leads to happiness.*";
P_HTM[992]="*Sukhasaṃvattanikā hissa paṭipadā paṭipannā sukhapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**For by practicing that way they gain happiness*";
P_HTM[993]="*So lābhī hoti sukhassa dibbassa vā mānusassa vā.**as a god or a human being.*";
P_HTM[994]="*Na kho, gahapati, arahati ariyasāvako yasakāmo yasaṃ āyācituṃ vā abhinandituṃ vā yasassa vāpi hetu.**A noble disciple who wants to be famous ought not pray for it, or hope for it, or pine for it.*";
P_HTM[995]="*Yasakāmena, gahapati, ariyasāvakena yasasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā paṭipajjitabbā.**Instead, they should practice the way that leads to fame.*";
P_HTM[996]="*Yasasaṃvattanikā hissa paṭipadā paṭipannā yasapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**For by practicing that way they gain fame*";
P_HTM[997]="*So lābhī hoti yasassa dibbassa vā mānusassa vā.**as a god or a human being.*";
P_HTM[998]="*Na kho, gahapati, arahati ariyasāvako saggakāmo saggaṃ āyācituṃ vā abhinandituṃ vā saggānaṃ vāpi hetu.**A noble disciple who wants to go to heaven ought not pray for it, or hope for it, or pine for it.*";
P_HTM[999]="*Saggakāmena, gahapati, ariyasāvakena saggasaṃvattanikā paṭipadā paṭipajjitabbā.**Instead, they should practice the way that leads to heaven.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*Saggasaṃvattanikā hissa paṭipadā paṭipannā saggapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**For by practicing that way they gain heaven,*";
P_HTM[1001]="*So lābhī hoti saggānanti.**they are one who gains the heavens.*";
P_HTM[1002]="*Āyuṃ vaṇṇaṃ yasaṃ kittiṃ,**For one who desires a continuous flow*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Saggaṃ uccākulīnataṃ;**of exceptional delights—*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Ratiyo patthayānena,**long life, beauty, fame and reputation,*";
P_HTM[1005]="*Uḷārā aparāparā.**heaven, and birth in an eminent family—*";
P_HTM[1006]="*Appamādaṃ pasaṃsanti,**the astute praise diligence*";
P_HTM[1007]="*puññakiriyāsu paṇḍitā;**in making merit.*";
P_HTM[1008]="*Appamatto ubho atthe,**Being diligent, an astute person*";
P_HTM[1009]="*adhigaṇhāti paṇḍito.**secures both benefits:*";
P_HTM[1010]="*Diṭṭhe dhamme ca yo attho,**the benefit in this life,*";
P_HTM[1011]="*yo cattho samparāyiko;**and in lives to come.*";
P_HTM[1012]="*Atthābhisamayā dhīro,**A wise one, comprehending the meaning,*";
P_HTM[1013]="*paṇḍitoti pavuccatī”ti.**is called ‘astute’.”*";
P_HTM[1014]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1015]="*4. Manāpadāyīsuttaṃ**Agreeable*";
P_HTM[1016]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[1017]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya yena uggassa gahapatino vesālikassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of the householder Ugga of Vesālī, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Atha kho uggo gahapati vesāliko yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho uggo gahapati vesāliko bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ugga went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1019]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1020]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.**‘The giver of the agreeable gets the agreeable.’*";
P_HTM[1021]="*Manāpaṃ me, bhante, sālapupphakaṃ khādanīyaṃ;**My sal flower porridge is agreeable:*";
P_HTM[1022]="*taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**may the Buddha please accept it from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1023]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted it out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**“Sir, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1025]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.**‘The giver of the agreeable gets the agreeable.’*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Manāpaṃ me, bhante, sampannakolakaṃ sūkaramaṃsaṃ;**My pork with jujube is agreeable:*";
P_HTM[1027]="*taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**may the Buddha please accept it from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted it out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1029]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1030]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1031]="*Manāpaṃ me, bhante, nibbattatelakaṃ nāliyasākaṃ;**“… My fried vegetable stalks are agreeable:*";
P_HTM[1032]="*taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**may the Buddha please accept them from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1033]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted them out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1034]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1035]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1036]="*Manāpo me, bhante, sālīnaṃ odano vicitakāḷako anekasūpo anekabyañjano;**“… My boiled fine rice with the dark grains picked out, served with many soups and sauces is agreeable:*";
P_HTM[1037]="*taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**may the Buddha please accept it from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted it out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1040]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1041]="*Manāpāni me, bhante, kāsikāni vatthāni;**“… My cloths imported from Kāsī are agreeable:*";
P_HTM[1042]="*tāni me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**may the Buddha please accept them from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1043]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted them out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1044]="*“Sammukhā metaṃ, bhante, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1045]="*‘manāpadāyī labhate manāpan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1046]="*Manāpo me, bhante, pallaṅko gonakatthato paṭalikatthato kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇo sauttaracchado ubhatolohitakūpadhāno.**“… My couch spread with woolen covers—shag-piled or embroidered with flowers—and spread with a fine deer hide, with a canopy above and red pillows at both ends is agreeable.*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Api ca, bhante, mayampetaṃ jānāma:**But, sir, I know that*";
P_HTM[1048]="*‘netaṃ bhagavato kappatī’ti.**this is not proper for the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Idaṃ me, bhante, candanaphalakaṃ agghati adhikasatasahassaṃ;**However, this plank of sandalwood is worth over a thousand dollars.*";
P_HTM[1050]="*taṃ me bhagavā paṭiggaṇhātu anukampaṃ upādāyā”ti.**May the Buddha please accept it from me out of compassion.”*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Paṭiggahesi bhagavā anukampaṃ upādāya.**So the Buddha accepted it out of compassion.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Atha kho bhagavā uggaṃ gahapatiṃ vesālikaṃ iminā anumodanīyena anumodi:**And then the Buddha rejoiced with Ugga with these verses of appreciation:*";
P_HTM[1053]="*“Manāpadāyī labhate manāpaṃ,**“The giver of the agreeable gets the agreeable,*";
P_HTM[1054]="*Yo ujjubhūtesu dadāti chandasā;**enthusiastically giving clothing, bedding,*";
P_HTM[1055]="*Acchādanaṃ sayanamannapānaṃ,**food and drink, and various requisites*";
P_HTM[1056]="*Nānāppakārāni ca paccayāni.**to those of upright conduct.*";
P_HTM[1057]="*Cattañca muttañca anuggahītaṃ,**Knowing the perfected ones to be like a field*";
P_HTM[1058]="*Khettūpame arahante viditvā;**for what’s given, offered and not held back,*";
P_HTM[1059]="*So duccajaṃ sappuriso cajitvā,**a good person gives what’s hard to give:*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Manāpadāyī labhate manāpan”ti.**the giver of the agreeable gets the agreeable.”*";
P_HTM[1061]="*Atha kho bhagavā uggaṃ gahapatiṃ vesālikaṃ iminā anumodanīyena anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**And then the Buddha, having rejoiced with Ugga with these verses of appreciation, got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*Atha kho uggo gahapati vesāliko aparena samayena kālamakāsi.**Then after some time Ugga passed away,*";
P_HTM[1063]="*Kālaṅkato ca uggo gahapati vesāliko aññataraṃ manomayaṃ kāyaṃ upapajji.**and was reborn in a host of mind-made gods.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Tena kho pana samayena bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At that time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1065]="*Atha kho uggo devaputto abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇo kevalakappaṃ jetavanaṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitaṃ kho uggaṃ devaputtaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**Then, late at night, the glorious god Ugga, lighting up the entire Jeta’s Grove, went up to the Buddha, bowed, and stood to one side. The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1066]="*“kacci te, ugga, yathādhippāyo”ti?**“Ugga, I trust it is all you wished?”*";
P_HTM[1067]="*“Taggha me, bhagavā, yathādhippāyo”ti.**“Sir, it is indeed just as I wished.”*";
P_HTM[1068]="*Atha kho bhagavā uggaṃ devaputtaṃ gāthāhi ajjhabhāsi:**Then the Buddha addressed Ugga in verse:*";
P_HTM[1069]="*“Manāpadāyī labhate manāpaṃ,**“The giver of the agreeable gets the agreeable,*";
P_HTM[1070]="*Aggassa dātā labhate punaggaṃ;**the giver of the foremost gets the foremost,*";
P_HTM[1071]="*Varassa dātā varalābhi hoti,**the giver of the excellent gets the excellent,*";
P_HTM[1072]="*Seṭṭhaṃ dado seṭṭhamupeti ṭhānaṃ.**the giver of the best gets the best.*";
P_HTM[1073]="*Yo aggadāyī varadāyī,**A person who gives the foremost,*";
P_HTM[1074]="*seṭṭhadāyī ca yo naro;**the excellent, the best:*";
P_HTM[1075]="*Dīghāyu yasavā hoti,**they’re long-lived and famous*";
P_HTM[1076]="*yattha yatthūpapajjatī”ti.**wherever they’re reborn.”*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1078]="*5. Puññābhisandasuttaṃ**Overflowing Merit*";
P_HTM[1079]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1081]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cīvaraṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**When a mendicant enters and remains in a limitless immersion of heart while using a robe …*";
P_HTM[1082]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu piṇḍapātaṃ paribhuñjamāno … pe … yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vihāraṃ paribhuñjamāno … pe … yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu mañcapīṭhaṃ paribhuñjamāno … pe ….**alms-food … lodging … bed and chair …*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Yassa, bhikkhave, bhikkhu gilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhāraṃ paribhuñjamāno appamāṇaṃ cetosamādhiṃ upasampajja viharati, appamāṇo tassa puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattati.**medicines and supplies for the sick, the overflowing of merit for the donor is limitless …*";
P_HTM[1084]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca puññābhisandā kusalābhisandā sukhassāhārā sovaggikā sukhavipākā saggasaṃvattanikā iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattanti.**These are the five kinds of overflowing merit, overflowing goodness. They nurture happiness, and are conducive to heaven, ripening in happiness, and leading to heaven. They lead to what is likable, desirable, agreeable, to welfare and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Imehi ca pana, bhikkhave, pañcahi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ:**When a noble disciple has these five kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to grasp how much merit they have by saying that*";
P_HTM[1086]="*‘ettako puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattatī’ti.**this is the extent of their overflowing merit … that leads to happiness.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Atha kho asaṅkheyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[1088]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, mahāsamudde na sukaraṃ udakassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ:**It’s like trying to grasp how much water is in the ocean. It’s not easy to say:*";
P_HTM[1089]="*‘ettakāni udakāḷhakānīti vā ettakāni udakāḷhakasatānīti vā ettakāni udakāḷhakasahassānīti vā ettakāni udakāḷhakasatasahassānīti vā;**‘This is how many gallons, how many hundreds, thousands, hundreds of thousands of gallons there are.’*";
P_HTM[1090]="*atha kho asaṅkheyyo appameyyo mahāudakakkhandhotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchati’.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of water.*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, imehi pañcahi puññābhisandehi kusalābhisandehi samannāgatassa ariyasāvakassa na sukaraṃ puññassa pamāṇaṃ gahetuṃ:**In the same way, when a noble disciple has these five kinds of overflowing merit and goodness, it’s not easy to grasp how much merit they have:*";
P_HTM[1092]="*‘ettako puññābhisando kusalābhisando sukhassāhāro sovaggiko sukhavipāko saggasaṃvattaniko iṭṭhāya kantāya manāpāya hitāya sukhāya saṃvattatī’ti.**‘This is how much this overflowing merit … leads to happiness.’*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Atha kho asaṅkheyyo appameyyo mahāpuññakkhandhotveva saṅkhaṃ gacchatīti.**It’s simply reckoned as an incalculable, immeasurable, great mass of merit.*";
P_HTM[1094]="*Mahodadhiṃ aparimitaṃ mahāsaraṃ,**Hosts of people use the rivers,*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Bahubheravaṃ ratnagaṇānamālayaṃ;**and though the rivers are many,*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Najjo yathā naragaṇasaṅghasevitā,**all reach the great deep, the boundless ocean,*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Puthū savantī upayanti sāgaraṃ.**the cruel sea that’s home to precious gems.*";
P_HTM[1098]="*Evaṃ naraṃ annadapānavatthadaṃ,**So too, when a person gives food, drink, and clothes;*";
P_HTM[1099]="*Seyyānisajjattharaṇassa dāyakaṃ;**and they’re a giver of beds, seats, and mats—*";
P_HTM[1100]="*Puññassa dhārā upayanti paṇḍitaṃ,**the streams of merit reach that astute person,*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Najjo yathā vārivahāva sāgaran”ti.**as the rivers bring their waters to the sea.”*";
P_HTM[1102]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1103]="*6. Sampadāsuttaṃ**Success*";
P_HTM[1104]="*“Pañcimā, bhikkhave, sampadā.**“Mendicants, there are five accomplishments.*";
P_HTM[1105]="*Katamā pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1106]="*Saddhāsampadā, sīlasampadā, sutasampadā, cāgasampadā, paññāsampadā—**Accomplishment in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1107]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, pañca sampadā”ti.**These are the five accomplishments.”*";
P_HTM[1108]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1109]="*7. Dhanasuttaṃ**Wealth*";
P_HTM[1110]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, dhanāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five kinds of wealth.*";
P_HTM[1111]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Saddhādhanaṃ, sīladhanaṃ, sutadhanaṃ, cāgadhanaṃ, paññādhanaṃ.**The wealth of faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, saddhādhanaṃ?**And what is the wealth of faith?*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a noble disciple has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[1115]="*‘itipi so bhagavā … pe … satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, saddhādhanaṃ.**This is called the wealth of faith.*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, sīladhanaṃ?**And what is the wealth of ethics?*";
P_HTM[1118]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti … pe … surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti.**It’s when a noble disciple doesn’t kill living creatures, steal, commit sexual misconduct, lie, or take alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.*";
P_HTM[1119]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sīladhanaṃ.**This is called the wealth of ethics.*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, sutadhanaṃ?**And what is the wealth of learning?*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako bahussuto hoti … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdho.**It’s when a noble disciple is very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s totally full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reciting them, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, sutadhanaṃ.**This is called the wealth of learning.*";
P_HTM[1123]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, cāgadhanaṃ?**And what is the wealth of generosity?*";
P_HTM[1124]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako vigatamalamaccherena cetasā agāraṃ ajjhāvasati muttacāgo payatapāṇi vosaggarato yācayogo dānasaṃvibhāgarato.**It’s when a noble disciple lives at home rid of the stain of stinginess, freely generous, open-handed, loving to let go, committed to charity, loving to give and to share.*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, cāgadhanaṃ.**This is called the wealth of generosity.*";
P_HTM[1126]="*Katamañca, bhikkhave, paññādhanaṃ?**And what is the wealth of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako paññavā hoti, udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**It’s when a noble disciple is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Idaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, paññādhanaṃ.**This is called the wealth of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca dhanānīti.**These are the five kinds of wealth.*";
P_HTM[1130]="*Yassa saddhā tathāgate,**Whoever has faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[1131]="*acalā suppatiṭṭhitā;**unwavering and well grounded;*";
P_HTM[1132]="*Sīlañca yassa kalyāṇaṃ,**whose ethical conduct is good,*";
P_HTM[1133]="*ariyakantaṃ pasaṃsitaṃ.**praised and loved by the noble ones;*";
P_HTM[1134]="*Saṅghe pasādo yassatthi,**who has confidence in the Saṅgha,*";
P_HTM[1135]="*ujubhūtañca dassanaṃ;**and correct view:*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Adaliddoti taṃ āhu,**they’re said to be prosperous,*";
P_HTM[1137]="*amoghaṃ tassa jīvitaṃ.**their life is not in vain.*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Tasmā saddhañca sīlañca,**So let the wise devote themselves*";
P_HTM[1139]="*pasādaṃ dhammadassanaṃ;**to faith, ethical behavior,*";
P_HTM[1140]="*Anuyuñjetha medhāvī,**confidence, and insight into the teaching,*";
P_HTM[1141]="*saraṃ buddhāna sāsanan”ti.**remembering the instructions of the Buddhas.”*";
P_HTM[1142]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1143]="*8. Alabbhanīyaṭhānasuttaṃ**Things That Cannot Be Had*";
P_HTM[1144]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, alabbhanīyāni ṭhānāni samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**“Mendicants, there are five things that cannot be had by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[1145]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1146]="*‘Jarādhammaṃ mā jīrī’ti alabbhanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**That someone liable to old age should not grow old.*";
P_HTM[1147]="*‘Byādhidhammaṃ mā byādhīyī’ti … pe … ‘maraṇadhammaṃ mā mīyī’ti … ‘khayadhammaṃ mā khīyī’ti … ‘nassanadhammaṃ mā nassī’ti alabbhanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**That someone liable to sickness should not get sick. … That someone liable to death should not die. … That someone liable to ending should not end. … That someone liable to perishing should not perish. …*";
P_HTM[1148]="*Assutavato, bhikkhave, puthujjanassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**An uneducated ordinary person has someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe na iti paṭisañcikkhati:**But they don’t reflect:*";
P_HTM[1150]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to old age who grows old. For as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn, they all have someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1151]="*Ahañceva kho pana jarādhamme jiṇṇe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to old age grows old, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1152]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe socati kilamati paridevati, urattāḷiṃ kandati, sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to old age grows old, they sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1154]="*‘assutavā puthujjano viddho savisena sokasallena attānaṃyeva paritāpeti’.**an uneducated ordinary person struck by sorrow’s poisoned arrow, who only mortifies themselves.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, assutavato puthujjanassa byādhidhammaṃ byādhīyati … pe … maraṇadhammaṃ mīyati … khayadhammaṃ khīyati … nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**Furthermore, an uneducated ordinary person has someone liable to sickness … death … ending … perishing.*";
P_HTM[1156]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe na iti paṭisañcikkhati:**But they don’t reflect:*";
P_HTM[1157]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa nassanadhammaṃ nassati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to perishing who perishes. For as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn, they all have someone liable to perishing who perishes.*";
P_HTM[1158]="*Ahañceva kho pana nassanadhamme naṭṭhe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to perishing perishes, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1159]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe socati kilamati paridevati, urattāḷiṃ kandati, sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to perishing perishes, they sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1161]="*‘assutavā puthujjano viddho savisena sokasallena attānaṃyeva paritāpeti’.**an uneducated ordinary person struck by sorrow’s poisoned arrow, who only mortifies themselves.*";
P_HTM[1162]="*Sutavato ca kho, bhikkhave, ariyasāvakassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**An educated noble disciple has someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1163]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe iti paṭisañcikkhati:**And they reflect:*";
P_HTM[1164]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to old age who grows old. For as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn, they all have someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Ahañceva kho pana jarādhamme jiṇṇe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to old age grows old, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1166]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe na socati na kilamati na paridevati, na urattāḷiṃ kandati, na sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to old age grows old, they don’t sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1168]="*‘sutavā ariyasāvako abbuhi savisaṃ sokasallaṃ, yena viddho assutavā puthujjano attānaṃyeva paritāpeti.**an educated noble disciple who has drawn out sorrow’s poisoned arrow, struck by which uneducated ordinary people only mortify themselves.*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Asoko visallo ariyasāvako attānaṃyeva parinibbāpeti’.**Sorrowless, free of thorns, that noble disciple only extinguishes themselves.*";
P_HTM[1170]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, sutavato ariyasāvakassa byādhidhammaṃ byādhīyati … pe … maraṇadhammaṃ mīyati … khayadhammaṃ khīyati … nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**Furthermore, an educated noble disciple has someone liable to sickness… death … ending … perishing.*";
P_HTM[1171]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe iti paṭisañcikkhati:**And they reflect:*";
P_HTM[1172]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa nassanadhammaṃ nassati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to perishing who perishes. For as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn, they all have someone liable to perishing who perishes.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*Ahañceva kho pana nassanadhamme naṭṭhe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to perishing perishes, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1174]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe na socati na kilamati na paridevati, na urattāḷiṃ kandati, na sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to perishing perishes, they don’t sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1175]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1176]="*‘sutavā ariyasāvako abbuhi savisaṃ sokasallaṃ, yena viddho assutavā puthujjano attānaṃyeva paritāpeti.**an educated noble disciple who has drawn out sorrow’s poisoned arrow, struck by which uneducated ordinary people only mortify themselves.*";
P_HTM[1177]="*Asoko visallo ariyasāvako attānaṃyeva parinibbāpetī’ti.**Sorrowless, free of thorns, that noble disciple only extinguishes themselves.*";
P_HTM[1178]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca alabbhanīyāni ṭhānāni samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasminti.**These are the five things that cannot be had by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[1179]="*Na socanāya paridevanāya,**Sorrowing and lamenting*";
P_HTM[1180]="*Atthodha labbhā api appakopi;**doesn’t do even a little bit of good.*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Socantamenaṃ dukhitaṃ viditvā,**When they know that you’re sad,*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Paccatthikā attamanā bhavanti.**your enemies are encouraged.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Yato ca kho paṇḍito āpadāsu,**When an astute person doesn’t waver in the face of adversity,*";
P_HTM[1184]="*Na vedhatī atthavinicchayaññū;**as they’re able to assess what’s beneficial,*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Paccatthikāssa dukhitā bhavanti,**their enemies suffer,*";
P_HTM[1186]="*Disvā mukhaṃ avikāraṃ purāṇaṃ.**seeing that their normal expression doesn’t change.*";
P_HTM[1187]="*Jappena mantena subhāsitena,**Chants, recitations, fine sayings,*";
P_HTM[1188]="*Anuppadānena paveṇiyā vā;**charity or traditions:*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Yathā yathā yattha labhetha atthaṃ,**if by means of any such things you benefit,*";
P_HTM[1190]="*Tathā tathā tattha parakkameyya.**then by all means keep doing them.*";
P_HTM[1191]="*Sace pajāneyya alabbhaneyyo,**But if you understand that ‘this good thing*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Mayāva aññena vā esa attho;**can’t be had by me or by anyone else’,*";
P_HTM[1193]="*Asocamāno adhivāsayeyya,**you should accept it without sorrowing, thinking:*";
P_HTM[1194]="*Kammaṃ daḷhaṃ kinti karomi dānī”ti.**‘The karma is strong. What can I do now?’”*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1196]="*9. Kosalasuttaṃ**The King of Kosala*";
P_HTM[1197]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*Atha kho rājā pasenadi kosalo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Then King Pasenadi of Kosala went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[1199]="*Tena kho pana samayena mallikā devī kālaṅkatā hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1200]="*Atha kho aññataro puriso yena rājā pasenadi kosalo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rañño pasenadissa kosalassa upakaṇṇake āroceti:**Then a man went up to the king and whispered in his ear,*";
P_HTM[1201]="*“mallikā devī, deva, kālaṅkatā”ti.**“Your Majesty, Queen Mallikā has passed away.”*";
P_HTM[1202]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā pasenadi kosalo dukkhī dummano pattakkhandho adhomukho pajjhāyanto appaṭibhāno nisīdi.**When this was said, King Pasenadi was miserable and sad. He sat with his shoulders drooping, downcast, depressed, with nothing to say.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*Atha kho bhagavā rājānaṃ pasenadiṃ kosalaṃ dukkhiṃ dummanaṃ pattakkhandhaṃ adhomukhaṃ pajjhāyantaṃ appaṭibhānaṃ viditvā rājānaṃ pasenadiṃ kosalaṃ etadavoca:**Knowing this, the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1204]="*“pañcimāni, mahārāja, alabbhanīyāni ṭhānāni samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**“Great king, there are five things that cannot be had by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[1205]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1206]="*‘Jarādhammaṃ mā jīrī’ti alabbhanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ … pe … na socanāya paridevanāya … pe … kammaṃ daḷhaṃ kinti karomi dānī”ti.**That someone liable to old age should not grow old. … Sorrowing and lamenting doesn’t do even a little bit of good … ‘The karma is strong. What can I do now?’”*";
P_HTM[1207]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1208]="*10. Nāradasuttaṃ**With Nārada*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā nārado pāṭaliputte viharati kukkuṭārāme.**At one time Venerable Nārada was staying at Pāṭaliputta, in the Chicken Monastery.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Tena kho pana samayena muṇḍassa rañño bhaddā devī kālaṅkatā hoti piyā manāpā.**Now at that time King Muṇḍa’s dear and beloved Queen Bhaddā had just passed away.*";
P_HTM[1211]="*So bhaddāya deviyā kālaṅkatāya piyāya manāpāya neva nhāyati na vilimpati na bhattaṃ bhuñjati na kammantaṃ payojeti—**And since that time, the king did not bathe, anoint himself, eat his meals, or apply himself to his work.*";
P_HTM[1212]="*rattindivaṃ bhaddāya deviyā sarīre ajjhomucchito.**Day and night he brooded over Queen Bhaddā’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*Atha kho muṇḍo rājā piyakaṃ kosārakkhaṃ āmantesi:**Then King Muṇḍa addressed his treasurer, Piyaka,*";
P_HTM[1214]="*“tena hi, samma piyaka, bhaddāya deviyā sarīraṃ āyasāya teladoṇiyā pakkhipitvā aññissā āyasāya doṇiyā paṭikujjatha, yathā mayaṃ bhaddāya deviyā sarīraṃ cirataraṃ passeyyāmā”ti.**“So, my good Piyaka, please place Queen Bhaddā’s corpse in an iron case filled with oil. Then close it up with another case, so that we can view Queen Bhaddā’s body even longer.”*";
P_HTM[1215]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho piyako kosārakkho muṇḍassa rañño paṭissutvā bhaddāya deviyā sarīraṃ āyasāya teladoṇiyā pakkhipitvā aññissā āyasāya doṇiyā paṭikujji.**“Yes, Your Majesty,” replied Piyaka the treasurer, and he did as the king instructed.*";
P_HTM[1216]="*Atha kho piyakassa kosārakkhassa etadahosi:**Then it occurred to Piyaka,*";
P_HTM[1217]="*“imassa kho muṇḍassa rañño bhaddā devī kālaṅkatā piyā manāpā.**“King Muṇḍa’s dear and beloved Queen Bhaddā has passed away.*";
P_HTM[1218]="*So bhaddāya deviyā kālaṅkatāya piyāya manāpāya neva nhāyati na vilimpati na bhattaṃ bhuñjati na kammantaṃ payojeti—**Since then the king does not bathe, anoint himself, eat his meals, or apply himself to his work.*";
P_HTM[1219]="*rattindivaṃ bhaddāya deviyā sarīre ajjhomucchito.**Day and night he broods over Queen Bhaddā’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*Kaṃ nu kho muṇḍo rājā samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā payirupāseyya, yassa dhammaṃ sutvā sokasallaṃ pajaheyyā”ti.**Now, what ascetic or brahmin might the king pay homage to, whose teaching could help the king give up sorrow’s arrow?”*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Atha kho piyakassa kosārakkhassa etadahosi:**Then it occurred to Piyaka,*";
P_HTM[1222]="*“ayaṃ kho āyasmā nārado pāṭaliputte viharati kukkuṭārāme.**“This Venerable Nārada is staying in the Chicken Monastery at Pāṭaliputta.*";
P_HTM[1223]="*Taṃ kho panāyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1224]="*‘paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī bahussuto cittakathī kalyāṇapaṭibhāno vuddho ceva arahā ca’.**‘He is astute, competent, intelligent, learned, a brilliant speaker, eloquent, mature, a perfected one.’*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Yannūna muṇḍo rājā āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ payirupāseyya, appeva nāma muṇḍo rājā āyasmato nāradassa dhammaṃ sutvā sokasallaṃ pajaheyyā”ti.**What if King Muṇḍa was to pay homage to Venerable Nārada? Hopefully when he hears Nārada’s teaching, the king could give up sorrow’s arrow.”*";
P_HTM[1226]="*Atha kho piyako kosārakkho yena muṇḍo rājā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā muṇḍaṃ rājānaṃ etadavoca:**Then Piyaka went to the king and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1227]="*“ayaṃ kho, deva, āyasmā nārado pāṭaliputte viharati kukkuṭārāme.**“Sire, this Venerable Nārada is staying in the Chicken Monastery at Pāṭaliputta.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Taṃ kho panāyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1229]="*‘paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī bahussuto cittakathī kalyāṇapaṭibhāno vuddho ceva arahā ca’.**‘He is astute, competent, intelligent, learned, a brilliant speaker, eloquent, mature, a perfected one.’*";
P_HTM[1230]="*Yadi pana devo āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ payirupāseyya, appeva nāma devo āyasmato nāradassa dhammaṃ sutvā sokasallaṃ pajaheyyā”ti.**What if Your Majesty was to pay homage to Venerable Nārada? Hopefully when you hear Nārada’s teaching, you could give up sorrow’s arrow.”*";
P_HTM[1231]="*“Tena hi, samma piyaka, āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ paṭivedehi.**“Well then, my good Piyaka, let Nārada know.*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ pubbe appaṭisaṃvidito upasaṅkamitabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti.**For how could one such as I presume to visit an ascetic or brahmin in my realm without first letting them know?”*";
P_HTM[1233]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho piyako kosārakkho muṇḍassa rañño paṭissutvā yenāyasmā nārado tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho piyako kosārakkho āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, Your Majesty,” replied Piyaka the treasurer. He went to Nārada, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1234]="*“Imassa, bhante, muṇḍassa rañño bhaddā devī kālaṅkatā piyā manāpā.**“Sir, King Muṇḍa’s dear and beloved Queen Bhaddā has passed away.*";
P_HTM[1235]="*So bhaddāya deviyā kālaṅkatāya piyāya manāpāya neva nhāyati na vilimpati na bhattaṃ bhuñjati na kammantaṃ payojeti—**And since she passed away, the king has not bathed, anointed himself, eaten his meals, or got his business done.*";
P_HTM[1236]="*rattindivaṃ bhaddāya deviyā sarīre ajjhomucchito.**Day and night he broods over Queen Bhaddā’s corpse.*";
P_HTM[1237]="*Sādhu, bhante, āyasmā nārado muṇḍassa rañño tathā dhammaṃ desetu yathā muṇḍo rājā āyasmato nāradassa dhammaṃ sutvā sokasallaṃ pajaheyyā”ti.**Sir, please teach the king so that, when he hears your teaching, he can give up sorrow’s arrow.”*";
P_HTM[1238]="*“Yassadāni, piyaka, muṇḍo rājā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**“Please, Piyaka, let the king come when he likes.”*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Atha kho piyako kosārakkho uṭṭhāyāsanā āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena muṇḍo rājā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā muṇḍaṃ rājānaṃ etadavoca:**Then Piyaka got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled Venerable Nārada, keeping him on his right, before going to the king and saying,*";
P_HTM[1240]="*“katāvakāso kho, deva, āyasmatā nāradena.**“Sire, the request for an audience with Venerable Nārada has been granted.*";
P_HTM[1241]="*Yassadāni devo kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**Please, Your Majesty, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1242]="*“Tena hi, samma piyaka, bhadrāni bhadrāni yānāni yojāpehī”ti.**“Well then, my good Piyaka, harness the finest chariots.”*";
P_HTM[1243]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho piyako kosārakkho muṇḍassa rañño paṭissutvā bhadrāni bhadrāni yānāni yojāpetvā muṇḍaṃ rājānaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, Your Majesty,” replied Piyaka the treasurer. He did so, then told the king:*";
P_HTM[1244]="*“yuttāni kho te, deva, bhadrāni bhadrāni yānāni.**“Sire, the finest chariots are harnessed.*";
P_HTM[1245]="*Yassadāni devo kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**Please, Your Majesty, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1246]="*Atha kho muṇḍo rājā bhadraṃ yānaṃ abhiruhitvā bhadrehi bhadrehi yānehi yena kukkuṭārāmo tena pāyāsi mahaccā rājānubhāvena āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ dassanāya.**Then King Muṇḍa mounted a fine carriage and, along with other fine carriages, set out in full royal pomp to see Venerable Nārada at the Chicken Monastery.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi yānena gantvā, yānā paccorohitvā pattikova ārāmaṃ pāvisi.**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and entered the monastery on foot.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*Atha kho muṇḍo rājā yena āyasmā nārado tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho muṇḍaṃ rājānaṃ āyasmā nārado etadavoca:**Then the king went up to Nārada, bowed, and sat down to one side. Then Nārada said to him:*";
P_HTM[1249]="*“Pañcimāni, mahārāja, alabbhanīyāni ṭhānāni samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**“Great king, there are five things that cannot be had by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1251]="*‘Jarādhammaṃ mā jīrī’ti alabbhanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**That someone liable to old age should not grow old. …*";
P_HTM[1252]="*‘Byādhidhammaṃ mā byādhīyī’ti … pe … ‘maraṇadhammaṃ mā mīyī’ti … ‘khayadhammaṃ mā khīyī’ti … ‘nassanadhammaṃ mā nassī’ti alabbhanīyaṃ ṭhānaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**That someone liable to sickness should not get sick. … That someone liable to death should not die. … That someone liable to ending should not end. … That someone liable to perishing should not perish. …*";
P_HTM[1253]="*Assutavato, mahārāja, puthujjanassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**An uneducated ordinary person has someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1254]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe na iti paṭisañcikkhati:**But they don’t reflect on the nature of old age:*";
P_HTM[1255]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to old age who grows old. For all sentient beings have someone liable to old age who grows old, as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1256]="*Ahañceva kho pana jarādhamme jiṇṇe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to old age grows old, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1257]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe socati kilamati paridevati, urattāḷiṃ kandati, sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to old age grows old, they sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, mahārāja:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1259]="*‘assutavā puthujjano viddho savisena sokasallena attānaṃyeva paritāpeti’.**an uneducated ordinary person struck by sorrow’s poisoned arrow, who only mortifies themselves.*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahārāja, assutavato puthujjanassa byādhidhammaṃ byādhīyati … pe … maraṇadhammaṃ mīyati … khayadhammaṃ khīyati … nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**Furthermore, an uneducated ordinary person has someone liable to sickness … death … ending … perishing.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe na iti paṭisañcikkhati:**But they don’t reflect on the nature of perishing:*";
P_HTM[1262]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa nassanadhammaṃ nassati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to perishing who perishes. For all sentient beings have someone liable to perishing who perishes, as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Ahañceva kho pana nassanadhamme naṭṭhe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to perishing perishes, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1264]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe socati kilamati paridevati, urattāḷiṃ kandati, sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to perishing perishes, they sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, mahārāja:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1266]="*‘assutavā puthujjano viddho savisena sokasallena attānaṃyeva paritāpeti’.**an uneducated ordinary person struck by sorrow’s poisoned arrow, who only mortifies themselves.*";
P_HTM[1267]="*Sutavato ca kho, mahārāja, ariyasāvakassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**An educated noble disciple has someone liable to old age who grows old.*";
P_HTM[1268]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe iti paṭisañcikkhati:**So they reflect on the nature of old age:*";
P_HTM[1269]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa jarādhammaṃ jīrati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ jarādhammaṃ jīrati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to old age who grows old. For all sentient beings have someone liable to old age who grows old, as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1270]="*Ahañceva kho pana jarādhamme jiṇṇe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to old age grows old, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1271]="*So jarādhamme jiṇṇe na socati na kilamati na paridevati, na urattāḷiṃ kandati, na sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to old age grows old, they don’t sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1272]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, mahārāja:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1273]="*‘sutavā ariyasāvako abbuhi savisaṃ sokasallaṃ, yena viddho assutavā puthujjano attānaṃyeva paritāpeti.**an educated noble disciple who has drawn out sorrow’s poisoned arrow, struck by which uneducated ordinary people only mortify themselves.*";
P_HTM[1274]="*Asoko visallo ariyasāvako attānaṃyeva parinibbāpeti’.**Sorrowless, free of thorns, that noble disciple only extinguishes themselves.*";
P_HTM[1275]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahārāja, sutavato ariyasāvakassa byādhidhammaṃ byādhīyati … pe … maraṇadhammaṃ mīyati … khayadhammaṃ khīyati … nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**Furthermore, an educated noble disciple has someone liable to sickness… death … ending … perishing.*";
P_HTM[1276]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe iti paṭisañcikkhati:**So they reflect on the nature of perishing:*";
P_HTM[1277]="*‘na kho mayhevekassa nassanadhammaṃ nassati, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ nassanadhammaṃ nassati.**‘It’s not just me who has someone liable to perishing who perishes. For all sentient beings have someone liable to perishing who perishes, as long as sentient beings come and go, pass away and are reborn.*";
P_HTM[1278]="*Ahañceva kho pana nassanadhamme naṭṭhe soceyyaṃ kilameyyaṃ parideveyyaṃ, urattāḷiṃ kandeyyaṃ, sammohaṃ āpajjeyyaṃ, bhattampi me nacchādeyya, kāyepi dubbaṇṇiyaṃ okkameyya, kammantāpi nappavatteyyuṃ, amittāpi attamanā assu, mittāpi dummanā assū’ti.**If I were to sorrow and pine and lament, beating my breast and falling into confusion, just because someone liable to perishing perishes, I’d lose my appetite and my body would become ugly. My work wouldn’t get done, my enemies would be encouraged, and my friends would be dispirited.’*";
P_HTM[1279]="*So nassanadhamme naṭṭhe na socati na kilamati na paridevati, na urattāḷiṃ kandati, na sammohaṃ āpajjati.**And so, when someone liable to perishing perishes, they don’t sorrow and pine and lament, beating their breast and falling into confusion.*";
P_HTM[1280]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, mahārāja:**This is called*";
P_HTM[1281]="*‘sutavā ariyasāvako abbuhi savisaṃ sokasallaṃ, yena viddho assutavā puthujjano attānaṃyeva paritāpeti.**an educated noble disciple who has drawn out sorrow’s poisoned arrow, struck by which uneducated ordinary people only mortify themselves.*";
P_HTM[1282]="*Asoko visallo ariyasāvako attānaṃyeva parinibbāpeti’.**Sorrowless, free of thorns, that noble disciple only extinguishes themselves.*";
P_HTM[1283]="*Imāni kho, mahārāja, pañca alabbhanīyāni ṭhānāni samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasminti.**These are the five things that cannot be had by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[1284]="*Na socanāya paridevanāya,**Sorrowing and lamenting*";
P_HTM[1285]="*Atthodha labbhā api appakopi;**doesn’t do even a little bit of good.*";
P_HTM[1286]="*Socantamenaṃ dukhitaṃ viditvā,**When they know that you’re sad,*";
P_HTM[1287]="*Paccatthikā attamanā bhavanti.**your enemies are encouraged.*";
P_HTM[1288]="*Yato ca kho paṇḍito āpadāsu,**When an astute person doesn’t waver in the face of adversity,*";
P_HTM[1289]="*Na vedhatī atthavinicchayaññū;**as they’re able to assess what’s beneficial,*";
P_HTM[1290]="*Paccatthikāssa dukhitā bhavanti,**their enemies suffer,*";
P_HTM[1291]="*Disvā mukhaṃ avikāraṃ purāṇaṃ.**seeing that their normal expression doesn’t change.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*Jappena mantena subhāsitena,**Chants, recitations, fine sayings,*";
P_HTM[1293]="*Anuppadānena paveṇiyā vā;**charity or traditions:*";
P_HTM[1294]="*Yathā yathā yattha labhetha atthaṃ,**if by means of any such things you benefit,*";
P_HTM[1295]="*Tathā tathā tattha parakkameyya.**then by all means keep doing them.*";
P_HTM[1296]="*Sace pajāneyya alabbhaneyyo,**But if you understand that ‘this good thing*";
P_HTM[1297]="*Mayāva aññena vā esa attho;**can’t be had by me or by anyone else’,*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Asocamāno adhivāsayeyya,**you should accept it without sorrowing, thinking:*";
P_HTM[1299]="*Kammaṃ daḷhaṃ kinti karomi dānī”ti.**‘The karma is strong. What can I do now?’”*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Evaṃ vutte, muṇḍo rājā āyasmantaṃ nāradaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, King Muṇḍa said to Venerable Nārada,*";
P_HTM[1301]="*“ko nāmo ayaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo”ti?**“Sir, what is the name of this exposition of the teaching?”*";
P_HTM[1302]="*“Sokasallaharaṇo nāma ayaṃ, mahārāja, dhammapariyāyo”ti.**“Great king, this exposition of the teaching is called ‘Pulling Out Sorrow’s Arrow’.”*";
P_HTM[1303]="*“Taggha, bhante, sokasallaharaṇo.**“Indeed, sir, this is the pulling out of sorrow’s arrow!*";
P_HTM[1304]="*Imañhi me, bhante, dhammapariyāyaṃ sutvā sokasallaṃ pahīnan”ti.**Hearing this exposition of the teaching, I’ve given up sorrow’s arrow.”*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Atha kho muṇḍo rājā piyakaṃ kosārakkhaṃ āmantesi:**Then King Muṇḍa addressed his treasurer, Piyaka,*";
P_HTM[1306]="*“tena hi, samma piyaka, bhaddāya deviyā sarīraṃ jhāpetha; thūpañcassā karotha.**“Well then, my good Piyaka, cremate Queen Bhaddā’s corpse and build a monument.*";
P_HTM[1307]="*Ajjatagge dāni mayaṃ nhāyissāma ceva vilimpissāma bhattañca bhuñjissāma kammante ca payojessāmā”ti.**From this day forth, I will bathe, anoint myself, eat my meals, and apply myself to my work.”*";
P_HTM[1308]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1309]="*Muṇḍarājavaggo pañcamo.* **";
P_HTM[1310]="*Ādiyo sappuriso iṭṭhā,* **";
P_HTM[1311]="*manāpadāyībhisandaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1312]="*Sampadā ca dhanaṃ ṭhānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[1313]="*kosalo nāradena cāti.* **";
P_HTM[1314]="*Paṭhamo paṇṇāsako samatto.* **";
P_HTM[1315]="*13. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Hindrances*";
P_HTM[1316]="*1. Āvaraṇasuttaṃ**Obstacles*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1320]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[1321]="*“Bhadante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1323]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, āvaraṇā nīvaraṇā cetaso ajjhāruhā paññāya dubbalīkaraṇā.**“Mendicants, there are these five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Kāmacchando, bhikkhave, āvaraṇo nīvaraṇo cetaso ajjhāruho paññāya dubbalīkaraṇo.**Sensual desire …*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Byāpādo, bhikkhave, āvaraṇo nīvaraṇo cetaso ajjhāruho paññāya dubbalīkaraṇo.**Ill will …*";
P_HTM[1327]="*Thinamiddhaṃ, bhikkhave, āvaraṇaṃ nīvaraṇaṃ cetaso ajjhāruhaṃ paññāya dubbalīkaraṇaṃ.**Dullness and drowsiness …*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ, bhikkhave, āvaraṇaṃ nīvaraṇaṃ cetaso ajjhāruhaṃ paññāya dubbalīkaraṇaṃ.**Restlessness and remorse …*";
P_HTM[1329]="*Vicikicchā, bhikkhave, āvaraṇā nīvaraṇā cetaso ajjhāruhā paññāya dubbalīkaraṇā.**Doubt …*";
P_HTM[1330]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca āvaraṇā nīvaraṇā cetaso ajjhāruhā paññāya dubbalīkaraṇā.**These are the five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1331]="*So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ime pañca āvaraṇe nīvaraṇe cetaso ajjhāruhe paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe appahāya, abalāya paññāya dubbalāya attatthaṃ vā ñassati paratthaṃ vā ñassati ubhayatthaṃ vā ñassati uttari vā manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanavisesaṃ sacchikarissatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Take a mendicant who has feeble and weak wisdom, not having given up these five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom. It’s simply impossible that they would know what’s for their own good, the good of another, or the good of both; or that they would realize any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, nadī pabbateyyā dūraṅgamā sīghasotā hārahārinī.**Suppose there was a mountain river that flowed swiftly, going far, carrying all before it.*";
P_HTM[1333]="*Tassā puriso ubhato naṅgalamukhāni vivareyya.**But then a man would open channels on both sides,*";
P_HTM[1334]="*Evañhi so, bhikkhave, majjhe nadiyā soto vikkhitto visaṭo byādiṇṇo neva dūraṅgamo assa na sīghasoto na hārahārī.**so the mid-river current would be dispersed, spread out, and separated. The river would no longer flow swiftly, going far, carrying all before it.*";
P_HTM[1335]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, so vata bhikkhu ime pañca āvaraṇe nīvaraṇe cetaso ajjhāruhe paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe appahāya, abalāya paññāya dubbalāya attatthaṃ vā ñassati paratthaṃ vā ñassati ubhayatthaṃ vā ñassati uttari vā manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanavisesaṃ sacchikarissatīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**In the same way, take a mendicant who has feeble and weak wisdom, not having given up these five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom. It’s simply impossible that they would know what’s for their own good, the good of another, or the good of both; or that they would realize any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[1336]="*So vata, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ime pañca āvaraṇe nīvaraṇe cetaso ajjhāruhe paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe pahāya, balavatiyā paññāya attatthaṃ vā ñassati paratthaṃ vā ñassati ubhayatthaṃ vā ñassati uttari vā manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanavisesaṃ sacchikarissatīti ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**Take a mendicant who has powerful wisdom, having given up these five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom. It’s quite possible that they would know what’s for their own good, the good of another, or the good of both; or that they would realize any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[1337]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, nadī pabbateyyā dūraṅgamā sīghasotā hārahārinī.**Suppose there was a mountain river that flowed swiftly, going far, carrying all before it.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*Tassā puriso ubhato naṅgalamukhāni pidaheyya.**But then a man would close up the channels on both sides,*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Evañhi so, bhikkhave, majjhe nadiyā soto avikkhitto avisaṭo abyādiṇṇo dūraṅgamo ceva assa sīghasoto ca hārahārī ca.**so the mid-river current would not be dispersed, spread out, and separated. The river would keep flowing swiftly for a long way, carrying all before it.*";
P_HTM[1340]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, so vata bhikkhu ime pañca āvaraṇe nīvaraṇe cetaso ajjhāruhe paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe pahāya, balavatiyā paññāya attatthaṃ vā ñassati paratthaṃ vā ñassati ubhayatthaṃ vā ñassati uttari vā manussadhammā alamariyañāṇadassanavisesaṃ sacchikarissatīti ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī”ti.**In the same way, take a mendicant who has powerful wisdom, having given up these five obstacles and hindrances, parasites of the mind that weaken wisdom. It’s quite possible that they would know what’s for their own good, the good of another, or the good of both; or that they would realize any superhuman distinction in knowledge and vision worthy of the noble ones.”*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1342]="*2. Akusalarāsisuttaṃ**A Heap of the Unskillful*";
P_HTM[1343]="*“Akusalarāsīti, bhikkhave, vadamāno pañca nīvaraṇe sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**“Mendicants, rightly speaking, you’d call the five hindrances a ‘heap of the unskillful’.*";
P_HTM[1344]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, akusalarāsi yadidaṃ pañca nīvaraṇā.**For these five hindrances are entirely a heap of the unskillful.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1346]="*Kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ.**The hindrances of sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Akusalarāsīti, bhikkhave, vadamāno ime pañca nīvaraṇe sammā vadamāno vadeyya.**Rightly speaking, you’d call these five hindrances a ‘heap of the unskillful’.*";
P_HTM[1348]="*Kevalo hāyaṃ, bhikkhave, akusalarāsi yadidaṃ pañca nīvaraṇā”ti.**For these five hindrances are entirely a heap of the unskillful.”*";
P_HTM[1349]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1350]="*3. Padhāniyaṅgasuttaṃ**Factors That Support Meditation*";
P_HTM[1351]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, padhāniyaṅgāni.**“Mendicants, there are these five factors that support meditation.*";
P_HTM[1352]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1353]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**It’s when a mendicant has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[1354]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1355]="*Appābādho hoti appātaṅko;**They are rarely ill or unwell.*";
P_HTM[1356]="*samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya majjhimāya padhānakkhamāya;**Their stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, but just right, and fit for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1357]="*asaṭho hoti amāyāvī;**They’re not devious or deceitful.*";
P_HTM[1358]="*yathābhūtaṃ attānaṃ āvikattā satthari vā viññūsu vā sabrahmacārīsu;**They reveal themselves honestly to the Teacher or sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[1359]="*āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu;**They live with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1360]="*paññavā hoti, udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**They’re wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, pañca padhāniyaṅgānī”ti.**These are the five factors that support meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1362]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1363]="*4. Samayasuttaṃ**Times Good for Meditation*";
P_HTM[1364]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, asamayā padhānāya.**“Mendicants, there are five times that are not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1365]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1366]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu jiṇṇo hoti jarāyābhibhūto.**Firstly, a mendicant is old, overcome with old age.*";
P_HTM[1367]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo asamayo padhānāya.**This is the first time that’s not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1368]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu byādhito hoti byādhinābhibhūto.**Furthermore, a mendicant is sick, overcome by sickness.*";
P_HTM[1369]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo asamayo padhānāya.**This is the second time that’s not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1370]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, dubbhikkhaṃ hoti dussassaṃ dullabhapiṇḍaṃ, na sukaraṃ uñchena paggahena yāpetuṃ.**Furthermore, there’s a famine, a bad harvest, so it’s hard to get alms-food, and not easy to keep going by collecting alms.*";
P_HTM[1371]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo asamayo padhānāya.**This is the third time that’s not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhayaṃ hoti aṭavisaṅkopo, cakkasamārūḷhā jānapadā pariyāyanti.**Furthermore, there’s peril from wild savages, and the countryfolk mount their vehicles and flee everywhere.*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho asamayo padhānāya.**This is the fourth time that’s not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1374]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, saṅgho bhinno hoti.**Furthermore, there’s a schism in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Saṅghe kho pana, bhikkhave, bhinne aññamaññaṃ akkosā ca honti, aññamaññaṃ paribhāsā ca honti, aññamaññaṃ parikkhepā ca honti, aññamaññaṃ pariccajā ca honti.**When the Saṅgha is split, they abuse, insult, block, and reject each other.*";
P_HTM[1376]="*Tattha appasannā ceva nappasīdanti, pasannānañca ekaccānaṃ aññathattaṃ hoti.**This doesn’t inspire confidence in those without it, and it causes some with confidence to change their minds.*";
P_HTM[1377]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo asamayo padhānāya.**This is the fifth time that’s not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1378]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca asamayā padhānāyāti.**These are the five times that are not good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*Pañcime, bhikkhave, samayā padhānāya.**There are five times that are good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu daharo hoti yuvā susu kāḷakeso bhadrena yobbanena samannāgato paṭhamena vayasā.**Firstly, a mendicant is a youth, young, black-haired, blessed with youth, in the prime of life.*";
P_HTM[1382]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo samayo padhānāya.**This is the first time that’s good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1383]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu appābādho hoti appātaṅko, samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya majjhimāya padhānakkhamāya.**Furthermore, they are rarely ill or unwell. Their stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, but just right, and fit for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo samayo padhānāya.**This is the second time that’s good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, subhikkhaṃ hoti susassaṃ sulabhapiṇḍaṃ, sukaraṃ uñchena paggahena yāpetuṃ.**Furthermore, there’s plenty of food, a good harvest, so it’s easy to get alms-food, and easy to keep going by collecting alms.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo samayo padhānāya.**This is the third time that’s good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, manussā samaggā sammodamānā avivadamānā khīrodakībhūtā aññamaññaṃ piyacakkhūhi sampassantā viharanti.**Furthermore, people live in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, blending like milk and water, and regarding each other with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho samayo padhānāya.**This is the fourth time that’s good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1389]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, saṃgho samaggo sammodamāno avivadamāno ekuddeso phāsu viharati.**Furthermore, the Saṅgha lives comfortably, in harmony, appreciating each other, without quarreling, with one recitation.*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Saṃghe kho pana, bhikkhave, samagge na ceva aññamaññaṃ akkosā honti, na ca aññamaññaṃ paribhāsā honti, na ca aññamaññaṃ parikkhepā honti, na ca aññamaññaṃ pariccajā honti.**When the Saṅgha is in harmony, they don’t abuse, insult, block, or reject each other.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Tattha appasannā ceva pasīdanti, pasannānañca bhiyyobhāvo hoti.**This inspires confidence in those without it, and increases confidence in those who have it.*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo samayo padhānāya.**This is the fifth time that’s good for meditation.*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca samayā padhānāyā”ti.**These are the five times that are good for meditation.”*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1395]="*5. Mātāputtasuttaṃ**Mother and Son*";
P_HTM[1396]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[1397]="*Tena kho pana samayena sāvatthiyaṃ ubho mātāputtā vassāvāsaṃ upagamiṃsu—**Now, at that time a mother and son had both entered the rainy season residence at Sāvatthī,*";
P_HTM[1398]="*bhikkhu ca bhikkhunī ca.**as a monk and a nun.*";
P_HTM[1399]="*Te aññamaññassa abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmā ahesuṃ.**They wanted to see each other often.*";
P_HTM[1400]="*Mātāpi puttassa abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmā ahosi;**The mother wanted to see her son often,*";
P_HTM[1401]="*puttopi mātaraṃ abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmo ahosi.**and the son his mother.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Tesaṃ abhiṇhaṃ dassanā saṃsaggo ahosi.**Seeing each other often, they became close.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Saṃsagge sati vissāso ahosi.**Being so close, they became intimate.*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Vissāse sati otāro ahosi.**And being intimate, lust overcame them.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Te otiṇṇacittā sikkhaṃ apaccakkhāya dubbalyaṃ anāvikatvā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭiseviṃsu.**With their minds swamped by lust, without rejecting the training and declaring their inability to continue, they had sex.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Atha kho sambahulā bhikkhū yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then several mendicants went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*“idha, bhante, sāvatthiyaṃ ubho mātāputtā vassāvāsaṃ upagamiṃsu—* **";
P_HTM[1408]="*bhikkhu ca bhikkhunī ca, te aññamaññassa abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmā ahesuṃ, mātāpi puttassa abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmā ahosi, puttopi mātaraṃ abhiṇhaṃ dassanakāmo ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[1409]="*Tesaṃ abhiṇhaṃ dassanā saṃsaggo ahosi, saṃsagge sati vissāso ahosi, vissāse sati otāro ahosi, te otiṇṇacittā sikkhaṃ apaccakkhāya dubbalyaṃ anāvikatvā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭiseviṃsū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1410]="*“Kiṃ nu so, bhikkhave, moghapuriso maññati:**“Mendicants, how could that silly man imagine that*";
P_HTM[1411]="*‘na mātā putte sārajjati, putto vā pana mātarī’ti?**a mother cannot lust for her son, or that a son cannot lust for his mother?*";
P_HTM[1412]="*Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, aññaṃ ekarūpampi samanupassāmi evaṃ rajanīyaṃ evaṃ kamanīyaṃ evaṃ madanīyaṃ evaṃ bandhanīyaṃ evaṃ mucchanīyaṃ evaṃ antarāyakaraṃ anuttarassa yogakkhemassa adhigamāya yathayidaṃ, bhikkhave, itthirūpaṃ.**Compared to the sight of a woman, I do not see a single sight that is so arousing, sensuous, intoxicating, captivating, and infatuating, and such an obstacle to reaching the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1413]="*Itthirūpe, bhikkhave, sattā rattā giddhā gathitā mucchitā ajjhosannā.**Sentient beings are lustful, greedy, tied, infatuated, and attached to the sight of a woman.*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Te dīgharattaṃ socanti itthirūpavasānugā.**They sorrow for a long time under the sway of a woman’s sight.*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, aññaṃ ekasaddampi … ekagandhampi … ekarasampi … ekaphoṭṭhabbampi samanupassāmi evaṃ rajanīyaṃ evaṃ kamanīyaṃ evaṃ madanīyaṃ evaṃ bandhanīyaṃ evaṃ mucchanīyaṃ evaṃ antarāyakaraṃ anuttarassa yogakkhemassa adhigamāya yathayidaṃ, bhikkhave, itthiphoṭṭhabbaṃ.**Compared to the sound … smell … taste … touch of a woman, I do not see a single touch that is so arousing, sensuous, intoxicating, captivating, and infatuating, and such an obstacle to reaching the supreme sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Itthiphoṭṭhabbe, bhikkhave, sattā rattā giddhā gathitā mucchitā ajjhosannā.**Sentient beings are lustful, greedy, tied, infatuated, and attached to the touch of a woman.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*Te dīgharattaṃ socanti itthiphoṭṭhabbavasānugā.**They sorrow for a long time under the sway of a woman’s touch.*";
P_HTM[1418]="*Itthī, bhikkhave, gacchantīpi purisassa cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati;**When a woman walks, she occupies a man’s mind.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*ṭhitāpi … pe … nisinnāpi … sayānāpi … hasantīpi … bhaṇantīpi … gāyantīpi … rodantīpi … ugghātitāpi … matāpi purisassa cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati.**When a woman stands … sits … lies down … laughs … speaks … sings … cries … is injured, she occupies a man’s mind. Even when a woman is dead, she occupies a man’s mind.*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Yañhi taṃ, bhikkhave, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**For if anyone should be rightly called ‘an all-round snare of Māra’, it’s females.*";
P_HTM[1421]="*‘samantapāso mārassā’ti mātugāmaṃyeva sammā vadamāno vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[1422]="*‘samantapāso mārassā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1423]="*Sallape asihatthena,**You might chat with someone who has knife in hand.*";
P_HTM[1424]="*pisācenāpi sallape;**You might even chat with a goblin.*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Āsīvisampi āsīde,**You might sit close by a viper,*";
P_HTM[1426]="*yena daṭṭho na jīvati;**whose bite would take your life.*";
P_HTM[1427]="*Na tveva eko ekāya,**But never should you chat*";
P_HTM[1428]="*mātugāmena sallape.**one on one with a female.*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Muṭṭhassatiṃ tā bandhanti,**They captivate the unmindful*";
P_HTM[1430]="*pekkhitena sitena ca;**with a glance and a smile.*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Athopi dunnivatthena,**Or scantily clad,*";
P_HTM[1432]="*mañjunā bhaṇitena ca;**they speak charming words.*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Neso jano svāsīsado,**It’s not good to sit with such a person,*";
P_HTM[1434]="*api ugghātito mato.**even if she’s injured or dead.*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Pañca kāmaguṇā ete,**These five kinds of sensual stimulation*";
P_HTM[1436]="*itthirūpasmiṃ dissare;**are apparent in a woman’s body:*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Rūpā saddā rasā gandhā,**sights, sounds, tastes, smells,*";
P_HTM[1438]="*phoṭṭhabbā ca manoramā.**and touches so delightful.*";
P_HTM[1439]="*Tesaṃ kāmoghavūḷhānaṃ,**Those swept away by the flood of sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[1440]="*kāme aparijānataṃ;**not comprehending them,*";
P_HTM[1441]="*Kālaṃ gati bhavābhavaṃ,**prioritize transmigration—*";
P_HTM[1442]="*saṃsārasmiṃ purakkhatā.**time and destination, and life after life.*";
P_HTM[1443]="*Ye ca kāme pariññāya,**But those who completely understand sensual pleasures*";
P_HTM[1444]="*caranti akutobhayā;**live fearing nothing from any quarter.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*Te ve pāraṅgatā loke,**They are those in the world who’ve crossed over,*";
P_HTM[1446]="*ye pattā āsavakkhayan”ti.**having reached the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1447]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1448]="*6. Upajjhāyasuttaṃ**Mentor*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena sako upajjhāyo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā sakaṃ upajjhāyaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to his own mentor, and said,*";
P_HTM[1450]="*“etarahi me, bhante, madhurakajāto ceva kāyo, disā ca me na pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca maṃ nappaṭibhanti, thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, anabhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi, atthi ca me dhammesu vicikicchā”ti.**“Now, sir, my body feels like it’s drugged. I’m disorientated, the teachings don’t spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness fill my mind. I live the spiritual life dissatisfied, and have doubts about the teachings.”*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu taṃ saddhivihārikaṃ bhikkhuṃ ādāya yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then that mendicant took his pupil to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1452]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu evamāha:**“Sir, this mendicant says this:*";
P_HTM[1453]="*‘etarahi me, bhante, madhurakajāto ceva kāyo, disā ca maṃ na pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca me nappaṭibhanti, thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, anabhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi, atthi ca me dhammesu vicikicchā’”ti.**‘Now, sir, my body feels like it’s drugged. I’m disorientated, the teachings don’t spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness fill my mind. I live the spiritual life dissatisfied, and have doubts about the teachings.’”*";
P_HTM[1454]="*“Evañhetaṃ, bhikkhu, hoti indriyesu aguttadvārassa, bhojane amattaññuno, jāgariyaṃ ananuyuttassa, avipassakassa kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ, pubbarattāpararattaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanānuyogaṃ ananuyuttassa viharato, yaṃ madhurakajāto ceva kāyo hoti, disā cassa na pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca taṃ nappaṭibhanti, thinamiddhañcassa cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, anabhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carati, hoti cassa dhammesu vicikicchā.**“That’s how it is, mendicant, when your sense doors are unguarded, you eat too much, you’re not dedicated to wakefulness, you’re unable to discern skillful qualities, and you don’t pursue the development of the qualities that lead to awakening in the evening and toward dawn. Your body feels like it’s drugged. You’re disorientated, the teachings don’t spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness fill your mind. You live the spiritual life dissatisfied, and have doubts about the teachings.*";
P_HTM[1455]="*Tasmātiha te, bhikkhu, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[1456]="*‘indriyesu guttadvāro bhavissāmi, bhojane mattaññū, jāgariyaṃ anuyutto, vipassako kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ, pubbarattāpararattaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyutto viharissāmī’ti.**‘I will guard my sense doors, eat in moderation, be dedicated to wakefulness, discern skillful qualities, and pursue the development of the qualities that lead to awakening in the evening and toward dawn.’*";
P_HTM[1457]="*Evañhi te, bhikkhu, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[1458]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu bhagavatā iminā ovādena ovadito uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**When that mendicant had been given this advice by the Buddha, he got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Then that mendicant, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme culmination of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1460]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[1461]="*Aññataro pana so bhikkhu arahataṃ ahosi.**And that mendicant became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[1462]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu arahattaṃ patto yena sako upajjhāyo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā sakaṃ upajjhāyaṃ etadavoca:**When that mendicant had attained perfection, he went up to his own mentor, and said,*";
P_HTM[1463]="*“etarahi me, bhante, na ceva madhurakajāto kāyo, disā ca me pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca maṃ paṭibhanti, thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ na pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, abhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi, natthi ca me dhammesu vicikicchā”ti.**“Now, sir, my body doesn’t feel like it’s drugged. I’m not disorientated, the teachings spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness don’t fill my mind. I live the spiritual life satisfied, and have no doubts about the teachings.”*";
P_HTM[1464]="*Atha kho so bhikkhu taṃ saddhivihārikaṃ bhikkhuṃ ādāya yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then that mendicant took his pupil to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1465]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, bhikkhu evamāha:**“Sir, this mendicant says this:*";
P_HTM[1466]="*‘etarahi me, bhante, na ceva madhurakajāto kāyo, disā ca me pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca maṃ paṭibhanti, thinamiddhañca me cittaṃ na pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, abhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carāmi, natthi ca me dhammesu vicikicchā’”ti.**‘Now, sir, my body doesn’t feel like it’s drugged. I’m not disorientated, the teachings spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness don’t fill my mind. I live the spiritual life satisfied, and have no doubts about the teachings.’”*";
P_HTM[1467]="*“Evañhetaṃ, bhikkhu, hoti indriyesu guttadvārassa, bhojane mattaññuno, jāgariyaṃ anuyuttassa, vipassakassa kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ, pubbarattāpararattaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttassa viharato, yaṃ na ceva madhurakajāto kāyo hoti, disā cassa pakkhāyanti, dhammā ca taṃ paṭibhanti, thinamiddhañcassa cittaṃ na pariyādāya tiṭṭhati, abhirato ca brahmacariyaṃ carati, na cassa hoti dhammesu vicikicchā.**“That’s how it is, mendicant, when your sense doors are guarded, you’re moderate in eating, you’re dedicated to wakefulness, you’re able to discern skillful qualities, and you pursue the development of the qualities that lead to awakening in the evening and toward dawn. Your body doesn’t feel like it’s drugged. You’re not disorientated, the teachings spring to mind, and dullness and drowsiness don’t fill your mind. You live the spiritual life satisfied, and have no doubts about the teachings.*";
P_HTM[1468]="*Tasmātiha vo, bhikkhave, evaṃ sikkhitabbaṃ:**So you should train like this:*";
P_HTM[1469]="*‘indriyesu guttadvārā bhavissāma, bhojane mattaññuno, jāgariyaṃ anuyuttā, vipassakā kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ, pubbarattāpararattaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharissāmā’ti.**‘We will guard our sense doors, eat in moderation, be dedicated to wakefulness, discern skillful qualities, and pursue the development of the qualities that lead to awakening in the evening and toward dawn.’*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Evañhi vo, bhikkhave, sikkhitabban”ti.**That’s how you should train.”*";
P_HTM[1471]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1472]="*7. Abhiṇhapaccavekkhitabbaṭhānasuttaṃ**Subjects for Regular Reviewing*";
P_HTM[1473]="*“Pañcimāni, bhikkhave, ṭhānāni abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbāni itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**“Mendicants, a woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate should often review these five subjects.*";
P_HTM[1474]="*Katamāni pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1475]="*‘Jarādhammomhi, jaraṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**‘I am liable to grow old, I am not exempt from old age.’ A woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate should often review this.*";
P_HTM[1476]="*‘Byādhidhammomhi, byādhiṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**‘I am liable to get sick, I am not exempt from sickness.’ …*";
P_HTM[1477]="*‘Maraṇadhammomhi, maraṇaṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**‘I am liable to die, I am not exempt from death.’ …*";
P_HTM[1478]="*‘Sabbehi me piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**‘I must be parted and separated from all I hold dear and beloved.’ …*";
P_HTM[1479]="*‘Kammassakomhi, kammadāyādo kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇo.**‘I am the owner of my deeds and heir to my deeds. Deeds are my womb, my relative, and my refuge.*";
P_HTM[1480]="*Yaṃ kammaṃ karissāmi—kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā—**I shall be the heir of whatever deeds I do, whether good or bad.’*";
P_HTM[1481]="*tassa dāyādo bhavissāmī’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**A woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate should often review this.*";
P_HTM[1482]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘jarādhammomhi, jaraṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā?**What is the advantage for a woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to grow old, I am not exempt from old age’?*";
P_HTM[1483]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ yobbane yobbanamado, yena madena mattā kāyena duccaritaṃ caranti, vācāya duccaritaṃ caranti, manasā duccaritaṃ caranti.**There are sentient beings who, intoxicated with the vanity of youth, do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1484]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato yo yobbane yobbanamado so sabbaso vā pahīyati tanu vā pana hoti.**Reviewing this subject often, they entirely give up the vanity of youth, or at least reduce it.*";
P_HTM[1485]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘jarādhammomhi, jaraṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**This is the advantage for a woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to grow old, I am not exempt from old age’.*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘byādhidhammomhi, byādhiṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā?**What is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to get sick, I am not exempt from sickness’?*";
P_HTM[1487]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ ārogye ārogyamado, yena madena mattā kāyena duccaritaṃ caranti, vācāya duccaritaṃ caranti, manasā duccaritaṃ caranti.**There are sentient beings who, drunk on the vanity of health, do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1488]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato yo ārogye ārogyamado so sabbaso vā pahīyati tanu vā pana hoti.**Reviewing this subject often, they entirely give up the vanity of health, or at least reduce it.*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘byādhidhammomhi, byādhiṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**This is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to get sick, I am not exempt from sickness’.*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘maraṇadhammomhi, maraṇaṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā?**What is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to die, I am not exempt from death’?*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ jīvite jīvitamado, yena madena mattā kāyena duccaritaṃ caranti, vācāya duccaritaṃ caranti, manasā duccaritaṃ caranti.**There are sentient beings who, drunk on the vanity of life, do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1492]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato yo jīvite jīvitamado so sabbaso vā pahīyati tanu vā pana hoti.**Reviewing this subject often, they entirely give up the vanity of life, or at least reduce it.*";
P_HTM[1493]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘maraṇadhammomhi, maraṇaṃ anatīto’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**This is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I am liable to die, I am not exempt from death’.*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘sabbehi me piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā?**What is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I must be parted and separated from all I hold dear and beloved’?*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ piyesu manāpesu yo chandarāgo yena rāgena rattā kāyena duccaritaṃ caranti, vācāya duccaritaṃ caranti, manasā duccaritaṃ caranti.**There are sentient beings who, aroused by desire and lust for their dear and beloved, do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato yo piyesu manāpesu chandarāgo so sabbaso vā pahīyati tanu vā pana hoti.**Reviewing this subject often, they entirely give up desire and lust for their dear and beloved, or at least reduce it.*";
P_HTM[1497]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘sabbehi me piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.**This is the advantage of often reviewing this: ‘I must be parted and separated from all I hold dear and beloved’.*";
P_HTM[1498]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘kammassakomhi, kammadāyādo kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇo, yaṃ kammaṃ karissāmi—**What is the advantage of often reflecting like this: ‘I am the owner of my deeds and heir to my deeds. Deeds are my womb, my relative, and my refuge.*";
P_HTM[1499]="*kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā—tassa dāyādo bhavissāmī’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā?**I shall be the heir of whatever deeds I do, whether good or bad’?*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ kāyaduccaritaṃ vacīduccaritaṃ manoduccaritaṃ.**There are sentient beings who do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[1501]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato sabbaso vā duccaritaṃ pahīyati tanu vā pana hoti.**Reviewing this subject often, they entirely give up bad conduct, or at least reduce it.*";
P_HTM[1502]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, atthavasaṃ paṭicca ‘kammassakomhi, kammadāyādo kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇo, yaṃ kammaṃ karissāmi—**This is the advantage for a woman or a man, a layperson or a renunciate of often reflecting like this: ‘I am the owner of my deeds and heir to my deeds. Deeds are my womb, my relative, and my refuge.*";
P_HTM[1503]="*kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā—**I shall be the heir of whatever deeds I do, whether good or bad.’*";
P_HTM[1504]="*tassa dāyādo bhavissāmī’ti abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ itthiyā vā purisena vā gahaṭṭhena vā pabbajitena vā.* **";
P_HTM[1505]="*Sa kho so, bhikkhave, ariyasāvako iti paṭisañcikkhati:**Then that noble disciple reflects:*";
P_HTM[1506]="*‘na kho ahaññeveko jarādhammo jaraṃ anatīto, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbe sattā jarādhammā jaraṃ anatītā’ti.**‘It’s not just me who is liable to grow old, not being exempt from old age. For all sentient beings grow old according to their nature, as long as they come and go, pass away and are reborn.’*";
P_HTM[1507]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato maggo sañjāyati.**When they review this subject often, the path is born in them.*";
P_HTM[1508]="*So taṃ maggaṃ āsevati bhāveti bahulīkaroti.**They cultivate, develop, and make much of it.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Tassa taṃ maggaṃ āsevato bhāvayato bahulīkaroto saṃyojanāni sabbaso pahīyanti anusayā byantīhonti.**By doing so, they give up the fetters and eliminate the underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1510]="*‘Na kho ahaññeveko byādhidhammo byādhiṃ anatīto, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbe sattā byādhidhammā byādhiṃ anatītā’ti.**‘It’s not just me who is liable to get sick, not being exempt from sickness. For all sentient beings get sick according to their nature, as long as they come and go, pass away and are reborn.’*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato maggo sañjāyati.**When they review this subject often, the path is born in them.*";
P_HTM[1512]="*So taṃ maggaṃ āsevati bhāveti bahulīkaroti.**They cultivate, develop, and make much of it.*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Tassa taṃ maggaṃ āsevato bhāvayato bahulīkaroto saṃyojanāni sabbaso pahīyanti, anusayā byantīhonti.**By doing so, they give up the fetters and eliminate the underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1514]="*‘Na kho ahaññeveko maraṇadhammo maraṇaṃ anatīto, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbe sattā maraṇadhammā maraṇaṃ anatītā’ti.**‘It’s not just me who is liable to die, not being exempt from death. For all sentient beings die according to their nature, as long as they come and go, pass away and are reborn.’*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato maggo sañjāyati.**When they review this subject often, the path is born in them.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*So taṃ maggaṃ āsevati bhāveti bahulīkaroti.**They cultivate, develop, and make much of it.*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Tassa taṃ maggaṃ āsevato bhāvayato bahulīkaroto saṃyojanāni sabbaso pahīyanti, anusayā byantīhonti.**By doing so, they give up the fetters and eliminate the underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1518]="*‘Na kho mayhevekassa sabbehi piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo, atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbesaṃ sattānaṃ piyehi manāpehi nānābhāvo vinābhāvo’ti.**‘It’s not just me who must be parted and separated from all I hold dear and beloved. For all sentient beings must be parted and separated from all they hold dear and beloved, as long as they come and go, pass away and are reborn.’*";
P_HTM[1519]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato maggo sañjāyati.**When they review this subject often, the path is born in them.*";
P_HTM[1520]="*So taṃ maggaṃ āsevati bhāveti bahulīkaroti.**They cultivate, develop, and make much of it.*";
P_HTM[1521]="*Tassa taṃ maggaṃ āsevato bhāvayato bahulīkaroto saṃyojanāni sabbaso pahīyanti, anusayā byantīhonti.**By doing so, they give up the fetters and eliminate the underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1522]="*‘Na kho ahaññeveko kammassako kammadāyādo kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇo, yaṃ kammaṃ karissāmi—kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā—tassa dāyādo bhavissāmi;**‘It’s not just me who shall be the owner of my deeds and heir to my deeds.*";
P_HTM[1523]="*atha kho yāvatā sattānaṃ āgati gati cuti upapatti sabbe sattā kammassakā kammadāyādā kammayoni kammabandhu kammapaṭisaraṇā, yaṃ kammaṃ karissanti—kalyāṇaṃ vā pāpakaṃ vā—tassa dāyādā bhavissantī’ti.**For all sentient beings shall be the owners of their deeds and heirs to their deeds, as long as they come and go, pass away and are reborn.’*";
P_HTM[1524]="*Tassa taṃ ṭhānaṃ abhiṇhaṃ paccavekkhato maggo sañjāyati.**When they review this subject often, the path is born in them.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*So taṃ maggaṃ āsevati bhāveti bahulīkaroti.**They cultivate, develop, and make much of it.*";
P_HTM[1526]="*Tassa taṃ maggaṃ āsevato bhāvayato bahulīkaroto saṃyojanāni sabbaso pahīyanti, anusayā byantīhontīti.**By doing so, they give up the fetters and eliminate the underlying tendencies.*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Byādhidhammā jarādhammā,**For others, sickness is natural,*";
P_HTM[1528]="*atho maraṇadhammino;**and so are old age and death.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*Yathā dhammā tathā sattā,**Though this is how their nature is,*";
P_HTM[1530]="*jigucchanti puthujjanā.**ordinary people feel disgusted.*";
P_HTM[1531]="*Ahañce taṃ jiguccheyyaṃ,**If I were to be disgusted*";
P_HTM[1532]="*evaṃ dhammesu pāṇisu;**with creatures whose nature is such,*";
P_HTM[1533]="*Na metaṃ patirūpassa,**it would not be appropriate for me,*";
P_HTM[1534]="*mama evaṃ vihārino.**since my life is just the same.*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Sohaṃ evaṃ viharanto,**Living in such a way,*";
P_HTM[1536]="*ñatvā dhammaṃ nirūpadhiṃ;**I understood the reality without attachments.*";
P_HTM[1537]="*Ārogye yobbanasmiñca,**I mastered all vanities—*";
P_HTM[1538]="*jīvitasmiñca ye madā.**of health, of youth,*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Sabbe made abhibhosmi,**and even of life—*";
P_HTM[1540]="*Nekkhammaṃ daṭṭhu khemato;**seeing safety in renunciation.*";
P_HTM[1541]="*Tassa me ahu ussāho,**Zeal sprang up in me*";
P_HTM[1542]="*Nibbānaṃ abhipassato.**as I looked to extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1543]="*Nāhaṃ bhabbo etarahi,**Now I’m unable*";
P_HTM[1544]="*Kāmāni paṭisevituṃ;**to indulge in sensual pleasures;*";
P_HTM[1545]="*Anivatti bhavissāmi,**there’s no turning back,*";
P_HTM[1546]="*Brahmacariyaparāyaṇo”ti.**until the spiritual life is complete.”*";
P_HTM[1547]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1548]="*8. Licchavikumārakasuttaṃ**The Licchavi Youths*";
P_HTM[1549]="*Ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[1550]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Vesālī for alms.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto mahāvanaṃ ajjhogāhetvā aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle divāvihāraṃ nisīdi.**Then after the meal, on his return from alms-round, he plunged deep into the Great Wood and sat at the root of a tree for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[1552]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā licchavikumārakā sajjāni dhanūni ādāya kukkurasaṅghaparivutā mahāvane anucaṅkamamānā anuvicaramānā addasu bhagavantaṃ aññatarasmiṃ rukkhamūle nisinnaṃ;**Now at that time several Licchavi youths took strung bows and, escorted by a pack of hounds, were going for a walk in the Great Wood when they saw the Buddha seated at the root of a tree.*";
P_HTM[1553]="*disvāna sajjāni dhanūni nikkhipitvā kukkurasaṅghaṃ ekamantaṃ uyyojetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā tuṇhībhūtā tuṇhībhūtā pañjalikā bhagavantaṃ payirupāsanti.**When they saw him, they put down their strung bows, tied their hounds up to one side, and went up to him. They bowed and silently paid homage to the Buddha with joined palms.*";
P_HTM[1554]="*Tena kho pana samayena mahānāmo licchavi mahāvane jaṅghāvihāraṃ anucaṅkamamāno addasa te licchavikumārake tuṇhībhūte tuṇhībhūte pañjalike bhagavantaṃ payirupāsante;**Now at that time Mahānāma the Licchavi was going for a walk in the Great Wood when he saw those Licchavi youths silently paying homage to the Buddha with joined palms.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*disvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Seeing this, he went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side,*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho mahānāmo licchavi udānaṃ udānesi:**and was inspired to exclaim,*";
P_HTM[1557]="*“bhavissanti vajjī, bhavissanti vajjī”ti.**“They will make it as Vajjis! They will make it as Vajjis!”*";
P_HTM[1558]="*“Kiṃ pana tvaṃ, mahānāma, evaṃ vadesi:**“But Mahānāma, why do you say that they will make it as Vajjis?”*";
P_HTM[1559]="*‘bhavissanti vajjī, bhavissanti vajjī’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1560]="*“Ime, bhante, licchavikumārakā caṇḍā pharusā apānubhā.**“Sir, these Licchavi youths are violent, harsh, and brash.*";
P_HTM[1561]="*Yānipi tāni kulesu paheṇakāni pahīyanti, ucchūti vā badarāti vā pūvāti vā modakāti vā saṅkulikāti vā, tāni vilumpitvā vilumpitvā khādanti;**Whenever sweets are left out for families—sugar-cane, jujube fruits, pancakes, pies, or fritters—they filch them and eat them up.*";
P_HTM[1562]="*kulitthīnampi kulakumārīnampi pacchāliyaṃ khipanti.**And they hit women and girls of good families on their backs.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Te dānime tuṇhībhūtā tuṇhībhūtā pañjalikā bhagavantaṃ payirupāsantī”ti.**But now they’re silently paying homage to the Buddha with joined palms.”*";
P_HTM[1564]="*“Yassa kassaci, mahānāma, kulaputtassa pañca dhammā saṃvijjanti—* **";
P_HTM[1565]="*yadi vā rañño khattiyassa muddhāvasittassa, yadi vā raṭṭhikassa pettanikassa, yadi vā senāya senāpatikassa, yadi vā gāmagāmaṇikassa, yadi vā pūgagāmaṇikassa, ye vā pana kulesu paccekādhipaccaṃ kārenti, vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**“Mahānāma, you can expect only growth, not decline, when you find five qualities in any gentleman—whether he’s an anointed king, an appointed or hereditary official, an army general, a village chief, a guild chief, or a ruler of his own clan.*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1567]="*Idha, mahānāma, kulaputto uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi mātāpitaro sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti.**Firstly, a gentleman uses his legitimate wealth—earned by his efforts and initiative, built up with his own hands, gathered by the sweat of the brow—to honor, respect, esteem, and venerate his mother and father.*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Tamenaṃ mātāpitaro sakkatā garukatā mānitā pūjitā kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti:**Honored in this way, his mother and father love him with a good heart, wishing:*";
P_HTM[1569]="*‘ciraṃ jīva, dīghamāyuṃ pālehī’ti.**‘Live long! Stay alive for a long time!’*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Mātāpitānukampitassa, mahānāma, kulaputtassa vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**When a gentleman is loved by his mother and father, you can expect only growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahānāma, kulaputto uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi puttadāradāsakammakaraporise sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti.**Furthermore, a gentleman uses his legitimate wealth to honor, respect, esteem, and venerate his wives and children, bondservants, workers, and staff.*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Tamenaṃ puttadāradāsakammakaraporisā sakkatā garukatā mānitā pūjitā kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti:**Honored in this way, his wives and children, bondservants, workers, and staff love him with a good heart, wishing:*";
P_HTM[1573]="*‘ciraṃ jīva, dīghamāyuṃ pālehī’ti.**‘Live long! Stay alive for a long time!’*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Puttadāradāsakammakaraporisānukampitassa, mahānāma, kulaputtassa vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**When a gentleman is loved by his wives and children, bondservants, workers, and staff, you can expect only growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahānāma, kulaputto uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi khettakammantasāmantasabyohāre sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti.**Furthermore, a gentleman uses his legitimate wealth to honor, respect, esteem, and venerate those who work the neighboring fields, and those he does business with.*";
P_HTM[1576]="*Tamenaṃ khettakammantasāmantasabyohārā sakkatā garukatā mānitā pūjitā kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti:**Honored in this way, those who work the neighboring fields, and those he does business with love him with a good heart, wishing:*";
P_HTM[1577]="*‘ciraṃ jīva, dīghamāyuṃ pālehī’ti.**‘Live long! Stay alive for a long time!’*";
P_HTM[1578]="*Khettakammantasāmantasabyohārānukampitassa, mahānāma, kulaputtassa vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**When a gentleman is loved by those who work the neighboring fields, and those he does business with, you can expect only growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1579]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahānāma, kulaputto uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi yāvatā balipaṭiggāhikā devatā sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti.**Furthermore, a gentleman uses his legitimate wealth to honor, respect, esteem, and venerate the deities who receive spirit-offerings.*";
P_HTM[1580]="*Tamenaṃ balipaṭiggāhikā devatā sakkatā garukatā mānitā pūjitā kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti:**Honored in this way, the deities who receive spirit-offerings love him with a good heart, wishing:*";
P_HTM[1581]="*‘ciraṃ jīva, dīghamāyuṃ pālehī’ti.**‘Live long! Stay alive for a long time!’*";
P_HTM[1582]="*devatānukampitassa, mahānāma, kulaputtassa vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**When a gentleman is loved by the deities, you can expect only growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahānāma, kulaputto uṭṭhānavīriyādhigatehi bhogehi bāhābalaparicitehi sedāvakkhittehi dhammikehi dhammaladdhehi samaṇabrāhmaṇe sakkaroti garuṃ karoti māneti pūjeti.**Furthermore, a gentleman uses his legitimate wealth to honor, respect, esteem, and venerate ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1584]="*Tamenaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇā sakkatā garukatā mānitā pūjitā kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti:**Honored in this way, ascetics and brahmins love him with a good heart, wishing:*";
P_HTM[1585]="*‘ciraṃ jīva, dīghamāyuṃ pālehī’ti.**‘Live long! Stay alive for a long time!’*";
P_HTM[1586]="*Samaṇabrāhmaṇānukampitassa, mahānāma, kulaputtassa vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihāni.**When a gentleman is loved by ascetics and brahmins, you can expect only growth, not decline.*";
P_HTM[1587]="*Yassa kassaci, mahānāma, kulaputtassa ime pañca dhammā saṃvijjanti—**You can expect only growth, not decline, when you find these five qualities in any gentleman—*";
P_HTM[1588]="*yadi vā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa, yadi vā raṭṭhikassa pettanikassa, yadi vā senāya senāpatikassa, yadi vā gāmagāmaṇikassa, yadi vā pūgagāmaṇikassa, ye vā pana kulesu paccekādhipaccaṃ kārenti, vuddhiyeva pāṭikaṅkhā, no parihānīti.**whether he’s an anointed king, an appointed or hereditary official, an army general, a village chief, a guild chief, or a ruler of his own clan.*";
P_HTM[1589]="*Mātāpitukiccakaro,**He’s always dutiful to his mother and father,*";
P_HTM[1590]="*puttadārahito sadā;**and for the good of his wives and children.*";
P_HTM[1591]="*Antojanassa atthāya,**He looks after those in his household,*";
P_HTM[1592]="*ye cassa anujīvino.**and those dependent on him for their livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*Ubhinnañceva atthāya,**A kind and ethical person*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Vadaññū hoti sīlavā;**looks after the welfare of relatives—*";
P_HTM[1595]="*Ñātīnaṃ pubbapetānaṃ,**both those who have passed away,*";
P_HTM[1596]="*Diṭṭhe dhamme ca jīvataṃ.**and those alive at present.*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Samaṇānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ,**While living at home, an astute person*";
P_HTM[1598]="*devatānañca paṇḍito;**uses legitimate means to give rise to joy*";
P_HTM[1599]="*Vittisañjanano hoti,**for ascetics, brahmins,*";
P_HTM[1600]="*dhammena gharamāvasaṃ.**and also the gods.*";
P_HTM[1601]="*So karitvāna kalyāṇaṃ,**Having done good,*";
P_HTM[1602]="*pujjo hoti pasaṃsiyo;**he’s venerable and praiseworthy.*";
P_HTM[1603]="*Idheva naṃ pasaṃsanti,**They praise him in this life,*";
P_HTM[1604]="*pecca sagge pamodatī”ti.**and he departs to rejoice in heaven.”*";
P_HTM[1605]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1606]="*9. Paṭhamavuḍḍhapabbajitasuttaṃ**Gone Forth When Old (1st)*";
P_HTM[1607]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato dullabho vuḍḍhapabbajito.**“Mendicants, it’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who has five qualities.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Dullabho, bhikkhave, vuḍḍhapabbajito nipuṇo, dullabho ākappasampanno, dullabho bahussuto, dullabho dhammakathiko, dullabho vinayadharo.**It’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who is sophisticated, well-presented, and learned, who can teach Dhamma, and has memorized the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[1610]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato dullabho vuḍḍhapabbajitoti.**It’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who has these five qualities.”*";
P_HTM[1611]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1612]="*10. Dutiyavuḍḍhapabbajitasuttaṃ**Gone Forth When Old (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1613]="*Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato dullabho vuḍḍhapabbajito.**“Mendicants, it’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who has five qualities.*";
P_HTM[1614]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Dullabho, bhikkhave, vuḍḍhapabbajito suvaco, dullabho suggahitaggāhī, dullabho padakkhiṇaggāhī, dullabho dhammakathiko, dullabho vinayadharo.**It’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who is easy to admonish, retains what they learn, and learns respectfully, who can teach the Dhamma, and has memorized the texts on monastic training.*";
P_HTM[1616]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato dullabho vuḍḍhapabbajito”ti.**It’s hard to find someone gone forth when old who has these five qualities.”*";
P_HTM[1617]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1618]="*Nīvaraṇavaggo paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1619]="*Āvaraṇaṃ rāsi aṅgāni,* **";
P_HTM[1620]="*samayaṃ mātuputtikā;* **";
P_HTM[1621]="*Upajjhā ṭhānā licchavi,* **";
P_HTM[1622]="*kumārā aparā duveti.* **";
P_HTM[1623]="*13. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Perceptions*";
P_HTM[1624]="*1. Paṭhamasaññāsuttaṃ**Perceptions (1st)*";
P_HTM[1625]="*“Pañcimā, bhikkhave, saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā.**“Mendicants, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1626]="*Katamā pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Asubhasaññā, maraṇasaññā, ādīnavasaññā, āhāre paṭikūlasaññā, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā—**The perceptions of ugliness, death, drawbacks, repulsiveness of food, and dissatisfaction with the whole world.*";
P_HTM[1628]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, pañca saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā”ti.**These five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[1629]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1630]="*2. Dutiyasaññāsuttaṃ**Perceptions (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1631]="*“Pañcimā, bhikkhave, saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā.**“Mendicants, these five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.*";
P_HTM[1632]="*Katamā pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Aniccasaññā, anattasaññā, maraṇasaññā, āhāre paṭikūlasaññā, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññā—**The perceptions of impermanence, not-self, death, repulsiveness of food, and dissatisfaction with the whole world.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*imā kho, bhikkhave, pañca saññā bhāvitā bahulīkatā mahapphalā honti mahānisaṃsā amatogadhā amatapariyosānā”ti.**These five perceptions, when developed and cultivated, are very fruitful and beneficial. They culminate in the deathless and end with the deathless.”*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1636]="*3. Paṭhamavaḍḍhisuttaṃ**Growth (1st)*";
P_HTM[1637]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamāno ariyasāvako ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati, sārādāyī ca hoti varādāyī ca kāyassa.**“Mendicants, a male noble disciple who grows in five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[1638]="*Katamāhi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Saddhāya vaḍḍhati, sīlena vaḍḍhati, sutena vaḍḍhati, cāgena vaḍḍhati, paññāya vaḍḍhati—**He grows in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*imāhi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamāno ariyasāvako ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati, sārādāyī ca hoti varādāyī ca kāyassā”ti.**A male noble disciple who grows in these five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*“Saddhāya sīlena ca yo pavaḍḍhati,**He who grows in faith and ethics,*";
P_HTM[1642]="*Paññāya cāgena sutena cūbhayaṃ;**wisdom, and both generosity and learning—*";
P_HTM[1643]="*So tādiso sappuriso vicakkhaṇo,**a good man such as he sees clearly,*";
P_HTM[1644]="*Ādīyatī sāramidheva attano”ti.**and takes on what is essential for himself in this life.”*";
P_HTM[1645]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1646]="*4. Dutiyavaḍḍhisuttaṃ**Growth (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1647]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamānā ariyasāvikā ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati, sārādāyinī ca hoti varādāyinī ca kāyassa.**“Mendicants, a female noble disciple who grows in five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Katamāhi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1649]="*Saddhāya vaḍḍhati, sīlena vaḍḍhati, sutena vaḍḍhati, cāgena vaḍḍhati, paññāya vaḍḍhati—**She grows in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1650]="*imāhi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi vaḍḍhīhi vaḍḍhamānā ariyasāvikā ariyāya vaḍḍhiyā vaḍḍhati, sārādāyinī ca hoti varādāyinī ca kāyassāti.**A female noble disciple who grows in these five ways grows nobly, taking on what is essential and excellent in this life.*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Saddhāya sīlena ca yā pavaḍḍhati,**She who grows in faith and ethics,*";
P_HTM[1652]="*Paññāya cāgena sutena cūbhayaṃ;**wisdom, and both generosity and learning—*";
P_HTM[1653]="*Sā tādisī sīlavatī upāsikā,**a virtuous laywoman such as she*";
P_HTM[1654]="*Ādīyatī sāramidheva attano”ti.**takes on what is essential for herself in this life.”*";
P_HTM[1655]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1656]="*5. Sākacchasuttaṃ**Discussion*";
P_HTM[1657]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu alaṃsākaccho sabrahmacārīnaṃ.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is fit to hold a discussion with their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[1658]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1659]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā ca sīlasampanno hoti, sīlasampadāya kathāya ca āgataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**A mendicant is personally accomplished in ethics, and answers questions that come up when discussing accomplishment in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*attanā ca samādhisampanno hoti, samādhisampadāya kathāya ca āgataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in immersion, and they answer questions that come up when discussing accomplishment in immersion.*";
P_HTM[1661]="*attanā ca paññāsampanno hoti, paññāsampadāya kathāya ca āgataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in wisdom, and they answer questions that come up when discussing accomplishment in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*attanā ca vimuttisampanno hoti, vimuttisampadāya kathāya ca āgataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in freedom, and they answer questions that come up when discussing accomplishment in freedom.*";
P_HTM[1663]="*attanā ca vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya kathāya ca āgataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti.**They’re personally accomplished in the knowledge and vision of freedom, and they answer questions that come up when discussing accomplishment in the knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu alaṃsākaccho sabrahmacārīnan”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is fit to hold a discussion with their spiritual companions.”*";
P_HTM[1665]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1666]="*6. Sājīvasuttaṃ**Sharing Life*";
P_HTM[1667]="*“Pañcahi, bhikkhave, dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu alaṃsājīvo sabrahmacārīnaṃ.**“Mendicants, a mendicant with five qualities is fit to share their life with their spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1669]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attanā ca sīlasampanno hoti, sīlasampadāya kathāya ca kataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**A mendicant is personally accomplished in ethics, and answers questions posed when discussing accomplishment in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*attanā ca samādhisampanno hoti, samādhisampadāya kathāya ca kataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in immersion, and they answer questions posed when discussing accomplishment in immersion.*";
P_HTM[1671]="*attanā ca paññāsampanno hoti, paññāsampadāya kathāya ca kataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in wisdom, and they answer questions posed when discussing accomplishment in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1672]="*attanā ca vimuttisampanno hoti, vimuttisampadāya kathāya ca kataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti;**They’re personally accomplished in freedom, and they answer questions posed when discussing accomplishment in freedom.*";
P_HTM[1673]="*attanā ca vimuttiñāṇadassanasampanno hoti, vimuttiñāṇadassanasampadāya kathāya ca kataṃ pañhaṃ byākattā hoti.**They’re personally accomplished in the knowledge and vision of freedom, and they answer questions posed when discussing accomplishment in the knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[1674]="*Imehi kho, bhikkhave, pañcahi dhammehi samannāgato bhikkhu alaṃsājīvo sabrahmacārīnan”ti.**A mendicant with these five qualities is fit to share their life with their spiritual companions.”*";
P_HTM[1675]="*Chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1676]="*7. Paṭhamaiddhipādasuttaṃ**Bases of Psychic Power (1st)*";
P_HTM[1677]="*“Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā pañca dhamme bhāveti, pañca dhamme bahulīkaroti, tassa dvinnaṃ phalānaṃ aññataraṃ phalaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**“Mendicants, any monk or nun who develops and cultivates five qualities can expect one of two results:*";
P_HTM[1678]="*diṭṭheva dhamme aññā, sati vā upādisese anāgāmitā.**enlightenment in the present life, or if there’s something left over, non-return.*";
P_HTM[1679]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**A mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort …*";
P_HTM[1681]="*vīriyasamādhi … pe …**A mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy, and active effort …*";
P_HTM[1682]="*cittasamādhi …**A mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to mental development, and active effort …*";
P_HTM[1683]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**A mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[1684]="*ussoḷhiññeva pañcamiṃ.**And the fifth is sheer vigor.*";
P_HTM[1685]="*Yo hi koci, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vā bhikkhunī vā ime pañca dhamme bhāveti, ime pañca dhamme bahulīkaroti, tassa dvinnaṃ phalānaṃ aññataraṃ phalaṃ pāṭikaṅkhaṃ—**Any monk or nun who develops and cultivates these five qualities can expect one of two results:*";
P_HTM[1686]="*diṭṭheva dhamme aññā, sati vā upādisese anāgāmitā”ti.**enlightenment in the present life, or if there’s something left over, non-return.”*";
P_HTM[1687]="*Sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1688]="*8. Dutiyaiddhipādasuttaṃ**Bases of Psychic Power (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1689]="*“Pubbevāhaṃ, bhikkhave, sambodhā anabhisambuddho bodhisattova samāno pañca dhamme bhāvesiṃ, pañca dhamme bahulīkāsiṃ.**“Mendicants, before my awakening—when I was still not awake but intent on awakening—I developed and cultivated five things.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1691]="*Chandasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāvesiṃ, vīriyasamādhi … cittasamādhi … vīmaṃsāsamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāvesiṃ, ussoḷhiññeva pañcamiṃ.**The basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort … the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy, and active effort … the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to mental development, and active effort … the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to inquiry, and active effort. And the fifth is sheer vigor.*";
P_HTM[1692]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, imesaṃ ussoḷhipañcamānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā yassa yassa abhiññāsacchikaraṇīyassa dhammassa cittaṃ abhininnāmesiṃ abhiññāsacchikiriyāya,**When I had developed and cultivated these five things, with vigor as fifth,*";
P_HTM[1693]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇiṃ sati sati āyatane.**I became capable of realizing anything that can be realized by insight to which I extended the mind, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[1694]="*So sace ākaṅkhiṃ: ‘anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhaveyyaṃ … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteyyan’ti,**If I wished: ‘May I multiply myself and become one again … controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.’*";
P_HTM[1695]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇiṃ sati sati āyatane.**I was capable of realizing it, in each and every case.*";
P_HTM[1696]="*So sace ākaṅkhiṃ … pe … ‘āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihareyyan’ti,**If I wished: … ‘May I realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with my own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[1697]="*tatra tatreva sakkhibhabbataṃ pāpuṇiṃ sati sati āyatane”ti.**I was capable of realizing it, in each and every case.”*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1699]="*9. Nibbidāsuttaṃ**Disillusionment*";
P_HTM[1700]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, these five things, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu asubhānupassī kāye viharati, āhāre paṭikūlasaññī, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññī, sabbasaṅkhāresu aniccānupassī, maraṇasaññā kho panassa ajjhattaṃ sūpaṭṭhitā hoti.**A mendicant meditates observing the ugliness of the body, perceives the repulsiveness of food, perceives dissatisfaction with the whole world, observes the impermanence of all conditions, and has well established the perception of their own death.*";
P_HTM[1703]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These five things, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.”*";
P_HTM[1704]="*Navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1705]="*10. Āsavakkhayasuttaṃ**The Ending of Defilements*";
P_HTM[1706]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattanti.**“Mendicants, these five things, when developed and cultivated, lead to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1707]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1708]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu asubhānupassī kāye viharati, āhāre paṭikūlasaññī, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññī, sabbasaṅkhāresu aniccānupassī, maraṇasaññā kho panassa ajjhattaṃ sūpaṭṭhitā hoti.**A mendicant meditates observing the ugliness of the body, perceives the repulsiveness of food, perceives dissatisfaction with the whole world, observes the impermanence of all conditions, and has well established the perception of their own death.*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattantī”ti.**These five things, when developed and cultivated, lead to the ending of defilements.”*";
P_HTM[1710]="*Dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1711]="*Saññāvaggo dutiyo.* **";
P_HTM[1712]="*Dve ca saññā dve vaḍḍhī ca,* **";
P_HTM[1713]="*sākacchena ca sājīvaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1714]="*Iddhipādā ca dve vuttā,* **";
P_HTM[1715]="*nibbidā cāsavakkhayāti.* **";
P_HTM[1716]="*13. Rāgapeyyālaṃ**Warriors*";
P_HTM[1717]="*1. Paṭhamacetovimuttiphalasuttaṃ**Freedom of Heart is the Fruit (1st)*";
P_HTM[1718]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā cetovimuttiphalā ca honti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca honti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca.**“Mendicants, these five things, when developed and cultivated, have freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as their fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[1719]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu asubhānupassī kāye viharati, āhāre paṭikūlasaññī, sabbaloke anabhiratasaññī, sabbasaṅkhāresu aniccānupassī, maraṇasaññā kho panassa ajjhattaṃ sūpaṭṭhitā hoti.**A mendicant meditates observing the ugliness of the body, perceives the repulsiveness of food, perceives dissatisfaction with the whole world, observes the impermanence of all conditions, and has well established the perception of their own death.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā cetovimuttiphalā ca honti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca honti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca.**These five things, when developed and cultivated, have freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as their fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cetovimutto ca hoti paññāvimutto ca hoti—**When a mendicant has freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1723]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ‘bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho itipi, saṃkiṇṇaparikho itipi, abbūḷhesiko itipi, niraggaḷo itipi, ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto itipi’.**they’re called a mendicant who has lifted up the cross-bar, filled in the trench, and pulled up the pillar; they’re unbarred, a noble one with banner and burden put down, detached.*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho hoti?**And how has a mendicant lifted the cross-bar?*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno avijjā pahīnā hoti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**It’s when a mendicant has given up ignorance, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has lifted the cross-bar.*";
P_HTM[1727]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saṃkiṇṇaparikho hoti?**And how has a mendicant filled in the trench?*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ponobhaviko jātisaṃsāro pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṃkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**It’s when a mendicant has given up transmigrating through births in future lives, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saṃkiṇṇaparikho hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has filled in the trench.*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abbūḷhesiko hoti?**And how has a mendicant pulled up the pillar?*";
P_HTM[1731]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā pahīnā hoti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.**It’s when a mendicant has given up craving, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1732]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abbūḷhesiko hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has pulled up the pillar.*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu niraggaḷo hoti?**And how is a mendicant unbarred?*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni pahīnāni honti ucchinnamūlāni tālāvatthukatāni anabhāvaṅkatāni āyatiṃ anuppādadhammāni.**It’s when a mendicant has given up the five lower fetters, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, obliterated them, so they’re unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1735]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu niraggaḷo hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is unbarred.*";
P_HTM[1736]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto hoti?**And how is a mendicant a noble one with banner and burden put down, detached?*";
P_HTM[1737]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno asmimāno pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.**It’s when a mendicant has given up the conceit ‘I am’, cut it off at the root, made it like a palm stump, obliterated it, so it’s unable to arise in the future.*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto hotī”ti.**That’s how a mendicant is a noble one with banner and burden put down, detached.”*";
P_HTM[1739]="*Paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1740]="*2. Dutiyacetovimuttiphalasuttaṃ**Freedom of Heart is the Fruit (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1741]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā cetovimuttiphalā ca honti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca honti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca.**“Mendicants, these five things, when developed and cultivated, have freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as their fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Aniccasaññā, anicce dukkhasaññā, dukkhe anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā—**The perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of giving up, and the perception of fading away.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca dhammā bhāvitā bahulīkatā cetovimuttiphalā ca honti cetovimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca, paññāvimuttiphalā ca honti paññāvimuttiphalānisaṃsā ca.**These five things, when developed and cultivated, have freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom as their fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[1745]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu cetovimutto ca hoti paññāvimutto ca—**When a mendicant has freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom,*";
P_HTM[1746]="*ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhave, ‘bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho itipi, saṅkiṇṇaparikho itipi, abbūḷhesiko itipi, niraggaḷo itipi, ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto itipi’”.**they’re called a mendicant who has lifted up the cross-bar, filled in the trench, and pulled up the pillar; they’re unbarred, a noble one with banner and burden put down, detached. …”*";
P_HTM[1747]="*“Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho hoti?* **";
P_HTM[1748]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno avijjā pahīnā hoti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[1749]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ukkhittapaligho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1750]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saṅkiṇṇaparikho hoti?* **";
P_HTM[1751]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno ponobhaviko jātisaṃsāro pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1752]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu saṅkiṇṇaparikho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1753]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abbūḷhesiko hoti?* **";
P_HTM[1754]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno taṇhā pahīnā hoti ucchinnamūlā tālāvatthukatā anabhāvaṅkatā āyatiṃ anuppādadhammā.* **";
P_HTM[1755]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu abbūḷhesiko hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1756]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu niraggaḷo hoti?* **";
P_HTM[1757]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno pañcorambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni pahīnāni honti ucchinnamūlāni tālāvatthukatāni anabhāvaṅkatāni āyatiṃ anuppādadhammāni.* **";
P_HTM[1758]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu niraggaḷo hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1759]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto hoti?* **";
P_HTM[1760]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno asmimāno pahīno hoti ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo.* **";
P_HTM[1761]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu ariyo pannaddhajo pannabhāro visaṃyutto hotī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1762]="*Dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1763]="*3. Paṭhamadhammavihārīsuttaṃ**One Who Lives by the Teaching (1st)*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1765]="*“‘dhammavihārī, dhammavihārī’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘one who lives by the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, bhikkhu dhammavihārī hotī”ti?**How is one who lives by the teaching defined?”*";
P_HTM[1767]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇāti—**“Mendicant, take a mendicant who memorizes the teaching—*";
P_HTM[1768]="*suttaṃ, geyyaṃ, veyyākaraṇaṃ, gāthaṃ, udānaṃ, itivuttakaṃ, jātakaṃ, abbhutadhammaṃ, vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[1769]="*So tāya dhammapariyattiyā divasaṃ atināmeti, riñcati paṭisallānaṃ, nānuyuñjati ajjhattaṃ cetosamathaṃ.**They spend their days studying that teaching. But they neglect retreat, and are not committed to internal serenity of heart.*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu pariyattibahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who studies a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti.**Furthermore, a mendicant teaches Dhamma in detail to others as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[1772]="*So tāya dhammapaññattiyā divasaṃ atināmeti, riñcati paṭisallānaṃ, nānuyuñjati ajjhattaṃ cetosamathaṃ.**They spend their days advocating that teaching. But they neglect retreat, and are not committed to internal serenity of heart.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu paññattibahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who advocates a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1774]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant recites the teaching in detail as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[1775]="*So tena sajjhāyena divasaṃ atināmeti, riñcati paṭisallānaṃ, nānuyuñjati ajjhattaṃ cetosamathaṃ.**They spend their days reciting that teaching. But they neglect retreat, and are not committed to internal serenity of heart.*";
P_HTM[1776]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu sajjhāyabahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who recites a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati.**Furthermore, a mendicant thinks about and considers the teaching in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[1778]="*So tehi dhammavitakkehi divasaṃ atināmeti, riñcati paṭisallānaṃ, nānuyuñjati ajjhattaṃ cetosamathaṃ.**They spend their days thinking about that teaching. But they neglect retreat, and are not committed to internal serenity of heart.*";
P_HTM[1779]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu vitakkabahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who thinks a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1780]="*Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇāti—**Take a mendicant who memorizes the teaching—*";
P_HTM[1781]="*suttaṃ, geyyaṃ, veyyākaraṇaṃ, gāthaṃ, udānaṃ, itivuttakaṃ, jātakaṃ, abbhutadhammaṃ, vedallaṃ.**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[1782]="*So tāya dhammapariyattiyā na divasaṃ atināmeti, nāpi riñcati paṭisallānaṃ, anuyuñjati ajjhattaṃ cetosamathaṃ.**They don’t spend their days studying that teaching. They don’t neglect retreat, and they’re committed to internal serenity of heart.*";
P_HTM[1783]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammavihārī hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1784]="*Iti kho, bhikkhu, desito mayā pariyattibahulo, desito paññattibahulo, desito sajjhāyabahulo, desito vitakkabahulo, desito dhammavihārī.**So, mendicant, I’ve taught you the one who studies a lot, the one who advocates a lot, the one who recites a lot, the one who thinks a lot, and the one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1785]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, satthārā karaṇīyaṃ sāvakānaṃ hitesinā anukampakena anukampaṃ upādāya, kataṃ vo taṃ mayā.**Out of compassion, I’ve done what a teacher should do who wants what’s best for their disciples.*";
P_HTM[1786]="*Etāni, bhikkhu, rukkhamūlāni, etāni suññāgārāni. Jhāyatha, bhikkhu, mā pamādattha, mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha. Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**Here are these roots of trees, and here are these empty huts. Practice absorption, mendicant! Don’t be negligent! Don’t regret it later! This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1788]="*4. Dutiyadhammavihārīsuttaṃ**One Who Lives by the Teaching (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Atha kho aññataro bhikkhu yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so bhikkhu bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then a mendicant went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1790]="*“‘dhammavihārī, dhammavihārī’ti, bhante, vuccati.**“Sir, they speak of ‘one who lives by the teaching’.*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Kittāvatā nu kho, bhante, bhikkhu dhammavihārī hotī”ti?**How is one who lives by the teaching defined?”*";
P_HTM[1792]="*“Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇāti—**“Mendicant, take a mendicant who memorizes the teaching—*";
P_HTM[1793]="*suttaṃ, geyyaṃ, veyyākaraṇaṃ, gāthaṃ, udānaṃ, itivuttakaṃ, jātakaṃ, abbhutadhammaṃ, vedallaṃ;**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[1794]="*uttari cassa paññāya atthaṃ nappajānāti.**But they don’t understand the higher meaning.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu pariyattibahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who studies a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1796]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, uttari cassa paññāya atthaṃ nappajānāti.**Furthermore, a mendicant teaches Dhamma in detail to others as they learned and memorized it. But they don’t understand the higher meaning.*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu paññattibahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who advocates a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1798]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti, uttari cassa paññāya atthaṃ nappajānāti.**Furthermore, a mendicant recites the teaching in detail as they learned and memorized it. But they don’t understand the higher meaning.*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu sajjhāyabahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who recites a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1800]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhu, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati, uttari cassa paññāya atthaṃ nappajānāti.**Furthermore, a mendicant thinks about and considers the teaching in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it. But they don’t understand the higher meaning.*";
P_HTM[1801]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, bhikkhu: ‘bhikkhu vitakkabahulo, no dhammavihārī’.**That mendicant is called one who thinks a lot, not one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1802]="*Idha, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammaṃ pariyāpuṇāti—**Take a mendicant who memorizes the teaching—*";
P_HTM[1803]="*suttaṃ, geyyaṃ, veyyākaraṇaṃ, gāthaṃ, udānaṃ, itivuttakaṃ, jātakaṃ, abbhutadhammaṃ, vedallaṃ;**statements, songs, discussions, verses, inspired exclamations, legends, stories of past lives, amazing stories, and classifications.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*uttari cassa paññāya atthaṃ pajānāti.**And they do understand the higher meaning.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhu, bhikkhu dhammavihārī hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Iti kho, bhikkhu, desito mayā pariyattibahulo, desito paññattibahulo, desito sajjhāyabahulo, desito vitakkabahulo, desito dhammavihārī.**So, mendicant, I’ve taught you the one who studies a lot, the one who advocates a lot, the one who recites a lot, the one who thinks a lot, and the one who lives by the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Yaṃ kho, bhikkhu, satthārā karaṇīyaṃ sāvakānaṃ hitesinā anukampakena anukampaṃ upādāya, kataṃ vo taṃ mayā.**Out of compassion, I’ve done what a teacher should do who wants what’s best for their disciples.*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Etāni, bhikkhu, rukkhamūlāni, etāni suññāgārāni. Jhāyatha bhikkhu, mā pamādattha, mā pacchā vippaṭisārino ahuvattha. Ayaṃ vo amhākaṃ anusāsanī”ti.**Here are these roots of trees, and here are these empty huts. Practice absorption, mendicant! Don’t be negligent! Don’t regret it later! This is my instruction to you.”*";
P_HTM[1809]="*Catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1810]="*5. Paṭhamayodhājīvasuttaṃ**Warriors (1st)*";
P_HTM[1811]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, yodhājīvā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“Mendicants, these five warriors are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco yodhājīvo rajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati na santhambhati na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ.**Firstly, one warrior falters and founders at the mere sight of a cloud of dust. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to plunge into battle.*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the first warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ;**Furthermore, one warrior can prevail over a cloud of dust,*";
P_HTM[1817]="*api ca kho dhajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ.**but he falters and founders at the mere sight of a banner’s crest. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to plunge into battle.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1819]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the second warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ sahati dhajaggaṃ;**Furthermore, one warrior can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest,*";
P_HTM[1821]="*api ca kho ussāraṇaññeva sutvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ.**but he falters and founders at the mere sound of turmoil. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to plunge into battle.*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the third warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ;**Furthermore, one warrior can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil,*";
P_HTM[1825]="*api ca kho sampahāre haññati byāpajjati.**but he’s killed or injured when blows are struck.*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1827]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the fourth warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ, sahati sampahāraṃ.**Furthermore, one warrior can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil and being struck.*";
P_HTM[1829]="*So taṃ saṅgāmaṃ abhivijinitvā vijitasaṅgāmo tameva saṅgāmasīsaṃ ajjhāvasati.**He wins victory in battle, establishing himself as foremost in battle.*";
P_HTM[1830]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the fifth warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1832]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca yodhājīvā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**These are the five warriors found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1833]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcime yodhājīvūpamā puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā bhikkhūsu.**In the same way, these five people similar to warriors are found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1835]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu rajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**Firstly, one monk falters and founders at the mere sight of a cloud of dust. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1836]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1837]="*Kimassa rajaggasmiṃ?**What is his ‘cloud of dust’?*";
P_HTM[1838]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu suṇāti:**It’s when a monk hears:*";
P_HTM[1839]="*‘amukasmiṃ nāma gāme vā nigame vā itthī vā kumārī vā abhirūpā dassanīyā pāsādikā paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgatā’ti.**‘In such and such a village or town there’s a women or a girl who is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty.’*";
P_HTM[1840]="*So taṃ sutvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**Hearing this, he falters and founders. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1842]="*Idamassa rajaggasmiṃ.**This is his ‘cloud of dust’.*";
P_HTM[1843]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo rajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ;**I say that this person is like the warrior who falters and founders at the mere sight of a cloud of dust.*";
P_HTM[1844]="*tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1845]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the first person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1847]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sahati rajaggaṃ;**Furthermore, one monk can prevail over a cloud of dust,*";
P_HTM[1848]="*api ca kho dhajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**but at the mere sight of a banner’s crest he falters and founders. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1849]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Kimassa dhajaggasmiṃ?**What is his ‘banner’s crest’?*";
P_HTM[1851]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu na heva kho suṇāti:**It’s when a monk doesn’t hear:*";
P_HTM[1852]="*‘amukasmiṃ nāma gāme vā nigame vā itthī vā kumārī vā abhirūpā dassanīyā pāsādikā paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgatā’ti;**‘In such and such a village or town there’s a women or a girl who is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty.’*";
P_HTM[1853]="*api ca kho sāmaṃ passati itthiṃ vā kumāriṃ vā abhirūpaṃ dassanīyaṃ pāsādikaṃ paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgataṃ.**But he sees for himself a women or a girl who is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty.*";
P_HTM[1854]="*So taṃ disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**Seeing her, he falters and founders. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1855]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1856]="*Idamassa dhajaggasmiṃ.**This is his ‘banner’s crest’.*";
P_HTM[1857]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ;**I say that this person is like the warrior who can prevail over a cloud of dust,*";
P_HTM[1858]="*api ca kho dhajaggaññeva disvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ;**but he falters and founders at the mere sight of a banner’s crest.*";
P_HTM[1859]="*tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1860]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1861]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the second person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1862]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ;**Furthermore, one monk can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest,*";
P_HTM[1863]="*api ca kho ussāraṇaññeva sutvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**but he falters and founders at the mere sound of turmoil. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to enter the battle.*";
P_HTM[1864]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1865]="*Kimassa ussāraṇāya?**What is his ‘turmoil’?*";
P_HTM[1866]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ araññagataṃ vā rukkhamūlagataṃ vā suññāgāragataṃ vā mātugāmo upasaṅkamitvā ūhasati ullapati ujjagghati uppaṇḍeti.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, when a female comes up to him. She smiles, chats, laughs, and flirts with him.*";
P_HTM[1867]="*So mātugāmena ūhasiyamāno ullapiyamāno ujjagghiyamāno uppaṇḍiyamāno saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ.**He falters and founders. He doesn’t stay firm, and fails to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1869]="*Idamassa ussāraṇāya.**This is his ‘turmoil’.*";
P_HTM[1870]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ;**I say that this person is like the warrior who can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest,*";
P_HTM[1871]="*api ca kho ussāraṇaññeva sutvā saṃsīdati visīdati, na santhambhati, na sakkoti saṅgāmaṃ otarituṃ;**but he falters and founders at the mere sound of turmoil.*";
P_HTM[1872]="*tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1873]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the third person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1875]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ;**Furthermore, one monk can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil,*";
P_HTM[1876]="*api ca kho sampahāre haññati byāpajjati.**but he’s killed or injured when blows are struck.*";
P_HTM[1877]="*Kimassa sampahārasmiṃ?**What is his ‘blows are struck’?*";
P_HTM[1878]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ araññagataṃ vā rukkhamūlagataṃ vā suññāgāragataṃ vā mātugāmo upasaṅkamitvā abhinisīdati abhinipajjati ajjhottharati.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, when a female comes up to him. She sits right by him, lies down, or embraces him.*";
P_HTM[1879]="*So mātugāmena abhinisīdiyamāno abhinipajjiyamāno ajjhotthariyamāno sikkhaṃ apaccakkhāya dubbalyaṃ anāvikatvā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevati.**Without rejecting the training and declaring his inability to continue, he has sex.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*Idamassa sampahārasmiṃ.**This is his ‘blows are struck’.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ, api ca kho sampahāre haññati byāpajjati;**I say that this person is like the warrior who can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil, but is killed or injured when blows are struck.*";
P_HTM[1882]="*tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1883]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the fourth person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1885]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ, sahati sampahāraṃ, so taṃ saṅgāmaṃ abhivijinitvā vijitasaṅgāmo tameva saṅgāmasīsaṃ ajjhāvasati.**Furthermore, one monk can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil, and being struck. He wins victory in battle, establishing himself as foremost in battle.*";
P_HTM[1886]="*Kimassa saṅgāmavijayasmiṃ?**What is his ‘victory in battle’?*";
P_HTM[1887]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhuṃ araññagataṃ vā rukkhamūlagataṃ vā suññāgāragataṃ vā mātugāmo upasaṅkamitvā abhinisīdati abhinipajjati ajjhottharati.**It’s when a mendicant has gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, when a female comes up to him. She sits right by him, lies down, or embraces him.*";
P_HTM[1888]="*So mātugāmena abhinisīdiyamāno abhinipajjiyamāno ajjhotthariyamāno viniveṭhetvā vinimocetvā yena kāmaṃ pakkamati.**But he disentangles and frees himself, and goes wherever he wants.*";
P_HTM[1889]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**He frequents a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*So araññagato vā rukkhamūlagato vā suññāgāragato vā nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**Gone to a wilderness, or to the root of a tree, or to an empty hut, he sits down cross-legged, with his body straight, and establishes his mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up desire for the world, he meditates with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[1892]="*byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up ill will and malevolence, he meditates with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1893]="*thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, he meditates with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[1894]="*uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti;**Giving up restlessness and remorse, he meditates without restlessness, his mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[1895]="*vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati akathaṅkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, he meditates having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**He gives up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1897]="*vivicceva kāmehi … pe …**Then, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, he enters and remains in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[1898]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**second absorption … third absorption … fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1899]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhininnāmeti.**When his mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—he extends it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1900]="*So ‘idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ime āsavā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**He truly understands: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’. He truly understands: ‘These are defilements’ … ‘This is the origin of defilements’ … ‘This is the cessation of defilements’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements’.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati,**Knowing and seeing like this, his mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When it is freed, he knows it is freed.*";
P_HTM[1903]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**He understands: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1904]="*Idamassa saṅgāmavijayasmiṃ.**This is his ‘victory in battle’.*";
P_HTM[1905]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo sahati rajaggaṃ, sahati dhajaggaṃ, sahati ussāraṇaṃ, sahati sampahāraṃ, so taṃ saṅgāmaṃ abhivijinitvā vijitasaṅgāmo tameva saṅgāmasīsaṃ ajjhāvasati;**I say that this person is like the warrior who can prevail over a cloud of dust and a banner’s crest and turmoil and being struck. He wins victory in battle, establishing himself as foremost in battle.*";
P_HTM[1906]="*tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi.* **";
P_HTM[1907]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1908]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the fifth person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1909]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca yodhājīvūpamā puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā bhikkhūsū”ti.**These five people similar to warriors are found among the monks.”*";
P_HTM[1910]="*Pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1911]="*6. Dutiyayodhājīvasuttaṃ**Warriors (2nd)*";
P_HTM[1912]="*“Pañcime, bhikkhave, yodhājīvā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**“Mendicants, these five warriors are found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1913]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1914]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati.**Firstly, one warrior dons his sword and shield, fastens his bow and arrows, and plunges into the thick of battle.*";
P_HTM[1915]="*So tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati.**He strives and struggles in the battle,*";
P_HTM[1916]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti.**but his foes kill him and finish him off.*";
P_HTM[1917]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1918]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the first warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati.**Furthermore, one warrior dons his sword and shield, fastens his bow and arrows, and plunges into the thick of battle.*";
P_HTM[1920]="*So tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati.**He strives and struggles in the battle,*";
P_HTM[1921]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare upalikkhanti, tamenaṃ apanenti;**but his foes wound him.*";
P_HTM[1922]="*apanetvā ñātakānaṃ nenti.**He’s carried off and taken to his relatives,*";
P_HTM[1923]="*So ñātakehi nīyamāno appatvāva ñātake antarāmagge kālaṃ karoti.**but he dies on the road before he reaches them.*";
P_HTM[1924]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the second warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1926]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati.**Furthermore, one warrior dons his sword and shield, fastens his bow and arrows, and plunges into the thick of battle.*";
P_HTM[1927]="*So tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati.**He strives and struggles in the battle,*";
P_HTM[1928]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare upalikkhanti, tamenaṃ apanenti;**but his foes wound him.*";
P_HTM[1929]="*apanetvā ñātakānaṃ nenti.**He’s carried off and taken to his relatives,*";
P_HTM[1930]="*Tamenaṃ ñātakā upaṭṭhahanti paricaranti.**who nurse him and care for him.*";
P_HTM[1931]="*So ñātakehi upaṭṭhahiyamāno paricariyamāno teneva ābādhena kālaṃ karoti.**But he dies of his injuries while in their care.*";
P_HTM[1932]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1933]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the third warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1934]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati.**Furthermore, one warrior dons his sword and shield, fastens his bow and arrows, and plunges into the thick of battle.*";
P_HTM[1935]="*So tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati.**He strives and struggles in the battle,*";
P_HTM[1936]="*Tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare upalikkhanti, tamenaṃ apanenti;**but his foes wound him.*";
P_HTM[1937]="*apanetvā ñātakānaṃ nenti.**He’s carried off and taken to his relatives,*";
P_HTM[1938]="*Tamenaṃ ñātakā upaṭṭhahanti paricaranti.**who nurse him and care for him.*";
P_HTM[1939]="*So ñātakehi upaṭṭhahiyamāno paricariyamāno vuṭṭhāti tamhā ābādhā.**And while in their care, he recovers from his injuries.*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1941]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, catuttho yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the fourth warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati.**Furthermore, one warrior dons his sword and shield, fastens his bow and arrows, and plunges into the thick of battle.*";
P_HTM[1943]="*So taṃ saṅgāmaṃ abhivijinitvā vijitasaṅgāmo tameva saṅgāmasīsaṃ ajjhāvasati.**He wins victory in battle, establishing himself as foremost in battle.*";
P_HTM[1944]="*Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco yodhājīvo hoti.**Some warriors are like that.*";
P_HTM[1945]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, pañcamo yodhājīvo santo saṃvijjamāno lokasmiṃ.**This is the fifth warrior found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1946]="*Ime kho, bhikkhave, pañca yodhājīvā santo saṃvijjamānā lokasmiṃ.**These are the five warriors found in the world.*";
P_HTM[1947]="*Evamevaṃ kho, bhikkhave, pañcime yodhājīvūpamā puggalā santo saṃvijjamānā bhikkhūsu.**In the same way, these five people similar to warriors are found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1949]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññataraṃ gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā upanissāya viharati.**Firstly, a mendicant lives supported by a town or village.*";
P_HTM[1950]="*So pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya tameva gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya pavisati arakkhiteneva kāyena arakkhitāya vācāya arakkhitena cittena anupaṭṭhitāya satiyā asaṃvutehi indriyehi.**He robes up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, enters a village or town for alms without guarding body, speech, and mind, without establishing mindfulness, and without restraining the sense faculties.*";
P_HTM[1951]="*So tattha passati mātugāmaṃ dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā.**There he sees a female scantily clad, with revealing clothes.*";
P_HTM[1952]="*Tassa taṃ mātugāmaṃ disvā dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā rāgo cittaṃ anuddhaṃseti.**Lust infects his mind,*";
P_HTM[1953]="*So rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena sikkhaṃ apaccakkhāya dubbalyaṃ anāvikatvā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevati.**and, without rejecting the training and declaring his inability to continue, he has sex.*";
P_HTM[1954]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati, so tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare hananti pariyāpādenti; tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi. Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**I say that this person is like the warrior who is killed and finished off by his foes. Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1955]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the first person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññataraṃ gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā upanissāya viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives supported by a town or village.*";
P_HTM[1957]="*So pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya tameva gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya pavisati arakkhiteneva kāyena arakkhitāya vācāya arakkhitena cittena anupaṭṭhitāya satiyā asaṃvutehi indriyehi.**He robes up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, enters a village or town for alms without guarding body, speech, and mind, without establishing mindfulness, and without restraining the sense faculties.*";
P_HTM[1958]="*So tattha passati mātugāmaṃ dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā.**There he sees a female scantily clad, with revealing clothes.*";
P_HTM[1959]="*Tassa taṃ mātugāmaṃ disvā dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā rāgo cittaṃ anuddhaṃseti.**Lust infects his mind,*";
P_HTM[1960]="*So rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena pariḍayhateva kāyena pariḍayhati cetasā.**and his body and mind burn with it.*";
P_HTM[1961]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**He thinks:*";
P_HTM[1962]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ ārāmaṃ gantvā bhikkhūnaṃ āroceyyaṃ—**‘Why don’t I go to the monastery and tell the monks:*";
P_HTM[1963]="*rāgapariyuṭṭhitomhi, āvuso, rāgapareto, na sakkomi brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ;**“Reverends, I am overcome with lust, mired in lust. I am unable to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattissāmī’ti.**I declare my inability to continue training. I reject it and will return to a lesser life.”’*";
P_HTM[1965]="*So ārāmaṃ gacchanto appatvāva ārāmaṃ antarāmagge sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**But while traveling on the road, before he reaches the monastery he declares his inability to continue training. He rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati, so tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare upalikkhanti, tamenaṃ apanenti; apanetvā ñātakānaṃ nenti. So ñātakehi nīyamāno appatvāva ñātake antarāmagge kālaṃ karoti; tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi. Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**I say that this person is like the warrior who is taken to his relatives for care, but he dies on the road before he reaches them. Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1967]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the second person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[1968]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññataraṃ gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā upanissāya viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives supported by a town or village.*";
P_HTM[1969]="*So pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya tameva gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya pavisati arakkhiteneva kāyena arakkhitāya vācāya arakkhitena cittena anupaṭṭhitāya satiyā asaṃvutehi indriyehi.**He robes up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, enters a village or town for alms without guarding body, speech, and mind, without establishing mindfulness, and without restraining the sense faculties.*";
P_HTM[1970]="*So tattha passati mātugāmaṃ dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā.**There he sees a female scantily clad, with revealing clothes.*";
P_HTM[1971]="*Tassa taṃ mātugāmaṃ disvā dunnivatthaṃ vā duppārutaṃ vā rāgo cittaṃ anuddhaṃseti.**Lust infects his mind,*";
P_HTM[1972]="*So rāgānuddhaṃsitena cittena pariḍayhateva kāyena pariḍayhati cetasā.**and his body and mind burn with it.*";
P_HTM[1973]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**He thinks:*";
P_HTM[1974]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ ārāmaṃ gantvā bhikkhūnaṃ āroceyyaṃ—**‘Why don’t I go to the monastery and tell the monks:*";
P_HTM[1975]="*rāgapariyuṭṭhitomhi, āvuso, rāgapareto, na sakkomi brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ;**“Reverends, I am overcome with lust, mired in lust. I am unable to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1976]="*sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattissāmī’ti.**I declare my inability to continue training. I reject it and will return to a lesser life.”’*";
P_HTM[1977]="*So ārāmaṃ gantvā bhikkhūnaṃ āroceti:**He goes to the monastery and tells the monks:*";
P_HTM[1978]="*‘rāgapariyuṭṭhitomhi, āvuso, rāgapareto, na sakkomi brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ;**‘Reverends, I am overcome with lust, mired in lust. I am unable to keep up the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1979]="*sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattissāmī’ti.**I declare my inability to continue training. I reject it and will return to a lesser life.’*";
P_HTM[1980]="*Tamenaṃ sabrahmacārī ovadanti anusāsanti:**His spiritual companions advise and instruct him:*";
P_HTM[1981]="*‘appassādā, āvuso, kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**‘Reverend, the Buddha says that sensual pleasures give little gratification and much suffering and distress, and they are all the more full of drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[1982]="*Aṭṭhikaṅkalūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**With the similes of a skeleton …*";
P_HTM[1983]="*Maṃsapesūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a lump of meat …*";
P_HTM[1984]="*Tiṇukkūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a grass torch …*";
P_HTM[1985]="*Aṅgārakāsūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a pit of glowing coals …*";
P_HTM[1986]="*Supinakūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a dream …*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Yācitakūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**borrowed goods …*";
P_HTM[1988]="*Rukkhaphalūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**fruit on a tree …*";
P_HTM[1989]="*Asisūnūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a butcher’s knife and chopping block …*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Sattisūlūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a staking sword …*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Sappasirūpamā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo.**a snake’s head, the Buddha says that sensual pleasures give little gratification and much suffering and distress, and they are all the more full of drawbacks.*";
P_HTM[1992]="*Abhiramatāyasmā brahmacariye;**Be happy with the spiritual life.*";
P_HTM[1993]="*māyasmā sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattī’ti.**Venerable, please don’t declare your inability to continue training, reject it and return to a lesser life.’*";
P_HTM[1994]="*So sabrahmacārīhi evaṃ ovadiyamāno evaṃ anusāsiyamāno evamāha:**When thus advised and instructed by his spiritual companions, he says:*";
P_HTM[1995]="*‘kiñcāpi, āvuso, appassādā kāmā vuttā bhagavatā bahudukkhā bahupāyāsā, ādīnavo ettha bhiyyo;**‘Reverends, even though the Buddha says that sensual pleasures give little gratification and much suffering and distress, and they are all the more full of drawbacks,*";
P_HTM[1996]="*atha kho nevāhaṃ sakkomi brahmacariyaṃ sandhāretuṃ, sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattissāmī’ti.**I am unable to keep up the spiritual life. I declare my inability to continue training. I reject it and will return to a lesser life.’*";
P_HTM[1997]="*So sikkhādubbalyaṃ āvikatvā sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattati.**Declaring his inability to continue training, he rejects it and returns to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[1998]="*Seyyathāpi so, bhikkhave, yodhājīvo asicammaṃ gahetvā dhanukalāpaṃ sannayhitvā viyūḷhaṃ saṅgāmaṃ otarati, so tasmiṃ saṅgāme ussahati vāyamati, tamenaṃ ussahantaṃ vāyamantaṃ pare upalikkhanti, tamenaṃ apanenti; apanetvā ñātakānaṃ nenti, tamenaṃ ñātakā upaṭṭhahanti paricaranti. So ñātakehi upaṭṭhahiyamāno paricariyamāno teneva ābādhena kālaṃ karoti; tathūpamāhaṃ, bhikkhave, imaṃ puggalaṃ vadāmi. Evarūpopi, bhikkhave, idhekacco puggalo hoti.**I say that this person is like the warrior who dies of his injuries while in the care of his relatives. Some people are like that.*";
P_HTM[1999]="*Ayaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyo yodhājīvūpamo puggalo santo saṃvijjamāno bhikkhūsu.**This is the third person similar to a warrior found among the monks.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, bhikkhu aññataraṃ gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā upanissāya viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives supported by a town or village.*";
